inclair]]\n| Anti-Socialist/Liberal\n| [[Division of Moreton|Moreton]]\n| Qld\n| 1906\n|-\n| [[Bruce Smith (Australian politician)|Bruce Smith]]\n| Anti-Socialist/Liberal\n| [[Division of Parkes (1901-69)|Parkes]]\n| NSW\n| 1901\n|-\n| [[William Spence]]\n| Labor\n| [[Division of Darling|Darling]]\n| NSW\n| 1901\n|-\n| [[David Storrer]] {{ref|david_storrer}}\n| Protectionist/Independent\n| [[Division of Bass|Bass]]\n| Tas\n| 1901\n|-\n| [[Josiah Thomas]]\n| Labor\n| [[Division of Barrier|Barrier]]\n| NSW\n| 1901\n|-\n| [[Dugald Thomson]] *\n| Anti-Socialist/Liberal\n| [[Division of North Sydney|North Sydney]]\n| NSW\n| 1901\n|-\n| [[John Thomson (Australian politician)|John Thomson]]\n| Protectionist/Liberal\n| [[Division of Cowper|Cowper]]\n| NSW\n| 1906\n|-\n| [[Frank Tudor]]\n| Labor\n| [[Division of Yarra|Yarra]]\n| Vic\n| 1901\n|-\n| [[David Watkins (Australian politician)|David Watkins]]\n| Labor\n| [[Division of Newcastle|Newcastle]]\n| NSW\n| 1901\n|-\n| Hon [[Chris Watson]]\n| Labor\n| [[Division of South Sydney|South Sydney]]\n| NSW\n| 1901 {{ref|chris_watson}}\n|-\n| [[William Webster (Australian politician)|William Webster]]\n| Labor\n| [[Division of Gwydir|Gwydir]]\n| NSW\n| 1903\n|-\n| [[William Wilks (Australian politician)|William Wilks]]\n| Anti-Socialist/Liberal\n| [[Division of Dalley|Dalley]]\n| NSW\n| 1901\n|-\n| [[Henry Willis (Australian politician)|Henry Willis]]\n| Anti-Socialist/Liberal\n| [[Division of Robertson|Robertson]]\n| NSW\n| 1901\n|-\n| Dr [[Gratton Wilson]]\n| Anti-Socialist/Liberal\n| [[Division of Corangamite|Corangamite]]\n| Vic\n| 1903\n|-\n| [[George Wise (Australian politician)|George Wise]] {{ref|george_wise}}\n| Protectionist/Independent\n| [[Division of Gippsland|Gippsland]]\n| Vic\n| 1906\n|-\n| [[Agar Wynne]]\n| Independent/Liberal\n| [[Division of Balaclava|Balaclava]]\n| Vic\n| 1906\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n\n<nowiki>*</nowiki> These candidates were elected unopposed.<br>\n\u2020 These Divisions were created at the 1906 redistribution.\n\n# {{note|anti-socialist}} The Anti-Socialists were known as the [[Free Trade Party]] before the 1906 election. In 1909, the Anti-Socialists, the Protectionists and the Western Australia Party merged to form the [[Commonwealth Liberal Party]].\n# {{note|labor}} In 1908 the Labor Party became officially known as the [[Australian Labour Party]] (ALP).\n# {{note|thomas_brown}} Thomas Brown was first elected in 1901 to the [[Division of Canobolas]], which was abolished at the 1906 redistribution.\n# {{note|john_chanter}} John Chanter rejected the Commonwealth Liberal Party merger and joined the ALP.\n# {{note|protectionist}} There was no national [[Protectionist Party]] organisation in 1906. Members categorised as \"Protectionist\" were those who accepted the leadership of Alfred Deakin.\n# {{note|george_fairbairn}} George Fairbairn was endorsed by the Anti-Socialists, but campaigned as an independent Protectionist. He did not sit with the Anti-Socialists.\n# {{note|wap}} The two Western Australia Party members were considered to be independent conservatives.\n# {{note|james_fowler}} James Fowler defected from the ALP to the Commonwealth Liberal Party at the time of the merger.\n# {{note|frederick_holder}} Frederick Holder died in 1909. He was replaced at a by-election on 28 August 1909 by [[Richard Foster (Australia)|Richard Foster]] a Commonwealth Liberal Party candidate.\n# {{note|charles_kingston}} Charles Kingston died in 1908. He was replaced at a by-election on 13 June 1908 by [[Ernest Roberts (Australian politician)|Ernest Roberts]], a Labor candidate.\n# {{note|william_lyne}} Sir William Lyne rejected the Commonwealth Liberal Party merger and became an independent.\n# {{note|samuel_mauger}} Samuel Mauger was first elected in 1901 to the [[Division of Melbourne Ports]], which was abolished at the 1906 redistribution.\n# {{note|albert_palmer}} In 1907 Albert Palmer's election was declared void. He was re-elected in a by-election on 10 July 1907.\n# {{note|john_quick}} John Quick was endorsed by the Anti-Socialists, but sat as an independent.\n# {{note|sydney_sampson}} Sydney Sampson was endorsed by the Anti-Socialists, but sat as an independent.\n# {{note|david_storrer}} David Storrer rejected the Commonwealth Liberal Party merger and became an independent.\n# {{note|chris_watson}} Chris Watson was first elected in 1901 to the [[Division of Bland]], which was abolished at the 1906 redistribution.\n# {{note|george_wise}} George Wise rejected the Commonwealth Liberal Party merger and became an independent.\n\n{{Members of the Parliament of Australia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Members of the Australian House of Representatives, 1906-1910}}\n[[Category:Members of Australian parliaments by term]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2011}}\nThis is a list of the members of the [[Australian House of Representatives]] in the '''Third Australian Parliament''', which was elected on 12 December 1906.\n\nIn 1909 the [[Anti-Socialist Party]] (previously Free Trade) and most of the [[Protectionist Party]] merged to become the [[Commonwealth Liberal Party]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! '''Member'''\n! '''Party'''\n! '''Electorate'''\n! '''State'''\n! '''First elected'''\n|-\n| [[Edward Archer (politician)|Edward Archer]]\n| [[Anti-Socialist Party|Anti-Socialist]]/[[Commonwealth Liberal Party|Liberal]] {{ref|anti-socialist}}\n| [[Division of Capricornia|Capricornia]]\n| Qld\n| 1906\n|-\n| [[Llewellyn Atkinson]]\n| Anti-Socialist/Liberal\n| [[Division of Wilmot|Wilmot]]\n| Tas\n| 1906\n|-\n| [[Frederick Bamford]]\n| [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] {{ref|labor}}\n| [[Division of Herbert|Herbert]]\n| Qld\n| 1901\n|-\n| [[Lee Batchelor]] *\n| Labor\n| [[Division of Boothby|Boothby]]\n| SA\n| 1901\n|-\n| [[Eric Bowden]]\n| Anti-Socialist/Liberal\n| [[Division of Nepean|Nepean]] \u2020\n| NSW\n| 1906\n|-\n| [[Joseph Tilley Brown|Joseph Brown]]\n| Anti-Socialist/Liberal\n| [[Division of Indi|Indi]]\n| Vic\n| 1906\n|-\n| Hon [[Thomas Brown (Australian federal politician)|Thomas Brown]]\n| Labor\n| [[Division of Calare|Calare]] \u2020\n| NSW\n| 1901 {{ref|thomas_brown}}\n|-\n| [[Ernest Carr]]\n| Labor\n| [[Division of Macquarie|Macquarie]]\n| NSW\n| 1906\n|-\n| [[James Catts]]\n| Labor\n| [[Division of Cook (1906\u201355)|Cook]] \u2020\n| NSW\n| 1906\n|-\n| Hon [[John Chanter]] {{ref|john_chanter}}\n| [[Protectionist Party|Protectionist]]/Labor {{ref|protectionist}}\n| [[Division of Riverina|Riverina]]\n| NSW\n| 1904 ([[by-election]])\n|-\n| [[Austin Chapman]]\n| Protectionist/Liberal\n| [[Division of Eden-Monaro|Eden-Monaro]]\n| NSW\n| 1901\n|-\n| [[James Cook (Australian politician)|James Cook]]\n| Protectionist/Liberal\n| [[Division of Bourke|Bourke]]\n| Vic\n| 1901\n|-\n| Hon [[Joseph Cook]] *\n| Anti-Socialist/Liberal\n| [[Division of Parramatta|Parramatta]]\n| NSW\n| 1901\n|-\n| Hon [[Jabez Coon]]\n| Protectionist/Liberal\n| [[Division of Batman|Batman]] \u2020\n| Vic\n| 1906\n|-\n| [[Richard Crouch]]\n| Protectionist/Liberal\n| [[Division of Corio|Corio]]\n| Vic\n| 1901\n|-\n| Hon [[Alfred Deakin]]\n| Protectionist/Liberal\n| [[Division of Ballarat|Ballarat]]\n| Vic\n| 1901\n|-\n| Hon [[Richard Edwards (Australian politician)|Richard Edwards]]\n| Anti-Socialist/Liberal\n| [[Division of Oxley (1901-34)|Oxley]]\n| Qld\n| 1901\n|-\n| [[Thomas Ewing (Australian politician)|Thomas Ewing]]\n| Protectionist/Liberal\n| [[Division of Richmond|Richmond]]\n| NSW\n| 1901\n|-\n| [[George Fairbairn (politician)|George Fairbairn]] {{ref|george_fairbairn}}\n| Independent/Liberal\n| [[Division of Fawkner|Fawkner]] \u2020\n| Vic\n| 1906\n|-\n| [[Andrew Fisher]]\n| Labor\n| [[Division of Wide Bay|Wide Bay]]\n| Qld\n| 1901\n|-\n| Rt Hon Sir [[John Forrest]]\n| [[Western Australian Party|Western Australian]]/Liberal {{ref|wap}}\n| [[Division of Swan|Swan]]\n| WA