{"title_page": "Tarring and feathering", "text_new": "{{short description|Form of public torture and humiliation}}\n{{multiple image\n| image1=John Meintz, punished during World War I - NARA - 283633 - restored.jpg\n| alt1=Tarring and feathering victim front.\n| image2=John Meintz, punished during World War I - NARA - 283634.jpg \n| alt2=Tarring and feathering victim back as a form of humiliation\n| footer=[[German-American]] farmer [[John Meints]] of [[Luverne, Minnesota]] was tarred and feathered in August 1918 during [[World War I]] for allegedly not supporting war bond drives.<ref>{{cite web|last=Welter |first=Ben |url=http://www.startribune.com/nov-16-1919-tarred-and-feathered/70155507/ |title=Nov. 16, 1919: Tarred and feathered |publisher=StarTribune.com |date=2015-11-18 |accessdate=2017-09-19}}</ref> Minnesota historians have cited this incident as an example of [[nativism (politics)|nativism]] and [[anti-German sentiment]] in Minnesota during [[World War I]].<ref name=MNopedia>{{Cite encyclopedia |title=Anti-German Nativism, 1917\u20131919|encyclopedia=MNopedia |publisher=[[Minnesota Historical Society]] |url=https://www.mnopedia.org/anti-german-nativism-1917-1919 |last=Alam |first=Ehsan}}{{MNopedia}}</ref>\n| width=200\n}}\n\n'''Tarring and feathering''' is a form of [[Public humiliation|public torture and humiliation]] used to enforce unofficial justice or revenge. It was used in [[early modern Europe|feudal Europe]] and [[European colonialism|its colonies]] in the [[early modern period]], as well as the early [[American frontier]], mostly as a type of [[Lynching|mob vengeance]].\n\nThe victim would be stripped naked, or stripped to the waist. [[Wood tar]] (sometimes hot) was then either poured or painted onto the person while they were immobilized. Then the victim either had [[feathers]] thrown on them or was rolled around on a pile of feathers so that they stuck to the tar.\n\nThe image of a tarred-and-feathered outlaw remains a [[metaphor]] for severe public criticism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/tar%20and%20feather |title=Tar and Feather. The American Heritage Dictionary of Idioms by Christine Ammer. Houghton Mifflin Company |publisher=Dictionary.reference.com |date=1997-05-26 |accessdate=2012-03-07}}\n{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreedictionary.com/tars |title=Tars. The Free Online Dictionary |publisher=Thefreedictionary.com |date= |accessdate=2012-03-07}} \"To criticize severely and devastatingly; excoriate.\" (\"[[:wikt:excoriate|to excoriate]]\" [i.e. \"to flay\"] being itself a similar type of metaphor).</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe earliest mention of the punishment appears in orders that [[Richard I of England]] issued to his navy on starting for the [[Holy Land]] in 1189. \"Concerning the lawes and ordinances appointed by King Richard for his navie the forme thereof was this ... item, a thiefe or felon that hath stolen, being lawfully convicted, shal have his head shorne, and boyling pitch poured upon his head, and feathers or downe strawed upon the same whereby he may be knowen, and so at the first landing-place they shall come to, there to be cast up\" (transcript of original statute in ''[[Richard Hakluyt|Hakluyt]]'s Voyages'', ii. 21).{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}<ref>[http://avalon.law.yale.edu/medieval/richard.asp Tha Avalon Project documents] Accessed on 23rd June 2015</ref>\n\nA later instance of this penalty appears in ''[[Notes and Queries]]'' (series 4, vol. v), which quotes [[James Howell]] writing in Madrid in 1623 of the \"boisterous [[Bishop of Halberstadt]] ... having taken a place where there were two monasteries of nuns and friars, he caused divers feather beds to be ripped, and all the feathers thrown into a great hall, whither the nuns and friars were thrust naked with their bodies oiled and pitched and to tumble among these feathers, which makes them here (Madrid) presage him an ill-death.\"{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}} (The Bishop was apparently [[Christian the Younger of Brunswick]].)\n\nIn 1696, a London [[bailiff]] attempted to serve process on a [[debtor]] who had taken refuge within the precincts of the [[Liberties of the Savoy|Savoy]]. The bailiff was tarred and feathered and taken in a wheelbarrow to [[Strand, London|the Strand]], where he was tied to a [[maypole]] that stood by what is now [[Somerset House]] as an improvised [[pillory]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\n[[File:Philip Dawe (attributed), The Bostonians Paying the Excise-man, or Tarring and Feathering (1774) - 02.jpg|thumb|''The Bostonians Paying the Excise-Man'', 1774 British [[propaganda]] print that depicts the tarring and feathering of [[Boston]] Commissioner of Customs [[John Malcolm (Loyalist)|John Malcolm]]. This was the second time that Malcolm had been tarred and feathered.]]\n[[File:The alternative of Williamsburg, 1775 - NARA - 532891.tif|thumb|\"The Alternative of Williamsburg\" A 1775 British print showing loyalists being forced to sign either the associations or Resolutions drawn up in Williamsburg on August 1774. The note on gibbet at upper right reads: \"A Cure for the Refractory\"\u2014a bagful of feathers and a cask of tar. Phillip Dawe print]]\n\n===Coming of The American War of Independence===\nIn 1766, Captain William Smith was tarred, feathered, and dumped into the harbor of [[Norfolk, Virginia]] by a mob that included the town's mayor. A vessel picked him out of the water just as his strength was giving out. He survived and was later quoted as saying that they \"dawbed my body and face all over with tar and afterwards threw feathers on me.\" Smith was suspected of informing on smugglers to the British customs agents, as was the case with most other tar-and-feathers victims in the following decade.<ref>{{cite book|author=\"Letters of Governor Francis Fauquier\"|title= ''The William and Mary Quarterly''|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vikjAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA167|volume=21|year=1912|pages=166\u201367}}</ref>\n\nThe practice appeared in [[Salem, Massachusetts|Salem]], [[Massachusetts]] in 1767, when mobs attacked low-level employees of the customs service with tar and feathers. In October 1769, a mob in Boston attacked a customs service sailor the same way, and a few similar attacks followed through 1774. The tarring and feathering of Customs Commissioner [[John Malcolm (Loyalist)|John Malcolm]] received particular attention in 1774. Such acts associated the punishment with the [[Patriot (American Revolution)|Patriot]] side of the [[American Revolution]]. An exception occurred in March 1775 when a British regiment inflicted the same treatment on Thomas Ditson, a [[Billerica, Massachusetts]] man who attempted to buy a musket from one of the regiment's soldiers. There is no known case of a person dying from being tarred and feathered in this period. During the [[Whiskey Rebellion]], local farmers inflicted the punishment on federal tax agents.<ref>Benjamin H. Irvin, \"Tar, feathers, and the enemies of American liberties, 1768-1776.\" ''New England Quarterly'' (2003): 197-238. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/1559903 in JSTOR]</ref>\n\n===19th century===\nBeginning on September 11, 1791, western Pennsylvania farmers rebelled against the federal government's taxation on western Pennsylvania whiskey distillers during the [[Whiskey Rebellion]]. Their first victim was reportedly a recently appointed tax collector named Robert Johnson. He was tarred and feathered by a disguised gang in [[Washington County, Pennsylvania|Washington County]]. Other officials who attempted to serve court warrants on Johnson's attackers were whipped, tarred, and feathered. Because of these and other violent attacks, the tax went uncollected in 1791 and early 1792. The attackers modeled their actions on the protests of the [[American Revolution]].<ref>{{cite book | last = Slaughter | first = Thomas P. | title = The Whiskey Rebellion: Frontier Epilogue to the American Revolution | url = https://archive.org/details/whiskeyrebellion00slau | url-access = registration | publisher = Oxford University Press | date = 1986 | isbn = 0195051912 }} pages 113-114</ref>\n\n[[Joseph Smith]], founder of the [[Latter Day Saint movement]], was dragged from his home during the night of March 24, 1832 by a group of men who stripped and beat him before tarring and feathering him. His wife and infant child were knocked from their bed by the attackers and were forced from the home and threatened. (The infant died several days later from exposure.) Smith was left for dead, but limped back to the home of friends. They spent much of the night scraping the tar from his body, leaving his skin raw and bloody. The following day, Smith spoke at a church devotional meeting and was reported to have been covered with raw wounds and still weak from the attack.<ref>See [[Life of Joseph Smith from 1831 to 1834#Life in Kirtland, Ohio]]</ref>{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nIn 1851, a [[Know-Nothing]] mob in [[Ellsworth, Maine]] tarred and feathered Swiss-born [[Jesuit]] priest Father [[John Bapst]] in the midst of a local controversy over religious education in grammar schools. Bapst fled Ellsworth to settle in nearby [[Bangor, Maine]], where there was a large [[Irish-Catholic]] community, and a local high school there is named for him.<ref>{{CathEncy|id=02258a|title=John Bapst|first=Thomas|last=Campbell|accessdate=December 17, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===20th century===\n[[File:The tarring and feathering of Mrs Lowry.png|thumb|Image accompanying story of \"Female Whitecaps Chastise Woman\" from ''[[Ada Evening News]]'' November 27, 1906. The article describes an incident in East Sandy, Pennsylvania where four married women tarred and feathered Mrs. Hattie Lowry.]]\nTarring and feathering was not restricted to men. The November 27, 1906 Ada, Oklahoma ''Evening News'' reports that a vigilance committee consisting of four young married women from East Sandy, Pennsylvania corrected the alleged evil conduct of their neighbor Mrs. Hattie Lowry in [[Whitecapping|whitecap style]]. One of the women was a sister-in-law of the victim. The women appeared at Mrs. Lowry's home in open day and announced that she had not heeded the spokeswoman and leader. Two women held Mrs. Lowry to the floor while the other two smeared her face with stove polish until it was completely covered. They then poured thick molasses upon her head and emptied the contents of a feather pillow over the molasses. The women then marched the victim to a railroad camp, tied by the wrists, where two hundred workmen stopped work to watch the spectacle. After parading Mrs. Lowry through the camp, the women tied her to a large box where she remained until a man released her. Three of the women involved were arrested, pleaded guilty and each paid a $10.00 fine.<ref>[http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84026853/1906-11-21/ed-1/seq-7/#date1=11%2F01%2F1906&index=2&rows=20&searchType=advanced&language=&sequence=0&words=Hattie+Lowry&proxdistance=5&date2=11%2F31%2F1906&ortext=&proxtext=Hattie+Lowry&phrasetext=&andtext=&dateFilterType=range&page=1 The Abbeville press and banner., November 21, 1906, Image 7]</ref>\n\nThere were several examples of tarring and feathering of African Americans in the lead-up to [[World War I]] in [[Vicksburg, Mississippi]].<ref name=harris/> According to William Harris, this was a relatively rare form of mob punishment to Republican African-Americans in the post-bellum U.S. South, as its goal was typically pain and humiliation rather than death.<ref name=harris>Harris, William J. \"Etiquette, Lynching, and Racial Boundaries in Southern History: A Mississippi Example\". ''[[The American Historical Review]]''. Vol. 100, No. 2 (Apr., 1995), pp. 387\u2013410</ref>\n\nDuring World War I, [[anti-German sentiment]] was widespread in the United States and many German-Americans were attacked. For example, in August 1918 a German-American farmer, John Meints of Luverne, Minnesota, was captured by a group of men, taken to the nearby South Dakota border and tarred and feathered \u2013 for allegedly not supporting [[war bond]]s. Meints sued his assailants and lost, but on appeal to a federal court he won, and  in 1922 settled out of court for $6,000.<ref name=\"startribune.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/blogs/70155507.html |title=Nov. 16, 1919: Tarred and feathered |publisher=StarTribune.com |date= |accessdate=2012-03-07}}</ref> In March 1922, a German-born Catholic priest in [[Slaton, Texas]], Joseph M. Keller, who had been harassed by local residents during World War I due to his ethnicity, was accused of breaking the [[Seal of the Confessional (Catholic Church)|seal of confession]] and tarred and feathered. Thereafter Keller served a Catholic parish in Milwaukee, Wisconsin.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bills|first1=E. R.|title=Texas Obscurities: Stories of the Peculiar, Exceptional and Nefarious|date=October 29, 2013|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|location=\"Father Keller\"|isbn=9781625847652|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Vvx2CQAAQBAJ&pg=PT51&dq=Keller}}</ref>\n\nFuture Australian senator [[Fred Katz]] \u2013 a socialist and anti-conscriptionist of German parentage \u2013 was publicly tarred and feathered outside his office in Melbourne in December 1915.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://biography.senate.gov.au/katz-frederick-carl/|title=Katz, Frederick Carl (1877\u20131960)|work=The Biographical Dictionary of the Australian Senate|first=Frank|last=Bongiorno|year=2004|publisher=Melbourne University Press}}</ref> A week before the [[1919 Australian federal election]], former [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] MP [[John McDougall (Australian politician, born 1867)|John McDougall]] was kidnapped by a group of about 20 ex-soldiers in [[Ararat, Victoria]], and subsequently tarred and feathered before being dumped in the town's streets. He had earlier been revealed as the author of an anti-war poem that was perceived as insulting Australia's soldiers. Six men were charged with inflicting [[grievous bodily harm]], but pled down to common assault and were fined \u00a35 each. Many newspapers supported their actions.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Terry|last=King|title=The Tarring and Feathering of J. K. McDougall: 'Dirty Tricks' in the 1919 Federal Election|journal=Labour History|volume=45|year=1983|pages=54\u201367}}</ref>\n\nA group of black-robed Knights of Liberty (a faction of the [[KKK]]) tarred and feathered seventeen members of the [[Industrial Workers of the World]] (IWW) in Oklahoma in 1917, during an incident known as the [[Tulsa Outrage]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Chapman |first=Lee Roy |url=http://thislandpress.com/09/01/2011/tate-brady-battle-greenwood/ |title=The Nightmare of Dreamland This Land |date=September 2011 |accessdate=September 1, 2011}}</ref> In the 1920s, vigilantes were opposed to [[Industrial Workers of the World|IWW]] organizers at California's harbor of [[San Pedro, Los Angeles, California|San Pedro]]. They kidnapped at least one organizer, subjected him to tarring and feathering, and left him in a remote location.{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\nThe Wednesday, May 28, 1930 edition of the ''Miami Daily News-Record'' contains on its front page the arrests of five brothers (Isaac, Newton, Henry, Gordon and Charles Starns) from Louisiana accused of tarring and feathering Dr. S. L. Newsome, who was a prominent dentist. This was in retaliation for the dentist having an affair with one of the brother's wives.{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\nSimilar tactics were also used by the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army]] (IRA) during the early years of [[the Troubles]]. Many of the victims were women accused of sexual relationships with policemen or British soldiers.<ref>{{cite news |date=February 13, 2011 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2011/feb/13/paul-theroux-this-was-england |newspaper=The Observer |location=London |title=This was England |first=Paul |last=Theroux}}</ref> \nIn August 2007, [[Ulster loyalism|loyalist]] groups in Northern Ireland were linked to the tarring and feathering of an individual accused of drug-dealing.<ref>{{cite news |date=August 28, 2007 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/6966493.stm |publisher=BBC News Online |location=London |title=Belfast man tarred and feathered |accessdate=August 28, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Riding a rail|Riding the rail]]\n* [[Tarring and feathering in popular culture]]\n* [[:Category:Tarring and feathering in the United States|Tarring and feathering in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n'''Attribution'''\n*{{EB1911|wstitle=Tarring and Feathering|volume=26}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Tarring and feathering}}\n*[http://www.yale.edu/lawweb/avalon/medieval/richard.htm Text of law of Richard I]\n*\"[http://www.straightdope.com/classics/a3_020.html Has anyone actually ever been tarred and feathered?]\" at [[Straight Dope]]\n*Richard L. Bushman, ''[[Joseph Smith: Rough Stone Rolling]]''., Alfred Knopf, 2005, {{ISBN|1-4000-4270-4}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tarring And Feathering}}\n[[Category:Corporal punishments]]\n[[Category:Feathers]]\n[[Category:Vigilantism]]\n[[Category:Vigilantism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Physical torture techniques]]\n[[Category:Whiskey Rebellion]]\n[[Category:Tarring and feathering in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Form of public torture and humiliation}}\n{{multiple image\n| image1=John Meintz, punished during World War I - NARA - 283633 - restored.jpg\n| alt1=Tarring and feathering victim front.\n| image2=John Meintz, punished during World War I - NARA - 283634.jpg \n| alt2=Tarring and feathering victim back as a form of humiliation\n| footer=[[German-American]] farmer [[John Meints]] of [[Luverne, Minnesota]] was tarred and feathered in August 1918 during [[World War I]] for allegedly not supporting war bond drives.<ref>{{cite web|last=Welter |first=Ben |url=http://www.startribune.com/nov-16-1919-tarred-and-feathered/70155507/ |title=Nov. 16, 1919: Tarred and feathered |publisher=StarTribune.com |date=2015-11-18 |accessdate=2017-09-19}}</ref> Minnesota historians have cited this incident as an example of [[nativism (politics)|nativism]] and [[anti-German sentiment]] in Minnesota during [[World War I]].<ref name=MNopedia>{{Cite encyclopedia |title=Anti-German Nativism, 1917\u20131919|encyclopedia=MNopedia |publisher=[[Minnesota Historical Society]] |url=https://www.mnopedia.org/anti-german-nativism-1917-1919 |last=Alam |first=Ehsan}}{{MNopedia}}</ref>\n| width=200\n}}\n\n'''Tarring and feathering''' is a form of [[Public humiliation|public torture and humiliation]] used to enforce unofficial justice or revenge. It was used in [[early modern Europe|feudal Europe]] and [[European colonialism|its colonies]] in the [[early modern period]], as well as the early [[American frontier]], mostly as a type of [[Lynching|mob vengeance]].\n\nThe victim would be stripped naked, or stripped to the waist. [[Wood tar]] (sometimes hot) was then either poured or painted onto the person while they were immobilized. Then the victim either had [[feathers]] thrown on them or was rolled around on a pile of feathers so that they stuck to the tar.\n\nThe image of a tarred-and-feathered outlaw remains a [[metaphor]] for severe public criticism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/tar%20and%20feather |title=Tar and Feather. The American Heritage Dictionary of Idioms by Christine Ammer. Houghton Mifflin Company |publisher=Dictionary.reference.com |date=1997-05-26 |accessdate=2012-03-07}}\n{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreedictionary.com/tars |title=Tars. The Free Online Dictionary |publisher=Thefreedictionary.com |date= |accessdate=2012-03-07}} \"To criticize severely and devastatingly; excoriate.\" (\"[[:wikt:excoriate|to excoriate]]\" [i.e. \"to flay\"] being itself a similar type of metaphor).</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe earliest mention of the punishment appears in orders that [[Richard I of England]] issued to his navy on starting for the [[Holy Land]] in 1189. \"Concerning the lawes and ordinances appointed by King Richard for his navie the forme thereof was this ... item, a thiefe or felon that hath stolen, being lawfully convicted, shal have his head shorne, and boyling pitch poured upon his head, and feathers or downe strawed upon the same whereby he may be knowen, and so at the first landing-place they shall come to, there to be cast up\" (transcript of original statute in ''[[Richard Hakluyt|Hakluyt]]'s Voyages'', ii. 21).{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}<ref>[http://avalon.law.yale.edu/medieval/richard.asp Tha Avalon Project documents] Accessed on 23rd June 2015</ref>\n\nA later instance of this penalty appears in ''[[Notes and Queries]]'' (series 4, vol. v), which quotes [[James Howell]] writing in Madrid in 1623 of the \"boisterous [[Bishop of Halberstadt]] ... having taken a place where there were two monasteries of nuns and friars, he caused divers feather beds to be ripped, and all the feathers thrown into a great hall, whither the nuns and friars were thrust naked with their bodies oiled and pitched and to tumble among these feathers, which makes them here (Madrid) presage him an ill-death.\"{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}} (The Bishop was apparently [[Christian the Younger of Brunswick]].)\n\nIn 1696, a London [[bailiff]] attempted to serve process on a [[debtor]] who had taken refuge within the precincts of the [[Liberties of the Savoy|Savoy]]. The bailiff was tarred and feathered and taken in a wheelbarrow to [[Strand, London|the Strand]], where he was tied to a [[maypole]] that stood by what is now [[Somerset House]] as an improvised [[pillory]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\n[[File:Philip Dawe (attributed), The Bostonians Paying the Excise-man, or Tarring and Feathering (1774) - 02.jpg|thumb|''The Bostonians Paying the Excise-Man'', 1774 British [[propaganda]] print that depicts the tarring and feathering of [[Boston]] Commissioner of Customs [[John Malcolm (Loyalist)|John Malcolm]]. This was the second time that Malcolm had been tarred and feathered.]]\n[[File:The alternative of Williamsburg, 1775 - NARA - 532891.tif|thumb|\"The Alternative of Williamsburg\" A 1775 British print showing loyalists being forced to sign either the associations or Resolutions drawn up in Williamsburg on August 1774. The note on gibbet at upper right reads: \"A Cure for the Refractory\"\u2014a bagful of feathers and a cask of tar. Phillip Dawe print]]\n\n===Coming of The American War of Independence===\nIn 1766, Captain William Smith was tarred, feathered, and dumped into the harbor of [[Norfolk, Virginia]] by a mob that included the town's mayor. A vessel picked him out of the water just as his strength was giving out. He survived and was later quoted as saying that they \"dawbed my body and face all over with tar and afterwards threw feathers on me.\" Smith was suspected of informing on smugglers to the British customs agents, as was the case with most other tar-and-feathers victims in the following decade.<ref>{{cite book|author=\"Letters of Governor Francis Fauquier\"|title= ''The William and Mary Quarterly''|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vikjAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA167|volume=21|year=1912|pages=166\u201367}}</ref>\n\nThe practice appeared in [[Salem, Massachusetts|Salem]], [[Massachusetts]] in 1767, when mobs attacked low-level employees of the customs service with tar and feathers. In October 1769, a mob in Boston attacked a customs service sailor the same way, and a few similar attacks followed through 1774. The tarring and feathering of Customs Commissioner [[John Malcolm (Loyalist)|John Malcolm]] received particular attention in 1774. Such acts associated the punishment with the [[Patriot (American Revolution)|Patriot]] side of the [[American Revolution]]. An exception occurred in March 1775 when a British regiment inflicted the same treatment on Thomas Ditson, a [[Billerica, Massachusetts]] man who attempted to buy a musket from one of the regiment's soldiers. There is no known case of a person dying from being tarred and feathered in this period. During the [[Whiskey Rebellion]], local farmers inflicted the punishment on federal tax agents.<ref>Benjamin H. Irvin, \"Tar, feathers, and the enemies of American liberties, 1768-1776.\" ''New England Quarterly'' (2003): 197-238. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/1559903 in JSTOR]</ref>\n\n===19th century===\nBeginning on September 11, 1791, western Pennsylvania farmers rebelled against the federal government's taxation on western Pennsylvania whiskey distillers during the [[Whiskey Rebellion]]. Their first victim was reportedly a recently appointed tax collector named Robert Johnson. He was tarred and feathered by a disguised gang in [[Washington County, Pennsylvania|Washington County]]. Other officials who attempted to serve court warrants on Johnson's attackers were whipped, tarred, and feathered. Because of these and other violent attacks, the tax went uncollected in 1791 and early 1792. The attackers modeled their actions on the protests of the [[American Revolution]].<ref>{{cite book | last = Slaughter | first = Thomas P. | title = The Whiskey Rebellion: Frontier Epilogue to the American Revolution | url = https://archive.org/details/whiskeyrebellion00slau | url-access = registration | publisher = Oxford University Press | date = 1986 | isbn = 0195051912 }} pages 113-114</ref>\n\n[[Joseph Smith]], founder of the [[Latter Day Saint movement]], was dragged from his home during the night of March 24, 1832 by a group of men who stripped and beat him before tarring and feathering him. His wife and infant child were knocked from their bed by the attackers and were forced from the home and threatened. (The infant died several days later from exposure.) Smith was left for dead, but limped back to the home of friends. They spent much of the night scraping the tar from his body, leaving his skin raw and bloody. The following day, Smith spoke at a church devotional meeting and was reported to have been covered with raw wounds and still weak from the attack.<ref>See [[Life of Joseph Smith from 1831 to 1834#Life in Kirtland, Ohio]]</ref>{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nIn 1851, a [[Know-Nothing]] mob in [[Ellsworth, Maine]] tarred and feathered Swiss-born [[Jesuit]] priest Father [[John Bapst]] in the midst of a local controversy over religious education in grammar schools. Bapst fled Ellsworth to settle in nearby [[Bangor, Maine]], where there was a large [[Irish-Catholic]] community, and a local high school there is named for him.<ref>{{CathEncy|id=02258a|title=John Bapst|first=Thomas|last=Campbell|accessdate=December 17, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===20th century===\n[[File:The tarring and feathering of Mrs Lowry.png|thumb|Image accompanying story of \"Female Whitecaps Chastise Woman\" from ''[[Ada Evening News]]'' November 27, 1906. The article describes an incident in East Sandy, Pennsylvania where four married women tarred and feathered Mrs. Hattie Lowry.]]\nTarring and feathering was not restricted to men. The November 27, 1906 Ada, Oklahoma ''Evening News'' reports that a vigilance committee consisting of four young married women from East Sandy, Pennsylvania corrected the alleged evil conduct of their neighbor Mrs. Hattie Lowry in [[Whitecapping|whitecap style]]. One of the women was a sister-in-law of the victim. The women appeared at Mrs. Lowry's home in open day and announced that she had not heeded the spokeswoman and leader. Two women held Mrs. Lowry to the floor while the other two smeared her face with stove polish until it was completely covered. They then poured thick molasses upon her head and emptied the contents of a feather pillow over the molasses. The women then marched the victim to a railroad camp, tied by the wrists, where two hundred workmen stopped work to watch the spectacle. After parading Mrs. Lowry through the camp, the women tied her to a large box where she remained until a man released her. Three of the women involved were arrested, pleaded guilty and each paid a $10.00 fine.<ref>[http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84026853/1906-11-21/ed-1/seq-7/#date1=11%2F01%2F1906&index=2&rows=20&searchType=advanced&language=&sequence=0&words=Hattie+Lowry&proxdistance=5&date2=11%2F31%2F1906&ortext=&proxtext=Hattie+Lowry&phrasetext=&andtext=&dateFilterType=range&page=1 The Abbeville press and banner., November 21, 1906, Image 7]</ref>\n\nThere were several examples of tarring and feathering of African Americans in the lead-up to [[World War I]] in [[Vicksburg, Mississippi]].<ref name=harris/> According to William Harris, this was a relatively rare form of mob punishment to Republican African-Americans in the post-bellum U.S. South, as its goal was typically pain and humiliation rather than death.<ref name=harris>Harris, William J. \"Etiquette, Lynching, and Racial Boundaries in Southern History: A Mississippi Example\". ''[[The American Historical Review]]''. Vol. 100, No. 2 (Apr., 1995), pp. 387\u2013410</ref>\n\nDuring World War I, [[anti-German sentiment]] was widespread in the United States and many German-Americans were attacked. For example, in August 1918 a German-American farmer, John Meints of Luverne, Minnesota, was captured by a group of men, taken to the nearby South Dakota border and tarred and feathered \u2013 for allegedly not supporting [[war bond]]s. Meints sued his assailants and lost, but on appeal to a federal court he won, and  in 1922 settled out of court for $6,000.<ref name=\"startribune.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/blogs/70155507.html |title=Nov. 16, 1919: Tarred and feathered |publisher=StarTribune.com |date= |accessdate=2012-03-07}}</ref> In March 1922, a German-born Catholic priest in [[Slaton, Texas]], Joseph M. Keller, who had been harassed by local residents during World War I due to his ethnicity, was accused of breaking the [[Seal of the Confessional (Catholic Church)|seal of confession]] and tarred and feathered. Thereafter Keller served a Catholic parish in Milwaukee, Wisconsin.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bills|first1=E. R.|title=Texas Obscurities: Stories of the Peculiar, Exceptional and Nefarious|date=October 29, 2013|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|location=\"Father Keller\"|isbn=9781625847652|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Vvx2CQAAQBAJ&pg=PT51&dq=Keller}}</ref>\n\nFuture Australian senator [[Fred Katz]] \u2013 a socialist and anti-conscriptionist of German parentage \u2013 was publicly tarred and feathered outside his office in Melbourne in December 1915.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://biography.senate.gov.au/katz-frederick-carl/|title=Katz, Frederick Carl (1877\u20131960)|work=The Biographical Dictionary of the Australian Senate|first=Frank|last=Bongiorno|year=2004|publisher=Melbourne University Press}}</ref> A week before the [[1919 Australian federal election]], former [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] MP [[John McDougall (Australian politician)|John McDougall]] was kidnapped by a group of about 20 ex-soldiers in [[Ararat, Victoria]], and subsequently tarred and feathered before being dumped in the town's streets. He had earlier been revealed as the author of an anti-war poem that was perceived as insulting Australia's soldiers. Six men were charged with inflicting [[grievous bodily harm]], but pled down to common assault and were fined \u00a35 each. Many newspapers supported their actions.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Terry|last=King|title=The Tarring and Feathering of J. K. McDougall: 'Dirty Tricks' in the 1919 Federal Election|journal=Labour History|volume=45|year=1983|pages=54\u201367}}</ref>\n\nA group of black-robed Knights of Liberty (a faction of the [[KKK]]) tarred and feathered seventeen members of the [[Industrial Workers of the World]] (IWW) in Oklahoma in 1917, during an incident known as the [[Tulsa Outrage]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Chapman |first=Lee Roy |url=http://thislandpress.com/09/01/2011/tate-brady-battle-greenwood/ |title=The Nightmare of Dreamland This Land |date=September 2011 |accessdate=September 1, 2011}}</ref> In the 1920s, vigilantes were opposed to [[Industrial Workers of the World|IWW]] organizers at California's harbor of [[San Pedro, Los Angeles, California|San Pedro]]. They kidnapped at least one organizer, subjected him to tarring and feathering, and left him in a remote location.{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\nThe Wednesday, May 28, 1930 edition of the ''Miami Daily News-Record'' contains on its front page the arrests of five brothers (Isaac, Newton, Henry, Gordon and Charles Starns) from Louisiana accused of tarring and feathering Dr. S. L. Newsome, who was a prominent dentist. This was in retaliation for the dentist having an affair with one of the brother's wives.{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\nSimilar tactics were also used by the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army]] (IRA) during the early years of [[the Troubles]]. Many of the victims were women accused of sexual relationships with policemen or British soldiers.<ref>{{cite news |date=February 13, 2011 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2011/feb/13/paul-theroux-this-was-england |newspaper=The Observer |location=London |title=This was England |first=Paul |last=Theroux}}</ref> \nIn August 2007, [[Ulster loyalism|loyalist]] groups in Northern Ireland were linked to the tarring and feathering of an individual accused of drug-dealing.<ref>{{cite news |date=August 28, 2007 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/6966493.stm |publisher=BBC News Online |location=London |title=Belfast man tarred and feathered |accessdate=August 28, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Riding a rail|Riding the rail]]\n* [[Tarring and feathering in popular culture]]\n* [[:Category:Tarring and feathering in the United States|Tarring and feathering in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n'''Attribution'''\n*{{EB1911|wstitle=Tarring and Feathering|volume=26}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Tarring and feathering}}\n*[http://www.yale.edu/lawweb/avalon/medieval/richard.htm Text of law of Richard I]\n*\"[http://www.straightdope.com/classics/a3_020.html Has anyone actually ever been tarred and feathered?]\" at [[Straight Dope]]\n*Richard L. Bushman, ''[[Joseph Smith: Rough Stone Rolling]]''., Alfred Knopf, 2005, {{ISBN|1-4000-4270-4}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tarring And Feathering}}\n[[Category:Corporal punishments]]\n[[Category:Feathers]]\n[[Category:Vigilantism]]\n[[Category:Vigilantism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Physical torture techniques]]\n[[Category:Whiskey Rebellion]]\n[[Category:Tarring and feathering in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toJohn McDougall(link changed toJohn McDougall (Australian politician, born 1867)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tarring_and_feathering"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States", "text_new": "{{pp-move-indef|small=yes}}\n{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{short description|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=February 2020}}\n<!--NOTE: Please discuss on talk page before putting a \"current event\" template here. This is intended for short-term use only per advice at Template:Current-->\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States\n| map1            = COVID-19 outbreak USA per capita cases map.svg\n| legend1         = Confirmed cases per million inhabitants\n| disease         = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = United States\n| first_case      = [[Everett, Washington]]<!--no source, not mentioned in the article-->\n| arrival_date    = January 15, 2020<ref name= NEJMFirstCase/><br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=15|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}} ago)\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sheikh |first1=Knvul |last2=Rabin |first2=Roni Caryn |title=The Coronavirus: What Scientists Have Learned So Far |url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/what-is-coronavirus.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 10, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n| deaths          = 3,170 ([[Johns Hopkins University|JHU]])<ref name=\"JHU\">{{cite web| last = Johns Hopkins CSSE| title = Coronavirus COVID19 (2019-nCoV)| work = Coronavirus COVID-19 Global Cases| format = ArcGIS| accessdate = March 28, 2020| url = https://www.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6}}</ref><br /> 2,405 ([[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] confirmed)<ref name=\"CDC_case_numbers\">{{cite news |title=Cases in U.S. |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/cases-updates/cases-in-us.html |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |agency=Center for Disease Control}}</ref>\n| confirmed_cases = 164,539 ([[Johns Hopkins University|JHU]])<ref name=\"JHU\"/><br /> 140,904 ([[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] confirmed)<ref name=\"CDC_case_numbers\"/>\n| recovery_cases  = 5,945 ([[Johns Hopkins University|JHU]])<ref name=\"JHU\"/>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://coronavirus.gov/}}\n}}\n\nAn ongoing [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|worldwide pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] ({{nowrap|COVID-19}}), a new infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] ({{nowrap|SARS-CoV-2}}), was first confirmed to have spread to the [[United States]] in January 2020. Cases have been confirmed in all fifty [[U.S. state]]s, the [[Washington, D.C.|District of Columbia]], and all inhabited [[Territories of the United States|U.S. territories]] except [[American Samoa]].<ref name=mariana>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/03/28/saipan-confirms-two-covid-19-positive-cases/2932326001/|title=Saipan confirms two COVID-19 positive cases|date=March 28, 2020|website=www.samoanews.com|language=en|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> {{As of|2020|03|31|df=US}}, the U.S. has the most confirmed active cases in the world and ranks fourth in the number of total deaths from the virus.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6|title=Coronavirus COVID-19 Global Cases by the Center for Systems Science and Engineering (CSSE) at Johns Hopkins |access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> As of March 30, 2020, the number of US deaths (3,156)<ref name=\":5\" /> surpassed the death toll of the [[September 11 attacks]] (2,977).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2013/07/27/us/september-11-anniversary-fast-facts/index.html|title=September 11 Terror Attacks Fast Facts|last=Research|first=CNN Editorial|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nThe first known case of {{nowrap|COVID-19}} in the U.S. was confirmed on January 20, 2020, in a 35-year-old man who had returned from [[Wuhan]], China, five days earlier.<ref name=NEJMFirstCase>{{cite journal |vauthors=Holshue ML, DeBolt C, Lindquist S, Lofy KH, et al |title=First Case of 2019 Novel Coronavirus in the United States |journal=N. Engl. J. Med. |volume=382 |issue=10 |pages=929\u2013936 |date=March 2020 |pmid=32004427 |doi=10.1056/NEJMoa2001191 }}</ref> The [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]] was established on January 29.<ref name=\"Jan29WH\">{{cite press release|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/statement-press-secretary-regarding-presidents-coronavirus-task-force/|date=January 29, 2020|accessdate=March 15, 2020|publisher=[[White House]]|title=Statement from the Press Secretary Regarding the President's Coronavirus Task Force}}</ref> Two days later, most major airlines suspended flights between the U.S. and China,<ref name=Yen>{{cite news |last1=Yen |first1=Hope |title=AP FACT CHECK: Trump's inaccurate boasts on China travel ban |url=https://apnews.com/0dc271ad7f7917374a5a0cfb49273783 |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=AP |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref name=Koenig>{{cite news |last1=Koenig |first1=David |last2=Bussewitz |first2=Cathy |last3=Pisani |first3=Joseph |title=Delta, American and United suspend flights between US, China |url=https://apnews.com/7a165f73821fdd44e321a38be005886c |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=AP |date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> and the [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Trump administration]] declared a [[public health emergency (United States)|public health emergency]] and announced restrictions on travelers arriving from China.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/01/31/801686524/trump-declares-coronavirus-a-public-health-emergency-and-restricts-travel-from-c |work= [[NPR]] |date= January 31, 2020 |accessdate= March 18, 2020 |title= Trump Declares Coronavirus A Public Health Emergency And Restricts Travel From China |author= Aubrey, Allison}}</ref> On February 26, the first case in the U.S. in a person with \"no known exposure to the virus through travel or close contact with a known infected individual\" was confirmed by the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) in northern California.<ref name=HomeGrown>{{cite news |url= https://www.sacbee.com/news/california/article240674471.html |work= [[The Sacramento Bee]] | title= First U.S. coronavirus case of unknown origin confirmed in Northern California, CDC says |author= Smith, Darrell and Cathie Anderson |date= February 26, 2020 |accessdate= March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe United States got off to a slow start in [[COVID-19 testing]].<ref name=WhoriskeyMarch16/><ref name=WangMarch22/><ref>{{Cite news|last=Pilkington|first=Ed|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/28/trump-coronavirus-politics-us-health-disaster|title=The missing six weeks: how Trump failed the biggest test of his life|date=2020-03-28|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-28|last2=McCarthy|first2=Tom|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Until the end of February, the [[Food and Drug Administration|Food and Drug Administration (FDA)]] procedures forbade laboratories other than the CDC from releasing test results to patients, even if they followed internationally recognized test protocols. The CDC developed and distributed test kits of its own, but many of them were found to have a manufacturing flaw in a non-essential component, which made the kit illegal to use until the protocol was changed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/cdc-coronavirus-testing-error-resolved-by-throwing-away-reagent-2020-3|title=For more than 2 weeks, state labs were told they couldn't use the CDC's coronavirus tests\u2014but the tests could have been used all along|first=Aria|last=Bendix|website=Business Insider|date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref name=WhoriskeyMarch16/><ref name=WangMarch22/> The FDA did not allow use of any test kits other than the CDC's until the end of February. On February 29 the FDA began allowing public health agencies, hospitals, and private companies to develop tests and perform testing, and by mid-March private companies were shipping hundreds of thousands of tests.<ref name=LeeMarch21/> The FDA initially had very restrictive guidelines on who was allowed to be tested; on March 5 it said anyone with a doctor's order could be tested.<ref name=WangMarch22/> As of March 25, at least 418,000 tests had been conducted,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Subramaniam |first1=Tara |last2=Lybrand |first2=Holmes |title=Fact Check: US has done more coronavirus tests than South Korea, but not per person |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/25/politics/coronavirus-testing-trump-south-korea-fact-check/index.html |website=CNN}}</ref> and by March 30 the number had reached 945,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/interactives/2020/coronavirus-testing-by-state-chart-of-new-cases/|title=Live tracker: How many coronavirus cases have been reported in each U.S. state?|last=Jin|first=Beatrice|date=March 30, 2020|work=Politico|accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe CDC warned that widespread transmission of the disease may force large numbers of people to seek hospitalization and other healthcare, which may overload healthcare systems.<ref name=\"CDC COVID-19 Situation Summary\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/summary.html |title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) Situation Summary |last=CDC |publisher=CDC |accessdate=March 7, 2020|date=March 7, 2020 }}</ref> Since March 19, 2020, the U.S. [[United States Department of State|Department of State]] has advised U.S. citizens to avoid all international travel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://travel.state.gov/content/travel/en/traveladvisories/ea/travel-advisory-alert-global-level-4-health-advisory-issue.html|title=Global Level 4 Health Advisory\u2014Do Not Travel|website=travel.state.gov}}</ref> On March 16 the White House advised against any gatherings of more than 10 people.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Liptak |first1=Kevin |title=White House advises public to avoid groups of more than 10, asks people to stay away from bars and restaurants |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/16/politics/white-house-guidelines-coronavirus/index.html |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=[[CNN]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> In mid-March 2020, the [[Federal Emergency Management Agency]] (FEMA) told the [[United States Army Corps of Engineers]] (USACE) to plan to construct new facilities, including leased hotels and other buildings, and to convert them for use as [[hospitals]] and [[intensive care unit]]s.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.enr.com/articles/48927-rep-defazio-fema-asks-army-corps-to-help-build-emergency-health-facilities|title=Rep. DeFazio: FEMA Asks Army Corps to Help Build Emergency Health Facilities|last1=Ichniowski|first1=Tom|last2=Rubin|first2=Debra K.|date=March 18, 2020|work=Engineering News-Record|accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/balajis/status/1242029099310133248|title=Ok. It's just one clip. But it's by far the most intelligent thing I've heard any government official say in the last few months. Further increases likelihood the military will take over COVID19 response in the near future. |website=twitter.com/usarmy|first=Balaji S.|last=Srinivasan|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> [[U.S. state and local government response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic|State and local responses]] to the outbreak have included prohibitions and cancellation of large-scale gatherings, the closure of schools and other educational institutions, the cancellation of [[trade fair|trade shows]], [[Convention (meeting)|conventions]], and music festivals, and the cancellation and suspension of [[Sport|sporting events]] and [[Sports league|leagues]].<ref name=\"nyt sports\">{{Cite news|last=Deb|first=Sopan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/11/sports/basketball/warriors-coronavirus-fans.html|title=Sports Leagues Bar Fans and Cancel Games Amid Coronavirus Outbreak|date=March 11, 2020|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=March 12, 2020|last2=Cacciola|first2=Scott|issn=0362-4331|last3=Stein|first3=Marc}}</ref>\n\n==Current number of non-repatriated cases by state==\n\n<div style=\"display: flex; width: 100%;\"><!--serious rendering issues in current article with it floated to the right-->{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States cases by state}}</div>\n\nThe CDC publishes official numbers every Monday, Wednesday, and Friday, reporting several categories of cases: individual travelers, people who contracted the disease from other people within the U.S., and repatriated citizens who returned to the U.S. from crisis locations, such as [[Wuhan]], where the disease originated, and the cruise ship ''Diamond Princess''.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/cases-in-us.html|title=International Locations with Confirmed COVID-19 Cases|date=February 11, 2020|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222072600/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/cases-in-us.html|archive-date=February 22, 2020|access-date=February 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n{{further|Timeline of the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{see also|#CDC reported U.S. totals}}\n[[File:COVID-19 outbreak New York CSA per capita cases map.svg|thumb|Confirmed cases per 10,000 inhabitants near New York City. At over 80,000 (as of March 31) the New York metropolitan area contains about half the confirmed cases in the U.S.]]\n\nThe COVID-19 outbreak, which the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) declared a [[Public Health Emergency of International Concern]] by January 30,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Boseley |first1=Sarah |title=WHO declares coronavirus a global health emergency |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/30/who-declares-coronavirus-a-global-health-emergency |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=January 30, 2020}}</ref> and a [[pandemic]] by March 11,<ref name=\"nyt sports\"/> has had a disparate impact on different areas of the U.S. Of the 154 known deaths in the country prior to March 20, 94 occurred [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Washington (state)|in the state of Washington]], with 35 of those [[Life Care Centers of America#Kirkland, Washington COVID-19 outbreak|at one nursing home]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.kingcounty.gov/depts/health/news/2020/March/20-covid.aspx |title=Additional testing capacity, adjustments at King County jails, and other COVID-19 updates from Public Health\u2014Seattle & King County for March 20, 2020 |publisher=King County |date=March 20, 2020 |accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> By late March, the epicenter of the outbreak in the United States had shifted to New York. The state accounted for 56% of all U.S. confirmed cases on March 25, but was showing signs of a potentially declining growth rate of new cases .<ref>{{cite news |last1=Xu Klein |first1=Jodi |title=Coronavirus: New York Governor Andrew Cuomo says early signs show social distancing may be working |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/article/3077011/coronavirus-new-york-governor-andrew-cuomo-says-early-signs-show-social |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |publisher=South China Morning Post |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> For the country as a whole, the mortality rate for confirmed coronavirus cases was 1.3% based on March 24 data. In comparison, the other three most effected nations had significantly higher death rates of 4% in China, 9.8% in Italy, and 7.1% in Spain, while Germany in fifth place had a lower rate of .5%.<ref>{{cite news |title=US now has 3rd-most positive coronavirus cases, rate of death remains relatively low |url=https://fox4kc.com/tracking-coronavirus/us-now-has-3rd-most-positive-coronavirus-cases-rate-of-death-remains-relatively-low/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |publisher=FOX 4 KS |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn early March, the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) advised against non-essential travel to [[China]], [[Iran]], [[Malaysia]], the [[United Kingdom]], [[Ireland]], and the 26 European countries that comprise the [[Schengen Area]]. The United States also denied entry to foreign nationals who had traveled through China, Iran, or the aforementioned European regions within the past 14 days. Americans returning home after traveling in these regions were required to undergo a health screening and submit to a 14-day [[quarantine]].<ref>{{cite news |title=DHS Issues Supplemental Instructions for Inbound Flights with Individuals Who Have Been in China|url=https://www.dhs.gov/news/2020/02/02/dhs-issues-supplemental-instructions-inbound-flights-individuals-who-have-been-china|accessdate=March 9, 2020 |agency=[[Department of Homeland Security]]|date=March 8, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Madrigal\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2020/03/how-many-americans-have-been-tested-coronavirus/607597/|title=Exclusive: The Strongest Evidence Yet That America Is Botching Coronavirus Testing|last=Madrigal|first=Robinson Meyer, Alexis C.|date=March 6, 2020|website=[[The Atlantic]]}}</ref> Quarantines are governed by section 361 of the Public Health Service Act (42 U.S. Code \u00a7 264).<ref>{{cite web |title=U.S.C. Title 42\u2014THE PUBLIC HEALTH AND WELFARE |url=https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/USCODE-2011-title42/html/USCODE-2011-title42-chap6A-subchapII-partG.htm |website=www.govinfo.gov |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref name=myth13>{{cite web |author=Live Science Staff 10 |title=13 Coronavirus myths busted by science |url=https://www.livescience.com/coronavirus-myths.html |website=livescience.com |language=en |date=March 2020}}</ref> Throughout March, several state, city, and county governments imposed [[Stay-at-home order|\"stay at home\"]] [[U.S. state and local government response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic|quarantines on their populations]], in order to stem the spread of the virus.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nBy mid-March, all 50 states were able to perform tests, with a doctor's approval, either from the CDC or from commercial labs in a state, but the number of available test kits remained limited,<ref name=\"theatlantic.com\">[https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2020/03/why-coronavirus-testing-us-so-delayed/607954/ \"The 4 Key Reasons the U.S. Is So Behind on Coronavirus Testing\"], Atlantic Monthly, March 15, 2020</ref> which meant the true number of people infected with the virus was a challenge to estimate with any reasonable accuracy at the time. The CDC suggested that doctors use their own judgment along with certain guidelines before authorizing a test. By March 12, diagnosed cases of {{nowrap|COVID-19}} in the U.S. exceeded a thousand, which doubled every two days to reach more than 17,000 by March 20.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/03/11/coronavirus-live-updates/ Live updates: As U.S. coronavirus cases top 1,000, mixed signs of recovery in China, South Korea], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', Adam Taylor and Teo Armus, March 11, 2020. Retrieved March 11, 2020.</ref><ref>[https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/18/health/us-coronavirus-case-updates-wednesday/index.html US coronavirus cases soar past 8,500 as officials try to head off overwhelming effects], Holly Yan, Christina Maxouris and Steve Almasy, CNN, March 18, 2020</ref>\n\nAdministration officials warned on March 19 that the number of cases would begin to rise sharply as the country's testing capacity substantially increased.<ref name=\"CBSTesting\">{{cite news |last1=Kates |first1=Graham |title=Confirmed coronavirus cases will jump as testing ramps up |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/coronavirus-confirmed-cases-rise-tests/ |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |publisher=CBS |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> Around this time, the United States began running 50,000 to 70,000 coronavirus tests per day.<ref name=\"GageTesting\">{{cite news |last1=Gage |first1=John |title='Transformed the testing process': Deborah Birx says US has done more coronavirus testing in eight days than South Korea in eight weeks |url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/transformed-the-testing-process-deborah-birx-says-us-has-done-more-coronavirus-testing-in-eight-days-than-south-korea-in-eight-weeks |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |publisher=Washington Examiner |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> On March 26, the total number of confirmed cases surpassed that of China with over 85,000, making the U.S. the country with the highest number of coronavirus patients in the world.<ref name=\"SA-20200326\">{{cite news |last1=Berke |first1=Jeremy |last2=McFall-Johnsen |first2=Morgan |title=USA Now Has More COVID-19 Cases Than Any Other Country in The World |url=https://www.sciencealert.com/usa-is-now-the-centre-of-the-covid-19-outbreak-as-their-case-numbers-top-italy-s |date=26 March 2020 |work=ScienceAlert.com |accessdate=27 March 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"NYT-20200326\">{{cite news |last=McNeil, Jr. |first=Donald G. |title=The U.S. Now Leads the World in Confirmed Coronavirus Cases\u2014Following a series of missteps, the nation is now the epicenter of the pandemic. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/26/health/usa-coronavirus-cases.html |date=26 March 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=27 March 2020 }}</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52056586 Coronavirus: US overtakes China with most cases], BBC, March 27, 2020</ref> The country reached another critical mark, as the number of positive cases surged over 100,000 the next day on March 27.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chan |first1=Christine |last2=Shumaker |first2=Lisa |last3=Maler |first3=Sandra |title=Confirmed coronavirus cases in U.S. reach 100,000: Reuters tally |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-usa-cases/confirmed-coronavirus-cases-in-u-s-reach-100000-reuters-tally-idUSKBN21E3DA |date=28 March 2020 |work=Reuters.com |accessdate=28 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Government responses==\n===Task force formation===\n\n[[File:Coronavirus_Task_Force_Press_Briefing_(49608829838).jpg|thumb|[[Mike Pence]] delivers remarks at a [[Coronavirus Task Force]] briefing on February 29, 2020, accompanied by [[Alex Azar]] and [[Anthony Fauci]]]]\n \nOn January 29, 2020, President Trump established the [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]] to coordinate and oversee efforts to \"monitor, prevent, contain, and mitigate the spread\" of COVID-19 in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/statement-press-secretary-regarding-presidents-coronavirus-task-force/|title=Statement from the Press Secretary Regarding the President's Coronavirus Task Force|website=The White House}}</ref> Secretary of HHS [[Alex Azar]] was appointed as the leader of the task force.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/coronavirus|title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-2019)|date=March 13, 2020|publisher=U.S. Department of State|accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Jan29WH\" /> On February 26, Trump appointed Vice President [[Mike Pence]] to take charge of the nation's response to the virus.<ref name=NYT-Pence>{{cite news |last1=Shear |first1=Michael |last2=Weiland |first2=Noah |last3=Rogers |first3=Katie |title=Trump Names Mike Pence to Lead Coronavirus Response |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/26/us/politics/trump-coronavirus-cdc.html |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=February 26, 2020 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20200227003735/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/26/us/politics/trump-coronavirus-cdc.html |archivedate=February 27, 2020}}</ref> [[FEMA]] was put in charge of procuring medical supplies on March 17.<ref>{{cite web|website=CNN Politics|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/22/politics/pritzker-illinois-states-competing-medical-supplies/index.html?fbclid=IwAR2V-qnW7rlWo8NNUZs_F6BaQDDoyURi-y1BUbLt5pp40odOt5ggZcrhs5w|title=Illinois governor says 'it's a wild west' for medical supplies because of Trump's response to states' requests|accessdate=March 23, 2020|date=March 22, 2020|author=Devan Cole}}</ref><ref>[https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/22/trump-wants-defeat-coronavirus-credit-143531?fbclid=IwAR3gFHc5e-sTTlP2uQJsE302d-7WT8KV68Hl9HO92Pzd-XBfb8DwJzR3xtM Trump wants to defeat coronavirus\u2014and make sure he gets credit] By NANCY COOK, Politico, March 22, 2020, retrieved March 23, 2020</ref>\n\n===Containment and mitigation===\n\nThe early phases of public health efforts for epidemics and pandemics are to contain or limit further outbreaks. Those actions will often involve tracing contacts, implementing quarantines, and isolating infectious cases. They will demand significant human resources and government staffing at all levels. As an outbreak grows, new facilities may need to be constructed to manage additional infectious cases.<ref name=NCBI>[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK525302/#pt5.ch17.sec2 \"Pandemics: Risks, Impacts, and Mitigation\"], [[National Center for Biotechnology Information]] (NCBI)</ref>\n\nNational medical organizations like the CDC focus on both containment to first keep the virus from spreading after its detection, and mitigation, to prevent it from spreading quickly beyond containment limits. The process of mitigating the COVID-19 pandemic is needed to extend its time frame by spreading out cases and isolating individuals, which slows the spread of the disease. By that means, it lowers the peak, or number of new cases, which reduces the likelihood of suddenly over-crowding doctors' offices and hospitals beyond their capacity.<ref name=cleveland>[https://www.cleveland.com/news/2020/03/mad-about-coronavirus-cancellations-heres-why-mitigating-the-curve-matters.html \"Mad about coronavirus cancellations? Here's why mitigating the curve matters\"], ''Cleveland.com'', March 12, 2020</ref>\n\nThe risk of a truly global pandemic is limited for some diseases, such as [[Ebola]], because of the slow pace of transmission or high probability of detection and containment. COVID-19 is at the other extreme, being a pathogen that has high potential to cause a severe pandemic, especially because it easily transmits between people and remains asymptomatic for a long period, thereby lengthening the time it is infectious and not detected.<ref name=NCBI/>\n\nIn general, once a pandemic has begun within a country's borders, the government must begin taking steps to curtail interactions between infected and uninfected populations. The methods used could include isolation of infected patients, quarantine, physical distancing practices, school closures, use of personal protective equipment, and [[Travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|travel restrictions]].<ref name=NCBI/>\n\nThe WHO on January 30 warned that \"all countries should be prepared for containment, including active surveillance, early detection, isolation and case management, [[contact tracing]] and prevention of onward spread\" of the virus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kennedy |first1=Merrit |title=WHO Declares Coronavirus Outbreak A Global Health Emergency |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/01/30/798894428/who-declares-coronavirus-outbreak-a-global-health-emergency |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=[[NPR]] |date=January 30, 2020}}</ref> February 25 was the first day the CDC told the American public to prepare for an outbreak.<ref>Marisa Taylor ''[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-china-cdc-exclusiv-idUSKBN21910S Exclusive: U.S. axed CDC expert job in China months before virus outbreak]'' March 22, 2020 Reuters.com</ref>\n\n====Travel and entry restrictions====\n\n{{See|Travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:200318-H-NI589-120 (49679050593).jpg|thumb|US Customs and Border Protection officer checks travel documents of a pilot arriving in Virginia from an international flight]]\n\nChinese health authorities confirmed that they identified a cluster of a novel infectious coronavirus on December 31, 2019, in the city of Wuhan, officially reporting their findings on January 7, 2020. An American citizen, after traveling from Wuhan, China to his home in Washington state, became the first U.S. case of the new virus on January 20.<ref name=nejm>[https://www.nejm.org/doi/10.1056/NEJMoa2001191 \"First Case of 2019 Novel Coronavirus in the United States\"], ''The New England Journal of Medicine'', March 5, 2020</ref>\n\nAfter the first COVID-19 case appeared in the United States, and after most major airlines had already suspended flights between the U.S. and China,<ref name=Yen/><ref name=Koenig/> President Trump imposed travel restrictions on January 31 preventing foreign nationals from entering the U.S. if they had been in China within the previous two weeks. The immediate family members of U.S. citizens and permanent residents were exempt from this restriction. In addition, Trump imposed a quarantine for up to 14 days on American citizens returning from [[Hubei]] province, then a coronavirus hotspot. This is the first quarantine order the U.S. federal government has issued in over 50 years.<ref name=\"USA Today quarantine\" /><ref name=\"AP ban\">{{cite news |last1=Moritsugu |first1=Ken |last2=Miller |first2=Zeke |title=US bars foreigners coming from China for now over virus fear |url=https://apnews.com/9e22f8aabe2f454593b9f9b4c67eb31f |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> Although the WHO had recommended against travel restrictions at the time,<ref>{{cite news |title=WHO says countries should keep borders open, trade & people moving despite coronavirus |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-who/who-says-countries-should-keep-borders-open-trade-people-moving-despite-coronavirus-idUSKBN1ZU1C2 |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> HHS Secretary [[Alex Azar]] said the decision stemmed from the recommendations of HHS health officials.<ref name=factcheck>[https://www.factcheck.org/2020/03/the-facts-on-trumps-travel-restrictions/ \"The Facts on Trump's Travel Restrictions\"], ''Factcheck'', March 6, 2020</ref> Trump expanded those travel restrictions to Iran on February 29.<ref name=factcheck/>\n\nOver the following few weeks, the Trump administration imposed a number of other travel restrictions:\n\n* In mid-February, the CDC, along with President Trump, opposed allowing fourteen people who had tested positive for COVID-19 while passengers on the cruise ship ''[[Diamond Princess (ship)|Diamond Princess]]'' to be flown back to the U.S. without completing a 14-day quarantine. They were overruled by officials at the U.S. State Department.\"<ref name=\"ARS CDC 14\">{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2020/02/coronavirus-patients-flew-to-us-after-cdc-explicitly-recommended-against-it/|title=CDC didn't want 14 coronavirus patients flown to US\u2014it was overruled|last=Mole|first=Beth|date=February 21, 2020|website=[[Ars Technica]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228022158/https://arstechnica.com/science/2020/02/coronavirus-patients-flew-to-us-after-cdc-explicitly-recommended-against-it/|archive-date=February 28, 2020|access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n* On March 12, the CDC recommended against any non-essential travel to China,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/notices/warning/novel-coronavirus-china|title=COVID-19 in China|publisher=CDC|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> most of Europe,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/notices/warning/coronavirus-europe|title=COVID-19 in Europe|publisher=CDC|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Iran,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/notices/warning/coronavirus-iran|title=COVID-19 in Iran|publisher=CDC|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Malaysia,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/notices/warning/coronavirus-malaysia|title=COVID-19 in Malaysia\u2014Warning\u2014Level 3, Avoid Nonessential Travel\u2014Travel Health Notices {{!}} Travelers' Health {{!}} CDC|website=wwwnc.cdc.gov|access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> and South Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/notices/warning/coronavirus-south-korea|title=COVID-19 in South Korea|publisher=CDC|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref name=USATodayBan>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/2020/03/12/coronavirus-state-department-warns-americans-reconsider-traveling-abroad/5029446002/|title=State Department warns Americans to reconsider traveling abroad due to coronavirus|last=Tate|first=Curtis|website=USA Today|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The following week, the [[U.S. Department of State]] recommended that U.S. citizens not travel abroad, while those who are abroad should \"arrange for immediate return to the United States\" unless prepared to remain abroad indefinitely.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wong|first=Edward|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/19/us/politics/coronavirus-state-department-travel.html|title=As Pandemic Grows, U.S. Warns Americans Not to Travel Abroad|date=March 19, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 20, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://travel.state.gov/content/travel/en/traveladvisories/ea/travel-advisory-alert-global-level-4-health-advisory-issue.html|title=Global Level 4 Health Advisory\u2014Do Not Travel|publisher=[[United States Department of State]]|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n* On March 19, the State Department suspended routine visa services at all American embassies and consulates worldwide.<ref>[https://travel.state.gov/content/travel/en/News/visas-news/suspension-of-routine-visa-services.html \"Suspension of Routine Visa Services\"], Dept. of State, March 20, 2020</ref>\n* By March 20, the U.S. began barring entry to foreign nationals who had been in 28 European countries within the past 14 days. American citizens, [[Green card|permanent residents]], and their immediate families returning from abroad can re-enter the United States under the new restrictions, but those returning from one of the specified countries must undergo health screenings and submit to quarantines and monitoring for up to 14 days. In addition to the earlier travel restrictions in place, Trump extended this quarantine and monitoring requirement to those coming from Iran and the entirety of China. Flights from all restricted countries are required to land at one of 13 airports where the [[United States Department of Homeland Security]] (DHS) has \"enhanced\" entry screenings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dhs.gov/news/2020/03/17/fact-sheet-dhs-notice-arrival-restrictions-china-iran-and-certain-countries-europe|title=Fact Sheet: DHS Notice of Arrival Restrictions on China, Iran and Certain Countries of Europe|date=March 17, 2020|website=Department of Homeland Security|language=en|access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"USA Today quarantine\">{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/01/31/coronavirus-donald-trump-declares-public-health-emergency/4625299002/ |title=Trump administration declares coronavirus emergency, orders first quarantine in 50 years |last=Jackson |first=David |website=[[USA Today]] |access-date=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205090931/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/01/31/coronavirus-donald-trump-declares-public-health-emergency/4625299002/ |archive-date=February 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> At least 241 foreigners (including several Canadians), who had recently traveled in China and Iran, were denied entry to the United States between February{{nbsp}}2 and March 3.<ref>{{cite news|date=March 5, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020|title=DHS denies 241 people entry at US ports and airports over coronavirus|last=Sands|first=Geneva|publisher=CNN|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/05/politics/dhs-denies-entry-coronavirus/index.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=March 5, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020|title=U.S. refuses entry to more than 100 people from Canada as a result of coronavirus measures|last=Panetta|first=Alexander|work=[[CBC News]] |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/us-coronavirus-border-canada-1.5487696}}</ref>\n\n====Containment efforts within the U.S.====\n\n[[File:USNS Comfort.jpg|thumb|US Navy hospital ship ''Comfort'']]\n\nAs part of the early efforts to contain and mitigate the pandemic within the United States, Surgeon General [[Jerome Adams]] announced in early March that local leaders would soon have to consider whether to cancel large gatherings, consider telework policies, and close schools.<ref>[https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/08/health-officials-coronavirus-elderly-sick-risk-123889 \"Health officials shift tone on coronavirus, say elderly and sick at risk\"], ''Politico'', March 8, 2020</ref> Over the next few weeks, a number of states imposed lockdown measures of different scope and severity, which placed limits on where people can travel, work and shop away from their homes.<ref name=WSJ-lockdowns>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-state-by-state-guide-to-coronavirus-lockdowns-11584749351?mod=theme_coronavirus-ribbon \"A Guide to State Coronavirus Lockdowns\"], ''Wall Street Journal'', March 21, 2020</ref>\n\nBy March 21, governors in New York, California and other large states had ordered most businesses to close and for people to stay inside, with limited exceptions. The order in New York, for instance, exempts financial institutions, some retailers, pharmacies, hospitals, manufacturing plants and transportation companies, among others. It placed a ban on non-essential gatherings of any size and for any reason.<ref name=WSJ-lockdowns/>\n\nIn late March, Trump announced that the National Guard would be deployed to California, New York, and Washington, and FEMA would send large medical stations with thousands of beds to the three states.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/coronavirus-live-updates-us-now-highest-globally-covid/story?id=69733219|title=National Guard to deploy against coronavirus in NY, California, Washington|date=March 22, 2020|work=ABC News|accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> The city of Chicago said it will rent more than a thousand empty hotel rooms to house coronavirus patients who need to be isolated but do not require hospitalization.<ref>[https://www.businessinsider.com/chicago-to-rent-out-hotel-rooms-for-coronavirus-patients-isolation-2020-3 \"Chicago will start renting more than 1,000 of its empty hotel rooms to house coronavirus patients or those awaiting test results\"], ''Business Insider'', March 23, 2020</ref> Another containment and care facility planned would be two Navy hospital ships.<ref name=ships/> The [[USNS Mercy (T-AH-19)|USNS ''Mercy'']] arrived in Los Angeles on March 27,<ref name = mercyarrives/> and the [[USNS Comfort (T-AH-20)|USNS ''Comfort'']]\narrived in New York City on March 30.<ref name=comfortarrives/>\n\nOn March 28, the president said he had decided not to enact a tri-state lockdown of New York, New Jersey and Connecticut, after having publicly suggested earlier in the day that he was considering such a move; instead he ordered the CDC to issue a travel advisory suggesting voluntary travel limitations in these states.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus Live Updates: Trump Says a Quarantine 'Will Not Be Necessary' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/28/world/coronavirus-live-news-updates.html?action=click&module=Spotlight&pgtype=Homepage |accessdate=29 March 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===COVID-19 testing===\n\nBeyond identifying whether a person is currently infected, coronavirus testing helps health professionals ascertain how bad the epidemic is and where it is worst.<ref>[https://www.statnews.com/2020/03/13/coronavirus-testing-long-way-to-go/ \"Coronavirus testing is starting to get better\u2014but it has a long way to go\"], ''STAT'', March 13, 2020</ref> However, the accuracy of national statistics on the number of cases and deaths from the outbreak depend on knowing how many people are being tested every day, and how the available tests are being allocated. But as of late March, most countries do not provide official reports on tests performed, therefore there is no centralized WHO data on COVID-19 testing.<ref>[https://ourworldindata.org/coronavirus-testing-source-data \"Coronavirus Testing\u2014Source Data\"], ''Our World of Data'', March 20, 2020</ref>\n\nWhile the World Health Organization opted to use an approach developed by Germany to test for COVID-19, the United States developed its own testing approach. The German testing method was made public on January 13, and the American testing method was made public on January 28. The World Health Organization did not offer any test kits to the U.S. because the U.S. normally had the supplies to produce their own tests.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Greenberg |first1=Jon |last2=Knight |first2=Victoria |title=Mostly False: Joe Biden stated on March 15, 2020 in a Democratic primary debate: \"The World Health Organization offered the testing kits that they have available and to give it to us now. We refused them. We did not want to buy them.\" |url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/mar/16/joe-biden/biden-falsely-says-trump-administration-rejected-w/ |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Politifact]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> In February, the U.S. CDC produced 160,000 coronavirus tests, but soon it was discovered that many were defective and gave inaccurate readings.<ref name=\"WhoriskeyMarch16\">{{cite news |last1=Whoriskey |first1=Peter |last2=Satija |first2=Neena |title=How U.S. coronavirus testing stalled: Flawed tests, red tape and resistance to using the millions of tests produced by the WHO |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2020/03/16/cdc-who-coronavirus-tests/ |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kenen |first1=Joanne |title=How testing failures allowed coronavirus to sweep the U.S. |url=http://www.politico.com/amp/news/2020/03/06/coronavirus-testing-failure-123166 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=[[Politico]] |date=March 8, 2020}}</ref> Although academic laboratories and hospitals had developed their own tests, they were not allowed to use them until February 29, when the FDA issued approvals for them and private companies.<ref name=\"WhoriskeyMarch16\"/> Approvals were required by federal law due to the outbreak being declared as a public health emergency.<ref name=LeeMarch21>{{cite news |last1=Lee |first1=Timothy |title=America is finally testing for coronavirus in significant volumes |url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2020/03/america-is-finally-testing-for-coronavirus-in-significant-volumes/ |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=[[Ars Technica]] |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, from the start of the outbreak to early March 2020, the CDC gave restrictive guidelines on who should be eligible for COVID-19 testing. The initial criteria were (a) people who had recently traveled to certain countries affected by the outbreak, or (b) people with respiratory illness serious enough to require hospitalization, or (c) people who have been in contact with a person confirmed to have COVID-19. Only on March{{nbsp}}5 did the CDC relax the criteria to allow doctors discretion to decide who would be eligible for tests.<ref name=WangMarch22>{{cite news |last1=Wang |first1=Jessica |last2=Huth |first2=Lindsay |last3=Umlauf |first3=Taylor |last4=Wang |first4=Elbert |last5=McKay |first5=Betsy |title=How the CDC's Restrictive Testing Guidelines Hid the Coronavirus Epidemic |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-the-cdcs-restrictive-testing-guidelines-hid-the-coronavirus-epidemic-11584882001 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |archivedate=March 22, 2020 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=March 22, 2020 |archiveurl=http://archive.today/tp9HA}}</ref>\n[[File:Colorado National Guard (49673441472).jpg|thumb|Colorado National Guard, [[Colorado Department of Public Health and Environment|CDPHE]], and [[San Miguel County, Colorado|San Miguel County]] personnel assist at a drive-up testing center in [[Telluride, Colorado]]]]\n\nAs a result, the United States had a slow start in conducting widespread testing for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web |title=Squandered time: How the Trump administration lost control of the coronavirus crisis |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-coronavirus-response-squandered-time/2020/03/07/5c47d3d0-5fcb-11ea-9055-5fa12981bbbf_story.html |first1=Ashley |last1=Parker | first2=Yasmeen |last2=Abutaleb |first3=Lena |last3=Sun |website=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=March 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Cohen |first1=Jon |title=The United States badly bungled coronavirus testing\u2014but things may soon improve |url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/02/united-states-badly-bungled-coronavirus-testing-things-may-soon-improve |website=Science |date=February 28, 2020 |accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref> Fewer than 4,000 tests were conducted in the U.S. by February 27, with U.S. state laboratories conducting only around 200.<ref name=WhoriskeyMarch16/> The first U.S. case of a person having COVID-19 of unknown origin (a possible indication of [[community transmission]] in the [[state of California]]) saw the patient's test being delayed for four days after being hospitalized on February 19, because he had not qualified for a test under the initial federal testing criteria.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Abdalla |first1=Jihan |title=First US coronavirus case of unknown origin marks 'turning point' |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/02/coronavirus-case-unknown-origin-marks-turning-point-200227154643100.html |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=[[Al Jazeera]] |date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> Whereas in [[Washington state]], a group of researchers defied a lack of clearance from federal and state officials to conduct their own tests from February 25, using samples already collected from their flu study that their subjects had not given permission for COVID-19 testing. They quickly found a teenager infected with COVID-19 of unknown origin, newly indicating that an outbreak was already occurring in Washington. State regulators stopped these researchers' testing on March 2.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fink |first1=Sheri |last2=Baker |first2=Mike |title='It's Just Everywhere Already': How Delays in Testing Set Back the U.S. Coronavirus Response |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/10/us/coronavirus-testing-delays.html |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 5, Vice President Mike Pence, the leader of the coronavirus response team, acknowledged that \"we don't have enough tests\" to meet the predicted future demand; this announcement came only three days after [[FDA]] commissioner [[Stephen Hahn (oncologist)|Stephen Hahn]] committed to producing nearly a million tests by that week.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: White House concedes US lacks enough test kits |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51761435 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref> Senator [[Chris Murphy]] of Connecticut and representative [[Stephen F. Lynch|Stephen Lynch]] of Massachusetts both noted that as of March{{nbsp}}8 their states had not yet received the new test kits.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Cathey |first1=Libby |title=Government coronavirus response: Trump prepared to use the 'full power' of government |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/government-coronavirus-response-updates-fauci-warns-congress-worse/story?id=69532695 |website=ABC News |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> [[Anthony Fauci]], the head of the [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]], acknowledged on March 12 that it was \"a failing\" of the U.S. system that the demand for coronavirus tests was not being met; Fauci later clarified that he believed the private sector should have been brought in sooner to address the shortfall.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kessler |first1=Glenn |title=What did Dr. Anthony Fauci say about coronavirus testing 'failing'? |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/18/what-did-dr-fauci-say-about-coronavirus-testing-failing/ |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> By March 13, fewer than 14,000 tests had been done in the United States, reported ''[[The Atlantic]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Khazan |first1=Olga |title=The 4 Key Reasons the U.S. Is So Behind on Coronavirus Testing |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2020/03/why-coronavirus-testing-us-so-delayed/607954/ |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=[[The Atlantic]] |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe timing and availability of testing varies across countries. For example, by March 13 South Korea offered [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea#Drive-through testing site|drive-through testing centers]], which could get results the next day.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/03/13/815441078/south-koreas-drive-through-testing-for-coronavirus-is-fast-and-free \"South Korea's Drive-Through Testing For Coronavirus Is Fast\u2014And Free\"], NPR, March 13, 2020</ref> South Korea also had a government-funded daily testing capacity of 15,000.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/03/13/815441078/south-koreas-drive-through-testing-for-coronavirus-is-fast-and-free |title= South Korea's Drive-Through Testing For Coronavirus Is Fast\u2014And Free |last= Kuhn |first= Anthony |date= March 13, 2020 |website= [[NPR]] |publisher= |access-date= March 17, 2020}}</ref> According to March 16 and 17 statistics from [[Our World in Data]], the U.S. had tested 125 people per million of their population\u2014around the same as Japan. The U.K. tested nearly 750 per million, Italy more than 2,500 per million, and South Korea more than 5,500 per million.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McCarthy |first1=Niall |title=U.S. Lags Behind Other Countries In Coronavirus Testing |url=https://www.statista.com/chart/21108/covid-19-tests-performed-per-million-of-the-population/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=[[Statista]] |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> The first COVID-19 cases in the U.S. and South Korea were identified at around the same time.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McCann |first1=Larry |last2=Lai |first2=Rebecca |last3=McCann |first3=Allison |title=U.S. Lags in Coronavirus Testing |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/03/17/us/coronavirus-testing-data.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> Critics say the U.S. government has botched the approval and distribution of test kits, losing crucial time during the early weeks of the outbreak, with the result that the true number of cases in the United States was impossible to estimate with any reasonable accuracy.<ref name=\"theatlantic.com\"/><ref>{{Cite news|last=Pilkington|first=Ed|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/13/coronavirus-testing-us|title=Why has coronavirus testing in the US been such a disaster?|date=March 13, 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=March 15, 2020|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n[[File:U.S. Government COVID-19 Response Plan, March 13, 2020.pdf|thumb|The ''New York Times'' obtained this response plan for the pandemic by the HHS dated March 13, 2020.]]\n\nAs of March 12, all 50 states were able to perform tests, with a doctor's approval, either from the CDC or from commercial labs in a state.<ref>[https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/testing-in-us.html \"Testing in the U.S.\"], CDC, March 13, 2020</ref> This was followed by the government announcing a series of measures intended to speed up testing. These measures included the appointment of Admiral [[Brett Giroir]] of the [[United States Public Health Service|U.S. Public Health Service]] to oversee testing, funding for two companies developing rapid tests, and a hotline to help labs find needed supplies.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/03/13/815363944/trump-administration-announces-measures-to-speed-coronavirus-testing \"Trump Administration Announces Measures To Speed Coronavirus Testing\"], NPR, March 13, 2020</ref> The [[FDA]] also gave emergency authorization for New York to obtain an automated coronavirus test unit that will reduce testing time to 3.5 hours.<ref>[https://nypost.com/2020/03/13/fda-issues-emergency-authorization-for-coronavirus-test/ \"FDA authorizes coronavirus test that could drastically speed up screening\"], ''New York Post'', March 13, 2020</ref>\n\nOn March 13, drive-through testing in the U.S. began in [[Westchester County, New York|New Rochelle]], [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]], as New Rochelle was the U.S. town with the most diagnosed cases at that time.<ref name=\"pbs1\">{{cite news |accessdate=March 15, 2020 |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/show/new-york-launches-drive-thru-testing-site-for-covid-19 |title=New York launches drive-thru testing site for COVID-19 |work=PBS |location=New York, NY |date=March 14, 2020 |author=Booker, Christopher}}</ref> By March 22, drive-through testing had appeared in more than thirty states, however the [[Associated Press]] reported that \"the system has been marked by inconsistencies, delays, and shortages\", leading to many people waiting hours or days even though they showed symptoms and were recommended by a doctor to get a test. A lack of supplies had already forced the closure of drive-through testing in Alabama, Colorado, Florida, Louisiana, New Mexico, Utah and Virginia.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Michelle |title=Chaos, Inconsistency Mark Launch of Drive-Thru Virus Testing |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/business/articles/2020-03-22/chaos-inconsistency-mark-launch-of-drive-thru-virus-testing |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn a March 13 press conference, the Trump administration announced an effort for tests to be conducted in retail store parking lots across the country, with participating franchises including [[Walmart]], [[Target Corporation|Target]], [[CVS Health|CVS]], and [[Walgreens]]. The plan was that test data would be sent to labs to complete testing in partnership with local health departments and diagnostic labs.<ref name=\"reuters1\">{{cite news |accessdate=March 15, 2020 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-google/google-walmart-join-us-effort-to-speed-up-coronavirus-testing-idUSKBN21036R |title=Google, Walmart join U.S. effort to speed up coronavirus testing |work=Reuters |location=New York, NY |date=March 13, 2020 |author=Sanders, Chris}}</ref> Two weeks later, five stations had been opened by the companies: Walmart two, Target none, CVS one, Walgreens one, and one more from newcomer [[Rite Aid]]. These were labelled as \"prototype sites\" by the Trump administration.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dwoskin |first1=Elizabeth |last2=Bhattarai |first2=Abha |last3=Eilperin, |first3=Juliet |last4=Parker |first4=Ashley |title=Coronavirus: Drive-thru testing sites promised by Trump administration nowhere to be seen |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/trump-promised-scores-of-big-box-retailers-would-offer-parking-lots-for-covid-19-testing-there-are-only-five-of-them/2020/03/27/ece8ab06-703a-11ea-aa80-c2470c6b2034_story.html |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |date=March 28, 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref>\n\n===Research into vaccine and drug therapies===\n\n{{further|COVID-19 vaccine}}\n\nThere is currently no drug approved for treating COVID-19 either as a therapy or a vaccine, nor is there any clear evidence that COVID-19 infection leads to immunity (experts assume it does for some period).<ref>[https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-00798-8 \"Coronavirus vaccines: five key questions as trials begin\"], ''Nature'', March 18, 2020</ref> As of late March 2020, more than a hundred drugs are in testing.<ref>Bob Herman [https://www.axios.com/coronavirus-treatment-vaccine-research-pharma-drugs-55a28ea3-ee91-4f77-a093-44d450470b25.html Over 100 drugs are in testing in the race to treat coronavirus] March 25, 2020 Axios</ref>\n\t\nAmong the labs working on a vaccine is the [[Walter Reed Army Institute of Research]], which has previously studied other infectious diseases, such as HIV/AIDS, Ebola, and MERS. Speed in developing a vaccine is a key element in the midst of the pandemic. By March 18, tests had begun with a few dozen volunteers in Seattle, Washington, which was sponsored by the U.S. government. Similar safety trials of other coronavirus vaccines will begin soon in the U.S. Trials are also underway in China and Europe.<ref>[https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/walter-reed-researchers-join-global-search-coronavirus-vaccine-n1165806 \"Walter Reed researchers join global search for coronavirus vaccine\"], ''NBC News'', March 21, 2020</ref>\n[[File:President Trump at the National Institute of Health (49618032306).jpg|thumb|President Trump and [[Anthony Fauci]] visited the [[Vaccine Research Center]] and the Viral Pathogenesis Laboratory at the [[National Institutes of Health]] on March 3, 2020]]\n\nThe search for a vaccine has taken on aspects of national security and global competition.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/19/us/politics/coronavirus-vaccine-competition.html \"Search for Coronavirus Vaccine Becomes a Global Competition\"], ''New York Times'', March 19, 2020</ref> In March President Trump directed the [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) to accelerate the testing and possible use of certain medications to find out if they would help treat coronavirus patients.<ref name=WSJ-drugs>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-expected-to-detail-new-virus-therapies-but-expansion-could-be-controversial-11584629965?mod=searchresults&page=1&pos=10 \"U.S. Moves to Expand Array of Drug Therapies Deployed Against Coronavirus\"], ''Wall Street Journal'', March 19, 2020</ref> Among potential drugs are [[chloroquine]] and [[hydroxychloroquine]], which have long been used successfully to treat [[malaria]]. In March, both hydroxychloroquine and chloroquine were already being used to treat coronavirus patients by a number of physicians under the limited [[compassionate use]] approval of the FDA, while trials and analysis are still ongoing.<ref name=WSJ-drugs/> On March 29, the FDA issued an [[Emergency Use Authorization]], allowing the drugs as treatments for hospitalized coronavirus patients when clinical trials are not available for them to join.<ref name=\"JustinWise\">{{cite news |last1=Wise |first1=Justin |title=FDA issues emergency-use authorization for anti-malaria drugs amid coronavirus outbreak |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/490110-fda-issues-emergency-use-authorization-for-anti-malaria-drugs-amid |accessdate=30 March 2020 |publisher=The Hill |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n \t\nIn China, trials of chloroquine are underway at dozens of clinics, with early laboratory results showing that it seems to reduce the virus's rate of replication. Chloroquine has been used to treat patients with malaria for nearly a century.<ref name=LATimes-drugs>{{cite web |first1=Amina|last1=Khan|date=March 21, 2020|url-access=subscription|url=https://www.latimes.com/science/story/2020-03-21/coronavirus-treatments-where-we-are-and-what-we-know |title=Coronavirus drugs: Where we are and what we know| work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nLike chloroquine, the closely-related drug hydroxychloroquine has already been used to treat certain [[autoimmune disease]]s like [[lupus]] and [[rheumatoid arthritis]].<ref name=LATimes-drugs/> A study in the peer-reviewed medical journal ''[[Clinical Infectious Diseases]]'' published on March{{nbsp}}9 provided dosing recommendations for hydroxycholorquine as a COVID-19 treatment, and showed it to be more effective in inhibiting the virus in vitro than chloroquine.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Yao |first1=X. |display-authors=etal |title=In Vitro Antiviral Activity and Projection of Optimized Dosing Design of Hydroxychloroquine for the Treatment of Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2). |journal=[[Clinical Infectious Diseases]] |date=March 9, 2020 |doi=10.1093/cid/ciaa237 |pmid=32150618 }}</ref> Doctors are currently testing hydroxycholoroquine in coronavirus patients.<ref name=LATimes-drugs/> On March 20, the WHO announced a large global trial of both drugs.<ref>[https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/03/who-launches-global-megatrial-four-most-promising-coronavirus-treatments \"WHO launches global megatrial of the four most promising coronavirus treatments\"], [[Science (journal)|''Science'']], March 22, 2020</ref>\n\nBecause there is little time to fully test the drug, some experts{{who|date=March 2020}} in the U.S. have suggested using hydroxychloroquine as a [[first-line treatment]]. The heads of the FDA and the [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]] have been hesitant due to inherent risks{{which|date=March 2020}}. New York Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] planned to study its potential beginning March 24.<ref>[https://www.statnews.com/2020/03/22/why-trump-at-odds-with-medical-experts-over-malaria-drugs-against-covid-19/ \"Why President Trump is at odds with his medical experts over using malaria drugs against Covid-19\"], ''STAT'', March 22, 2020</ref> However, there is currently a shortage of hydroxychloroquine, and some would like the federal government to release any stockpiles it may have and contract with generic manufacturers to ramp up production.<ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/these-drugs-are-helping-our-coronavirus-patients-11584899438 \"These Drugs Are Helping Our Coronavirus Patients\"], ''Wall Street Journal'', March 22, 2020</ref> The French laboratory [[Sanofi]] said it had the ability to provide millions of doses, enough to treat 300,000 patients, if it proved effective.<ref name=TOI>[https://www.timesofisrael.com/teva-to-send-us-millions-of-malaria-pills-with-potential-to-help-covid-19/ \"Teva to send US millions of malaria pills with potential to help COVID-19\"], ''Times of Israel'', March 20, 2020</ref> In the same month the Israeli company [[Teva Pharmaceuticals]] said it planned to manufacture and donate ten million doses to U.S. hospitals at no charge.<ref name=TOI/> The HHS reported on March 29 that the government would make available 30 million doses of hydroxychloroquine and 1{{nbsp}}million doses of chloroquine recently donated to the Strategic National Stockpile for doctors to prescribe within limitations for COVID-19 patients.<ref name=\"JustinWise\" />\n\nAlso being tested in research clinics is the antiviral drug [[remdesivir]].<ref name=WSJ-drugs/> It was developed to fight [[Ebola]], although it failed to prove effective for that disease.<ref name=LATimes-drugs/>  At a Coronavirus Task Force briefing on March 19, Food and Drug Administration Commissioner [[Stephen Hahn (oncologist)|Stephen Hahn]] noted that the FDA had made remdesivir available for \"compassionate use\" for dying coronavirus patients, while the FDA standard approval process was still ongoing.<ref name=March19Briefing /> Due to the emergency nature of the pandemic, former FDA commissioners Drs. [[Scott Gottlieb]] and [[Mark McClellan]] have called for the FDA to develop therapeutics and vaccines that would be exempt from some regulatory requirements.<ref name=WSJ-drugs/>\n\n===Medical supplies===\n\nOn March 15, senior federal health official Anthony Fauci said the United States had 12,700 [[ventilator]]s in its national stockpile.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Knutson |first1=Jacob |title=Fauci on coronavirus: \"We'll be thankful that we're overreacting\" |url=https://www.axios.com/fauci-coronavirus-overreaction-decc88f5-ab25-4c27-86d2-aff3acea583c.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=[[Axios (website)|Axios]] |date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> On March 19, Vice President Mike Pence declared that the federal government had \"literally identified tens of thousands of ventilators\", but did not provide further details.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Walsh |first1=James |title=Elon Musk Can't Solve This |url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/03/car-manufacturers-alone-cant-solve-the-ventilator-crisis.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, Trump told state governors that for medical equipment including respirators and ventilators, \"We will be backing you, but try getting it yourselves.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Martin |first1=Jonathan |title=Trump to Governors on Ventilators: 'Try Getting It Yourselves' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/16/us/politics/trump-coronavirus-respirators.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 16, 2020 |archiveurl=http://archive.today/MbYiK |archivedate=March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 24, Trump said state governors who wanted help from the federal government \"have to treat us well, also\", because \"it's a two-way street\"; he warned against governors arguing \"we should get this, we should get that\".<ref name=McGrawMarch24>{{cite news |last1=McGraw |first1=Meredith |title=How to update the country on coronavirus: Thank Trump first |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/24/update-country-coronavirus-thank-trump-147625 |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=[[Politico]] |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> On March 24, the [[Governor of New York]], [[Andrew Cuomo]], declared that the [[state of New York]] would need 30,000 ventilators to handle the peak of the outbreak in the state, which was predicted to arrive in two weeks. Cuomo also said the federal government had sent only 400 ventilators to New York. Two days later, Trump, citing \"a feeling\", stated: \"I don't believe you need 40,000 or 30,000 ventilators.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Forgey |first1=Quint |last2=Choi |first2=Matthew |title=Trump downplays need for ventilators as New York begs to differ |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/26/trump-ventilators-coronavirus-151311 |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=[[Politico]] |date=March 27, 2020}}</ref> He also said that [[Governor of Washington]], [[Jay Inslee]], \"shouldn't be relying on the federal government\"; Inslee says the president needs to enact a \"national mobilization of the industrial base in this country\" to produce medical supplies.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Miller |first1=Zeke |last2=Colvin |first2=Jill |last3=Superville |first3=Darlene |title=Trump, rejecting blame, warns governors to be 'appreciative' |url=https://komonews.com/news/nation-world/trump-rejecting-blame-warns-governors-to-be-appreciative |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=[[Associated Press]] |date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nTrump signed the [[Defense Production Act]] on March 18, which allows the federal government a wide range of powers, including giving directions to industries on what to produce, having companies prioritize certain contracts, allocating supplies, giving incentives to industries, and allowing companies to cooperate. Initially under the act, he conferred more power over contracts and resources to the Health and Human Services Secretary and enacted provisions to prevent hoarding of medical resources.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vazquez |first1=Maegan |title=Trump invokes Defense Production Act to expand production of hospital masks and more |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/18/politics/trump-defense-production-act-coronavirus/index.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=[[CNN]] |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Rizzo |first1=Salvador |title=Is Trump using the Defense Production Act? |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/25/is-trump-using-defense-production-act/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> He first invoked the act to direct industry production on March 27, instructing the HHS to compel [[General Motors]] to manufacture ventilators, after negotiations with the company stalled. He also appointed [[Peter Navarro]] to oversee enforcement of the act.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clark |first1=Dartunorro |title=Trump invokes Defense Production Act to force GM to make ventilators for coronavirus fight |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/trump-invokes-defense-production-act-force-gm-make-ventilators-coronavirus-n1170746 |accessdate=29 March 2020 |publisher=NBC News |date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 18, Trump remarked that the federal government purchased 500 million [[N-95 mask]]s to make more private masks available and that American manufacturers were repurposing factories to manufacture masks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/remarks-president-trump-vice-president-pence-briefing-nurses-covid-19-response/|title=Remarks by President Trump and Vice President Pence in a Briefing with Nurses on COVID-19 Response|website=The White House|language=en-US|access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy March 21, the director of the [[Johns Hopkins Center for Health Security]] described American hospitals as already facing shortages of test kit reagents, test kit swabs, masks, gowns and gloves.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Diamond |first1=Dan |title=Short-term thinking plagues Trump's coronavirus response |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/21/short-term-thinking-trump-coronavirus-response-140883 |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=[[Politico]] |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> In a March 20 to March 24 survey of 214 American mayors (who manage a total 42 million people), 85% said they did not have enough ventilators, 92% said they did not have enough face masks, 88% said there was a shortage of other personal protective equipment, and 92% said they did not have enough test kits.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Adamczyk |first1=Ed |title=U.S. mayors say they're running out of supplies to fight coronavirus |url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/US/2020/03/27/US-mayors-say-theyre-running-out-of-supplies-to-fight-coronavirus/2751585333088/ |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=[[UPI]] |date=March 27, 2020}}</ref> On the prevalence of medical supplies, Trump said on March 29 that \"many of the states are stocked up\", with certain hospitals \"holding ventilators, they don't want to let 'em up\". Trump said he could not understand how demand for face masks had supposedly surged from 10,000 to 300,000 per week, stating that it was \"maybe worse than hoarding\": \"Are they going out the back door?\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Blake |first1=Aaron |title=Trump blames hospitals for mask and ventilator shortages |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/29/trump-bizarrely-blames-hospitals-mask-ventilator-shortages/ |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nVentilator manufacturers are facing a shortage of sub-components needed to produce the ventilators, reported [[Bloomberg News]] on March 25.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Light |first1=Joe |last2=Mider |first2=Zachary |last3=Proper |first3=Ellen |title=Ventilator Makers Can Speed Up But Face Shortages of Parts |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-24/ventilator-makers-can-speed-up-but-they-face-shortages-of-parts |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> When Trump was asked by a reporter on whether the United States would have enough ventilators as needed, he told the reporter: \"Don't be a cutie pie\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cathey |first1=Libby |title=Coronavirus government response updates: Trump signs $2T relief bill after House passage |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/coronavirus-government-response-updates-drama-house-votes-2t/story?id=69833576 |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=[[ABC News]] |date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, Trump stated governors should be \"appreciative\", with his administration having \"done a job, the likes of which nobody has seen\". Trump's outlook on the governors was: \"If they don't treat you right, I don't call.\" Thus, Trump told of advising Vice President Mike Pence, \"don't call\" Washington governor Inslee and [[Michigan governor]] [[Gretchen Whitmer]]\u2014although Pence would call anyway, said Trump.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Samuels |first1=Brett |title=Trump digs in on criticism of Democratic governors |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/489949-trump-digs-in-on-criticism-of-democratic-governors |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |date=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Blake |first1=Aaron |title=Trump ties coronavirus decisions to personal grievances |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/27/trump-suggests-personal-grievances-factor-into-his-coronavirus-decisions/ |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> Whitmer, who had previously argued that \"the federal government did not take this seriously early enough\", responded that Michigan still needed personal protective equipment, ventilators, masks and test kits.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jackson |first1=David |last2=Collins |first2=Michael |title=Trump to Mike Pence: 'Don't call the woman in Michigan,' aka Gov. Gretchen Whitmer |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/27/coronavirus-donald-trump-tells-pence-not-call-michigan-governor/2931251001/ |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=[[USA Today]] |date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Congressional response===\n\n[[File:President Trump Signs the Congressional Funding Bill for Coronavirus Response (49627907646).jpg|thumb|President Trump, with the Secretary of HHS, Alex Azar, signs the [[Coronavirus Preparedness and Response Supplemental Appropriations Act]] into law on March 6, 2020.]]\n\nOn March 6, 2020, President Trump signed into law the [[Coronavirus Preparedness and Response Supplemental Appropriations Act, 2020]], approved by both Houses to provide $8.3 billion to fight the pandemic. The deal includes \"more than $3&nbsp;billion for the research and development of vaccines, therapeutics and diagnostics, as well as $2.2&nbsp;billion for the CDC, and $950&nbsp;million to support state and local health agencies\".<ref name=\"Politico 8.3 billion agreement\">{{cite web |last1=Emma |first1=Caitlin |last2=Ferris |first2=Sarah |title=Congress strikes a deal on bipartisan $8.3B coronavirus package |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/04/house-coronavirus-funding-121065 |website=[[Politico]] |date=March 4, 2020|accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Trump signs $8.3 billion emergency package to combat coronavirus |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trump-signs-8-3-billion-emergency-package-to-combat-coronavirus/ |publisher=CBS News |date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref> Another bill, the [[Families First Coronavirus Response Act]] was approved on March 18. It provides paid emergency leave and food assistance be provided to affected employees, along with free testing.<ref name=\"NBC House passes\">{{cite web |last1=Moe |first1=Alex |last2=Shabad |first2=Rebecca |last3=Clark |first3=Dartunorro |title=House passes coronavirus aid package, sending bill to the Senate |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/congress/house-vote-friday-democrats-coronavirus-relief-package-n1158306 |publisher=NBC News |accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[U.S. House Committee on Financial Services]], chaired by Representative [[Maxine Waters]], released a stimulus proposal on March 18 in which the [[Federal Reserve]] would fund monthly payments of \"at least $2,000 for every adult and an additional $1000 for every child for each month of the crisis\". Other elements include suspending all consumer and small business credit payments.<ref name=\"Dems_Waters\">{{cite news|last1=Waters|first1=Maxine|url=https://financialservices.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=406440|title=Waters Announces Committee Plan for Comprehensive Fiscal Stimulus and Public Policy Response to Coronavirus Pandemic|date=March 18, 2020|work=financialservices.house.gov/|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> On March 18, Representative [[Rashida Tlaib]] proposed the similar \"Automatic BOOST to Communities Act\", which would involve sending pre-loaded $2,000 debit cards to every American, with $1,000 monthly payments thereafter until the economy recovers. This would be funded by the [[U.S.&nbsp;Treasury]] minting two [[trillion-dollar coin]]s. According to Tlaib, the Treasury has this authority, and it would not increase the national debt.<ref name=\"Mint_The_Coin\">{{cite news|last1=Higgins|first1=Eoin|url=https://www.commondreams.org/news/2020/03/21/two-1-trillion-coins-rashida-tlaib-proposal-calls-us-treasury-fund-coronavirus|title=Two $1 Trillion Coins': Rashida Tlaib Proposal Calls on US Treasury to Fund Coronavirus Recovery From US Mint|date=March 21, 2020|work=Common Dreams|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWith guidance from the White House, Senate Majority Leader [[Mitch McConnell]] proposed a third stimulus package amounting to over $1&nbsp;trillion.{{efn|This included $300&nbsp;billion to help small businesses with forgivable loans up to $10&nbsp;million<ref name=hurdles/> and $200&nbsp;billion to support industries such as airlines, cruise companies, and hotels through loans and other measures.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Stone |first1=Peter |title=Washington lobbyists in frenzied battle to secure billion-dollar coronavirus bailouts |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/20/coronavirus-washington-lobbyists-bailout |work=The Guardian |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Democrats have advocated for banning stock {{nowrap|buy-backs}} to prevent these funds from being used to make a profit.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Press |first1=Associated |title=Congress and White House resume talks on $1tn pandemic rescue deal |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/21/us-coronavirus-economic-rescue-trump |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>}}{{efn|It was suggested that $200\u2013500&nbsp;billion would fund tax rebate checks to Americans who made between $2,500 and $75,000 in 2018 to help cover short-term costs<ref name=trillion>{{cite news |last1=Hunt |first1=Kasie |last2=Caldwell |first2=Leigh Ann |last3=Tsirkin |first3=Julie |last4=Shabad |first4=Rebecca |title=White House eyeing $1 trillion coronavirus stimulus package |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/congress/senate-democrats-have-prepped-third-coronavirus-aid-package-n1161506 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=NBC News |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Singman |first1=Brooke |title=Trump wants to send Americans checks 'immediately' in response to coronavirus, Mnuchin says |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/trump-wants-to-send-money-to-americans-in-next-two-weeks-amid-coronavirus-outbreak |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=Fox News |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> via one or two payments of $600\u20131,200 per adult and $500 per child.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Breuninger |first1=Kevin |title=Trump wants direct payments of $1,000 for adults, $500 for kids in coronavirus stimulus bill, Mnuchin says |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/19/coronavirus-trump-wants-payments-of-1000-for-adults-500-for-kids.html |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=CNBC |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Re |first1=Gregg |title=McConnell's coronavirus stimulus plan would provide payments of $1,200 per person, $2,400 for couples |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/mcconnell-coronavirus-stimulus-plan-payments |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=Fox News |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=rebate/> A similar measure has been suggested by both Democrats and Republicans as a form of [[basic income]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clifford |first1=Catherine |title=Andrew Yang, AOC, Harvard professor: Free cash payments would help during coronavirus pandemic |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/13/andrew-yang-aoc-free-ubi-cash-can-help-during-coronavirus-pandemic.html |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |work=CNBC |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lahut |first1=Jake |title=Tom Cotton is calling for Americans to get cash payments through the coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/tom-cotton-calling-for-americans-to-get-100-month-coronavirus-2020-3 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=Business Insider |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> It is currently unclear whether the rebates would be tax-free.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Konish |first1=Lorie |title=Here's how your coronavirus rescue check from the government could be taxed |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/20/heres-how-your-rescue-check-from-the-government-could-be-taxed.html |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=CNBC |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>}}{{efn|Democrats prepared a $750&nbsp;billion package as a {{nowrap|counter-offer}},<ref>{{cite news |last1=Carney |first1=Jordain |title=McConnell takes reins of third coronavirus bill |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/488338-mcconnell-takes-reins-of-third-coronavirus-bill |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=The Hill |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Caygle |first1=Heather |last2=Bresnahan |first2=John |last3=Ferris |first3=Sarah |title=Pelosi looks to lay down marker on next stimulus plan |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/18/nancy-pelosi-coronavirus-stimulus-plan-136142 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=Politico |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> which focused on expanding [[unemployment benefits]] instead of tax rebates.<ref name=rebate>{{cite news |last1=Bolton |first1=Alexander |title=Democrats balk at $1,200 rebate checks in stimulus plan |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/488677-democrats-balk-at-1200-rebate-checks-in-stimulus-plan |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=The Hill |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> A compromise plan reportedly sets aside $250&nbsp;billion for tax rebates and the same amount for unemployment.<ref name=hurdles>{{cite news |last1=Mattingly |first1=Phil |title=Stimulus package could top $2 trillion as negotiators look to clear final major hurdles |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/21/politics/stimulus-package-negotiations-congress-coronavirus/index.html |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=CNN |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>}} On March 22 and 23, the $1.4&nbsp;trillion package, known as the [[Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act]] (or CARES Act), failed to pass in the Senate.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mill |first1=David |last2=Lee |first2=Muhyung |last3=Webb |first3=Sean |title=Coronavirus: CARES Act Vote Fails in Senate; Summary of the Tax Provisions of the Bill |url=https://content.natlawreview.com/article/coronavirus-cares-act-vote-fails-senate-summary-tax-provisions-bill |website=National Law Review |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref>{{efn|The revised draft included suspending federal student loan payments for six months without interest and $20&nbsp;billion in school funding;<ref>{{cite news |title=GOP's $2 Trillion Bill Adds Cash for Bailouts, States, Transit |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-23/gop-s-2-trillion-bill-adds-cash-for-bailouts-states-transit |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=Bloomberg.com |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Democrats said the bill did not go far enough to provide healthcare and unemployment aid, and that it provided a \"slush fund\" for corporations.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bresnahan |first1=John |last2=Levine |first2=Marianne |title=Dems seize on 'slush fund' to oppose Republican rescue package |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/23/democrats-slush-fund-republican-rescue-package-143565 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=Politico |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>}}{{efn|House Speaker [[Nancy Pelosi]] indicated that the House would prepare its own bill, expected to exceed $2.5&nbsp;trillion, as a counter-offer.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pramuk |first1=Jacob |title=House Democrats to introduce a $2.5 trillion coronavirus stimulus plan as Senate bill stalls |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/23/coronavirus-updates-pelosi-to-release-stimulus-bill-as-senate-plan-stalls.html |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=CNBC |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/pelosis-coronavirus-stimulus-bill-includes-return-of-obamaphones-climate-change-wishlist|title=Pelosi's coronavirus stimulus includes return of 'Obamaphones', other unrelated items, GOP says|last=Re|first=Gregg|date=March 23, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324041402/https://www.foxnews.com/politics/pelosis-coronavirus-stimulus-bill-includes-return-of-obamaphones-climate-change-wishlist|archive-date=March 23, 2020|access-date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>}} The act was revised in the Senate, coming to $2&nbsp;trillion, including $500&nbsp;billion for loans to larger businesses such as airlines, $350&nbsp;billion for small business loans, $250&nbsp;billion for individuals, $250&nbsp;billion for unemployment insurance, $150&nbsp;billion for state and municipal governments, and $130&nbsp;billion for hospitals.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Raju |first1=Manu |last2=Barrett |first2=Ted |last3=Foran |first3=Clare |last4=Wilson |first4=Kristin |title=White House, Senate reach historic $2 trillion stimulus deal amid growing coronavirus fears |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/25/politics/stimulus-senate-action-coronavirus/index.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=CNN |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> It passed unanimously in the Senate late the night of March 25.<ref name=\"CNBC Senate passes $2 trillion\">{{cite web |last1=Pramuk |first1=Jacob |title=Senate passes $2 trillion coronavirus stimulus package, sending it to the House |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/25/senate-passes-2-trillion-coronavirus-stimulus-package.html |website=CNBC |date=March 25, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> On March 27, the House approved the stimulus bill, and it was signed into law by President Trump.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Zeballos-Roig |first=Joseph |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-signs-coronavirus-economic-relief-aid-bill-checks-for-americans-2020-3 |title=Trump signs the $2 trillion coronavirus economic relief bill into law, which includes checks for Americans and business loans |date=March 27, 2020 |work=Business Insider |access-date=March 27, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Other federal policy responses===\n\nOn March 3, 2020, the Federal Reserve lowered [[Federal funds rate|target interest rates]] from 1.75% to 1.25%,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-fed/in-an-emergency-move-u-s-federal-reserve-cuts-interest-rates-to-battle-coronavirus-idUSKBN20Q22F|title=In an emergency move, U.S. Federal Reserve cuts interest rates to battle coronavirus|date=March 3, 2020|accessdate=March 3, 2020|agency=Reuters}}</ref> the largest emergency rate cut since the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u201308|2008 global financial crisis]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2020/03/03/economy-coronavirus-rate-cuts/|title=Fed makes largest emergency cut to interest rates since the financial crisis|date=March 3, 2020|work=The Washington Post|access-date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> in an attempt to counteract the outbreak's effect on the American economy. \"The coronavirus poses evolving risks to economic activity,\" the Federal Reserve said in a statement. \"In light of these risks and in support of achieving its maximum employment and price stability goals, the Federal Open Market Committee decided today to lower the target range for the federal funds rate.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/03/fed-cuts-rates-by-half-a-percentage-point-to-combat-coronavirus-slowdown.html|title=Fed cuts rates by half a percentage point to combat coronavirus slowdown|last=Cox|first=Jeff|date=March 3, 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304005925/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/03/fed-cuts-rates-by-half-a-percentage-point-to-combat-coronavirus-slowdown.html|archive-date=March 4, 2020|access-date=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, during his Oval Office address, Trump announced that he had requested a number of other policy changes:\n* He would ask Congress to provide financial relief and paid sick leave for workers who were quarantined or had to care for others.\n* He would instruct the [[Small Business Administration]] (SBA) to provide loans to businesses affected by the pandemic, and would ask Congress for an additional $50 billion to help hard-hit businesses.\n* He would request that tax payments be deferred beyond April 15 without penalty for those affected, which he said could add $200 billion in temporary liquidity to the economy.\n* He would ask Congress to provide payroll tax relief to those affected.<ref name=USAToday>[https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/11/trump-address-nation-over-u-s-response-coronavirus-pandemic/5022464002/ \"President Trump restricts 'all travel' from EU to US starting Friday\"], ''USA Today'', March 12, 2020</ref>\n\nOn March 15, the Fed cut their target interest rate again to a range of 0% to 0.25%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/15/business/economy/federal-reserve-coronavirus.html|title=Fed Slashes Rates to Near-Zero and Unveils Sweeping Program to Aid Economy|last1=Smialek|first1=Jeanna|last2=Irwin|first2=Neil|date=March 15, 2020|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> The Fed also announced a $700 billion [[quantitative easing]] program similar to the one initiated during the [[financial crisis of 2007\u201308]]. Despite the moves, stock index futures plunged, triggering trading limits to prevent panic selling.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/15/traders-await-futures-open-after-fed-cuts-rates-launches-easing-program.html|title=Stock futures drop\u2014hit 'limit down'\u2014even as Fed slashes rates; Dow futures off 1,000 points|last=Imbert|first=Fred|date=March 15, 2020|website=CNBC}}</ref> The Dow lost nearly 13% the next day, the third-largest one-day decline in the 124-year history of the index.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/15/traders-await-futures-open-after-fed-cuts-rates-launches-easing-program.html|title=Dow drops nearly 3,000 points, as coronavirus collapse continues; worst day since '87|first=Fred|last=Imbert|date=March 15, 2020|website=CNBC}}</ref> That day, the [[VIX]]\u2014informally known as the market \"fear index\"\u2014closed at the highest level since its inception in 1990.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/16/wall-streets-fear-gauge-hits-highest-level-ever.html|title=Wall Street's fear gauge closes at highest level ever, surpassing even financial crisis peak|first=Yun|last=Li|date=March 16, 2020|website=CNBC}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, the Federal Reserve announced a program to buy as much as $1 trillion in corporate [[commercial paper]] to ensure credit continued flowing in the economy. The measure was backed by $10 billion in Treasury funds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/business/economy/federal-reserve-coronavirus.html|title=Fed Unveils Emergency Lending Programs as Companies Struggle to Raise Cash|first1=Jeanna|last1=Smialek|first2=Kate|last2=Kelly|first3=Peter|last3=Eavis|date=March 17, 2020|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> At this point, the federal government neared agreement on an economic stimulus proposal totaling about $1 trillion, including direct cash payments to Americans.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/us-policy/2020/03/17/trump-coronavirus-stimulus-package/|title=White House expresses support for immediate cash payments to Americans as part of coronavirus stimulus package|first1=Erica|last1=Werner|first2=Jeff|last2=Stein|first3=Mike|last3=DeBonis|website=Washington Post}}</ref> Trump said his administration was working with the Congress to provide rapid relief to affected industries. He remarked that the relief would ensure the American economy would emerge as the strongest on earth. In addition, Trump announced that the Small Business Administration would be providing disaster loans which could provide impacted businesses with up to $2 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/remarks-president-trump-meeting-tourism-industry-executives-covid-19-response/|title=Remarks by President Trump in Meeting with Tourism Industry Executives on COVID-19 Response|website=The White House|language=en-US|access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n[[File:President Trump Visits the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.webmhd.webm|thumb|start=29:13|President Trump visits the CDC on March 6, 2020.]]\n\nOn March 18, Trump announced that the [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development]] (HUD) would be suspending all kinds of foreclosures and evictions until the end of April.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe week of March 19, the [[Federal Housing Finance Agency]] ordered federally-guaranteed loan providers to grant forbearance of up to 12 months on mortgage payments from people who lost income due to the pandemic. It encouraged the same for non-federal loans, and included a pass-through provision for landlords to grant forbearance to renters who lost income.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/22/819725417/the-u-s-orders-a-break-on-mortgage-payments-what-does-that-mean|title=The U.S. Orders A Break On Mortgage Payments. What Does That Mean?|website=NPR.org|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, Trump announced that the Department of Education will not be enforcing standardized testing for 2020. Trump had also instructed to waive all federally held student loans for the next sixty days, which could be extended if needed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/remarks-president-trump-vice-president-pence-members-c-oronavirus-task-force-press-briefing/|title=Remarks by President Trump, Vice President Pence, and Members of the Coronavirus Task Force in Press Briefing|website=The White House|language=en-US|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> Treasury Secretary [[Steven Mnuchin]] also announced that the deadline for all tax filings is moved to July 15.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-20/tax-filings-payment-due-date-extended-to-july-15-mnuchin-says|title=IRS Pushes Tax Date to July 15, Same as Payment Deadline|last=Davison|first=Laura|date=March 20, 2020|website=Bloomberg L.P.|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, Trump announced that he had directed FEMA to provide four large federal medical stations with 1,000 beds for New York, eight large federal medical stations with 2,000 beds for California, and three large federal medical stations and four small federal medical stations with 1,000 beds for the State of Washington.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn March 23, the Federal Reserve announced large-scale expansion of [[quantitative easing]], with no specific upper limit, and reactivation of the [[Term Asset-Backed Securities Loan Facility]]. This injects newly created money into a variety of financial markets including [[corporate bond]]s, [[exchange-traded funds]], [[small business loan]]s, [[mortgage-backed securities]], [[student loan]]s, [[auto loan]]s, and [[credit card]] loans. The Fed also lowered its [[repurchase agreement]] interest rate from 0.1% to 0%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/23/fed-announces-a-slew-of-new-programs-to-help-markets-including-open-ended-asset-purchases.html|title=The Federal Reserve just pledged asset purchases with no limit to support markets|first=Jeff|last=Cox|date=March 23, 2020|website=CNBC|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> On the same day, Trump also postponed the October 1, 2020, deadline for Americans on commercial airlines to carry [[Real ID]]-compliant documents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-23/trump-postpones-real-id-requirements-due-to-virus-concerns|title=Trump Postpones Real ID Requirements Due to Virus Concerns|last=Sink|first=Justin|date=March 23, 2020|website=Bloomberg L.P.|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Communication===\n====President Trump====\n\nFrom January 2020 to mid-March 2020, President Trump downplayed the threat posed by COVID-19 to the United States, giving many optimistic public statements,<ref name=BlakeMarch17>{{cite news |last1=Blake |first1=Aaron |title=A timeline of Trump playing down the coronavirus threat |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/12/trump-coronavirus-timeline/ |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 17, 2020 }}</ref> which may have been aimed at calming stock markets.<ref name=JazeeraMarch18>{{cite news |title=Analysis: US presidential politics in the time of coronavirus |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/analysis-presidential-politics-time-coronavirus-200317202843984.html |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=[[Al Jazeera]] |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> He initially said he had no worries about COVID-19 becoming a pandemic.<ref name=ManganMarch17>{{cite news |last1=Mangan |first1=Dan |title=Trump dismissed coronavirus pandemic worry in January\u2014now claims he long warned about it |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/17/trump-dissed-coronavirus-pandemic-worry-now-claims-he-warned-about-it.html |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=[[CNBC]] |date=March 17, 2019}}</ref> He went to state on multiple occasions that the situation was \"under control\", and gave assurances that the country was already overcoming the outbreak.<ref name=BlakeMarch17/> On February 26, he said of the virus: \"It's going to disappear. One day it's like a miracle, it will disappear. And from our shores, you know, it could get worse before it gets better. Could maybe go away. We'll see what happens. Nobody really knows.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Trump claimed coronavirus could 'disappear' in the United States, adding to the administration's mixed messages |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/coronavirus-trump-claims-covid-19-could-disappear-2020-2 |agency=Business Insider |date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> On February 27, he predicted the number of infected people in the country \"within a couple of days is going to be down to close to zero\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Abutaleb |first1=Yasmeen |last2=Park |first2=Ashley |last3=Dawsey |first3=Josh |title=Inside Trump's frantic attempts to minimize the coronavirus crisis |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/inside-trumps-frantic-attempts-to-minimize-the-coronavirus-crisis/2020/02/29/7ebc882a-5b25-11ea-9b35-def5a027d470_story.html |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 1, 2020}}</ref> In other remarks, he expressed a focus on the number of U.S. cases; commenting about cruise ship ''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic on cruise ships#Grand Princess|Grand Princess]]'', he stated his preference that infected passengers not disembark as he did not want \"to have the [U.S. case] numbers double because of one ship\".<ref name=MasonMarch9>{{cite news |last1=Mason |first1=Jeff |last2=Holland |first2=Steve |title=Trump's focus on coronavirus numbers could backfire, health experts say |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-trump-numbers-anal/trumps-focus-on-coronavirus-numbers-could-backfire-health-experts-say-idUSKBN20W16E |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=[[Reuters]] |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> He cited the relatively low number of confirmed cases in the initial stages of the outbreak, as proof of success of his travel restriction on China.<ref name=MasonMarch9/> In late February he judged the country as \"very, very ready for this, for anything\",<ref>{{cite news |title=Trump declares US 'very, very ready' for coronavirus; Pence to lead response |url=https://www.syracuse.com/health/2020/02/trump-declares-us-very-very-ready-for-coronavirus-pence-to-lead-response.html |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> while in mid-March he rated his administration's response a score of 10/10.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chalfant |first1=Morgan |title=Trump gives himself 10 out of 10 on coronavirus response |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/487883-trump-gives-himself-10-out-of-10-on-coronavirus-response |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n[[File:President Trump will address the nation LIVE at 9-00 p.m. ET..webm|thumb|right|start=|President Trump addressing the nation on March 11, 2020]]\n\nOn March 11, 2020, Trump delivered an [[Oval Office]] address on national television, just hours after the World Health Organization declared COVID-19 a global pandemic, which caused a quick fall in financial markets. It was the second such address to the country of his presidency, the first being in January 2019, addressing illegal immigration. In his speech, Trump declared that the United States was \"suspending all travel from Europe to the United States for the next 30 days\", except travel from the United Kingdom, and including \"the tremendous amount of trade and cargo\" (post-speech, Trump said trade was still approved, while administration officials clarified that \"American citizens or legal permanent residents or their families\" were not affected). Trump also listed several economic policy proposals, and declared that insurance companies \"have agreed to waive all co-payments for coronavirus treatments\" (post-speech, [[America's Health Insurance Plans]] clarified the waivers were only for tests, not treatments). Trump praised his administration's response to the \"foreign\" virus while blaming the European Union, stating that \"a large number of new clusters in the United States were seeded by travelers from Europe\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hohmann |first1=James |title=Clarifications after Trump's Oval Office address are emblematic of his uneven coronavirus response |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/paloma/daily-202/2020/03/12/daily-202-clarifications-after-trump-s-oval-office-address-are-emblematic-of-his-uneven-coronavirus-response/5e69c2b988e0fa101a7475b1/ |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, Trump changed his tone on the outbreak to a somber one. For the first time, he acknowledged that COVID-19 was \"not under control\", the situation was \"bad\" with months of impending disruption to daily lives, and a recession might occur.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dale |first1=Daniel |title=Fact check: Trump tries to erase the memory of him downplaying the coronavirus |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/17/politics/fact-check-trump-always-knew-pandemic-coronavirus/index.html |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=[[CNN]] |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> Also on March 16, President Trump and the Coronavirus Task Force released new recommendations based on CDC guidelines for Americans, titled \"15 Days to Slow the Spread\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/articles/15-days-slow-spread/|title=15 Days to Slow the Spread|date=March 16, 2020|website=The White House|language=en-US|access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Trump Issues Guidelines on '15 Days to Slow the Spread' |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/us/articles/2020-03-16/factbox-trump-issues-guidelines-on-15-days-to-slow-the-spread |work=U.S. News & World Report |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 17, \"I felt it was a pandemic long before it was called a pandemic.\"<ref name=\"Trump Now Claims\">{{Cite news|last=Rogers|first=Katie|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/us/politics/trump-coronavirus.html|title=Trump Now Claims He Always Knew the Coronavirus Would Be a Pandemic|date=March 17, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 18, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> He also said America will achieve total victory against the \"invisible enemy\", and called Americans to sacrifice together.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/remarks-president-trump-vice-president-pence-members-coronavirus-task-force-press-briefing-5/|title=Remarks by President Trump, Vice President Pence, and Members of the Coronavirus Task Force in Press Briefing|website=The White House|language=en-US|access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, Trump began referring to COVID-19 as the \"Chinese virus\", and as a result he was criticized by Chinese and WHO officials for creating a potential [[Social stigma|stigma]] against [[List of incidents of xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Chinese and Asians]]. Trump disagreed with the criticism, and said that \"China tried to say at one point\u2014maybe they stopped\u2014that it was caused by American soldiers. That can't happen.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gstalter |first1=Morgan |title=WHO official warns against calling it 'Chinese virus', says 'there is no blame in this' |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/488479-who-official-warns-against-calling-it-chinese-virus-says-there-is-no |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Shinkman |first1=Paul |title=Trump Fires Back at Complaints He's Stigmatizing China Over Coronavirus |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/national-news/articles/2020-03-17/trump-refutes-claims-of-anti-chinese-stigma-in-coronavirus-reponse |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=[[US News]] |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> Trump stopped using the term on March 23, citing the possibility of \"nasty language\" towards Asian-Americans.<ref name=\"DelaneyMarch24\">[https://www.scmp.com/news/world/united-states-canada/article/3076522/donald-trump-drops-chinese-virus-terminology-white \"Donald Trump drops 'Chinese virus' terminology in White House briefing, calls for protecting Asian-Americans\"], ''South China Morning Post'', March 24, 2020</ref> On March 26, President Trump spoke on the phone with China's President [[Xi Jinping]], when they pledged to cooperate in fighting against the pandemic. It signaled a fresh d\u00e9tente between the two countries after weeks of rising tensions.<ref name=\"phonecall\">{{cite news |last1=Leigh |first1=Karen |title=Trump, Xi Vow Virus Cooperation After Weeks of Rising Tensions |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-27/trump-touts-very-good-talk-with-xi-as-u-s-cases-surpass-china |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |date=26 March 2020}}</ref> Trump described their conversation: \n{{quote|Just finished a very good conversation with President Xi of China. Discussed in great detail the Coronavirus that is ravaging large parts of our Planet. China has been through much and has developed a strong understanding of the Virus. We are working closely together. Much respect!<ref name=\"phonecall\" />}} On the same day, after a video call summit with the other [[G20]] leaders, Trump stated the United States was working with international allies to stop the spread of the coronavirus and to increase rapid information and data sharing.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Batrawy |first1=Aya |last2=Lederer |first2=Edith M. |title=World leaders vow to coordinate virus response in video call |url=https://apnews.com/b1379fde50341508f095381191b9a71c |accessdate=28 March 2020 |agency=AP |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n[[File:White House Press Briefing (49668784683).jpg|thumb|Trump and members of the [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]] brief the media on March 16, 2020]]\n\nAfter learning about a French clinical study which showed a 70% cure rate in 20 patients,<ref name=\"IrishTimes\">{{cite news |last1=Marlowe |first1=Lara |title=Coronavirus: France hoping unorthodox virologist can save world |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/europe/coronavirus-france-hoping-unorthodox-virologist-can-save-world-1.4210278 |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |publisher=[[The Irish Times]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Elder |first1=Lane |title=Things to know about the malaria drug proposed to treat COVID-19 |url=https://www.ajc.com/news/what-hydroxychloroquine-effective-treating-coronavirus/awkTbcGymLAECtNmhyRLsO/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]] |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> Trump promoted the drugs [[chloroquine]] (also known as [[chloroquine phosphate]])<ref>{{cite web |title=Medicines for the Prevention of Malaria While Traveling Chloroquine (Aralen\u2122) |url=https://www.cdc.gov/malaria/resources/pdf/fsp/drugs/Chloroquine.pdf |website=CDC.gov |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |quote=Chloroquine (also known as chloroquine phosphate) is an antimalarial medicine.}}</ref> and [[hydroxychloroquine]] as potential treatments for COVID-19 on March 19. He noted the drugs showed \"tremendous promise\" and said he was working together with Governor Cuomo to begin quickly studying and treating coronavirus patients with the drugs in New York. He also remarked on their long-term usage as medicines in the United States saying, \"the nice part is, it's been around for a long time, so we know that if it\u2014if things don't go as planned, it's not going to kill anybody.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nisen |first1=Max |title=Trump Is Overhyping Unproven Coronavirus Drugs |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/trump-is-overhyping-unproven-coronavirus-drugs/2020/03/19/ed1ff4e2-6a1a-11ea-b199-3a9799c54512_story.html |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=The Washington Post |agency=Bloomberg |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=March19Briefing>{{cite web |title=Remarks by President Trump, Vice President Pence, and Members of the Coronavirus Task Force in Press Briefing |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/remarks-president-trump-vice-president-pence-members-coronavirus-task-force-press-briefing-6/ |website=whitehouse.gov |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Fatal overdoses of these drugs have occurred, and potential [[side effects]] are also known.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vergano |first1=Dan |title=Chloroquine Is Being Touted As A Miracle Drug For Coronavirus, But There Are Reasons To Be Wary |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/danvergano/chloroquine-dangers-coronavirus?bfsource=relatedmanual |accessdate=March 28, 2020 |work=[[Buzzfeed News]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Also during the briefing, Trump falsely claimed that chloroquine had already been \"approved very, very quickly\" by the Food and Drug Administration as a treatment for COVID-19 (leading to the FDA stating it had not yet approved any COVID-19 treatments).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dale |first1=Daniel |title=Fact check: Trump wrongly claims FDA 'approved' drug chloroquine to treat the coronavirus |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/19/politics/fact-check-chloroquine-trump-fda/index.html |accessdate=March 29, 2020 |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWithin days of this briefing, a shortage occurred for chloroquine and hydroxychloroquine in the United States, while [[panic-buying]] occurred overseas in [[Africa]] and [[South Asia]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rowland |first1=Christopher |title=As Trump touts an unproven coronavirus treatment, supplies evaporate for patients who need those drugs |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2020/03/20/hospitals-doctors-are-wiping-out-supplies-an-unproven-coronavirus-treatment/ |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=The Washington Post |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Parkinson |first1=Joe |last2=Gauthier-Villars |first2=David |title=Trump Claim That Malaria Drugs Treat Coronavirus Sparks Warnings, Shortages |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-claim-that-malaria-drugs-treat-coronavirus-sparks-warnings-shortages-11584981897 |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=[[Wall Street Journal]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> In the [[state of Arizona]], a man died, with his wife in critical condition, after they ingested fish bowl cleaner, which contained chloroquine phosphate. The couple believed the chemical cleaner could prevent them from contracting COVID-19, although the chloroquine phosphate in fish bowl cleaners is not the same formulation found in the medicines chloroquine or hydroxychloroquine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gander |first1=Kashmira |title=Health Officials Warn Against Self-Medicating With Chloroquine for Coronavirus After Man Dies From Taking Fish Tank Cleaner |url=https://www.newsweek.com/health-officials-warn-against-self-medicating-chloroquine-coronavirus-after-man-dies-taking-fish-1493874 |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |publisher=[[Newsweek]] |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The woman said she'd watched Trump's briefing in which she believed he promoted chloroquine as \"basically pretty much a cure\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Galvan |first1=Astrid |last2=Cooper |first2=Jonathan J. |title=Man dead, wife critically ill after taking additive found in anti-malaria drug touted by Trump as coronavirus treatment |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/coronavirus/ct-nw-coronavirus-chloroquine-phosphate-death-20200324-nu3qrbdqcvdwjnoed44g5vcbcy-story.html |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=Chicago Tribune |agency=Associated Press |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> During the same briefing, Trump also discussed remdesivir as another promising COVID-19 therapy.<ref name=March19Briefing />\n\nOn March 22, Trump indicated that he was considering scaling back social distancing measures implemented around a week ago: \"We cannot let the cure be worse than the problem itself\". A day later, Trump argued that economic problems arising from social distancing measures will cause \"suicides by the thousands\" (without citing evidence) and \"probably more death\" than COVID-19 itself. He declared that the United States would \"soon, be open for business\", in a matter of weeks.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clench |first1=Sam |title=Coronavirus: Donald Trump wants to 'reopen' US economy in weeks, not months |url=https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/health-problems/coronavirus-donald-trump-wants-to-reopen-us-economy-in-weeks-not-months/news-story/42206bca2be90f0e0b02cd69fa0e7323 |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[news.com.au]] |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Bartz |first1=Diane |title=Trump says restrictions will lead to thousands of deaths, cites no evidence |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-trump-restrictions/trump-says-restrictions-will-lead-to-thousands-of-deaths-cites-no-evidence-idUSKBN21B34A |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=[[Reuters]] |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> On March 24, Trump expressed a target of lifting restrictions \"if it's good\" by April 12, the [[Easter]] holiday, for \"packed churches all over our country\".<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite news |last1=Liptak |first1=Kevin |last2=Vazquez |first2=Maegan |last3=Valencia |first3=Nick |last4=Acosta |first4=Jim |title=Trump says he wants the country 'opened up and just raring to go by Easter', despite health experts' warnings |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/24/politics/trump-easter-economy-coronavirus/index.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=[[CNN]] |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> However, a survey of prominent economists by the University of Chicago indicated abandoning an economic lock-down prematurely would do more economic damage than maintaining it.<ref name=\"IGM_Lockdown\"/> Later on March 29, 2020, Trump expressed to maintain social distancing until April 30, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/03/29/coronavirus-latest-news/|title=Live updates: Trump says federal guidance urging social distancing will stay in place through April 30|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nOn March 28, Trump raised the possibility of placing a two-week enforceable quarantine on New York, New Jersey, and \"certain parts of Connecticut\" in order to prevent travel from those places to Florida.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Haring |first1=Bruce |title=President Trump Now Considering Quarantine For NY, NJ And Connecticut |url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/presidenti-trump-considering-quarantine-for-new-york-new-jersey-connecticut-1202895023/ |accessdate=March 28, 2020 |work=Deadline |date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The federal quarantine power is limited to preventing people reasonably believed to be infected with a communicable disease from entering the country or crossing state lines.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Parmet |first1=Wendy E. |last2=Sinha |first2=Michael S. |title=Covid-19\u2014The Law and Limits of Quarantine |journal=The New England Journal of Medicine |date=March 18, 2020 |doi=10.1056/NEJMp2004211 |pmid=32187460 }}</ref> Later that day, following criticism from the three governors, Trump withdrew the quarantine proposal. Instead, the CDC issued a travel advisory advising residents of the three states to \"refrain from non-essential domestic travel for 14 days effective immediately\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus Live Updates: Trump Drops Idea of Quarantining New York Region |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/29/world/coronavirus-news.html?action=click&module=Spotlight&pgtype=Homepage |accessdate=29 March 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=29 March 2020}}</ref> On March 30, Trump said the total number of Americans who would die during the epidemic could be 100,000 or more, following a statement from Fauci that 100,000 to 200,000 Americans could die of the virus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bohn |first1=Kevin  |title=Trump concedes US coronavirus death toll could be 100,000 or more |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/29/politics/trump-deaths-coronavirus/index.html |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=CNN}}</ref>\n\n====Administration officials====\n\n[[File:President Trump, Vice President Pence, and Members of the Coronavirus Task Force Brief the Press (49645645448).jpg|thumb|Vice Admiral [[Jerome Adams]] speaks to the [[White House]] press corps on COVID-19 in March 2020]]\n\nDuring the early stages of the outbreak, Trump administration officials gave mixed assessments of the seriousness and scale of the COVID-19 outbreak. CDC Director Robert Redfield said in late January that \"the immediate risk to the American public is low\", then in late February stated it would be \"prudent to assume this pathogen will be with us for some time to come\". While federal economic policy chief [[Larry Kudlow]] was declaring the COVID-19 spread being contained \"pretty close to airtight\" in late February, Nancy Messonnier (head of the National Center for Immunization and Respiratory Diseases) and [[Anthony Fauci]] (head of the [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]]) warned of the impending community spread of the virus in the United States, with Messonnier stating: \"Disruption to everyday life might be severe\". Around this point, [[Stephen Hahn]], the head of the FDA, warned of national medical supplies being disrupted due to the outbreak. Later in early March, the [[Surgeon General of the United States|U.S. Surgeon General]], Vice Admiral [[Jerome Adams]], declared that \"this is likely going to get worse before it gets better\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Goldberg |first1=Dan |title='It's going to disappear': Trump's changing tone on coronavirus |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/17/how-trump-shifted-his-tone-on-coronavirus-134246 |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=[[Politico]] |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> In March, while giving public briefings from the White House addressing the pandemic, many administration officials and health experts took time to thank Trump for his leadership, as he watched nearby.<ref name=McGrawMarch24/>\n\nIn February 2020, the CDC was notifying the press that it was expecting the infections to spread, and urged local governments, businesses, and schools to develop plans for the outbreak. Among the suggested preparations were canceling mass gatherings, switching to teleworking, and planning for continued business operations in the face of increased absenteeism or disrupted supply chains.<ref name=\"ABC CDC expects spread\">{{cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/coronavirus-live-updates-cdc-warns-americans-significant-disruption/story?id=69190968 |title=CDC warns Americans of 'significant disruption' from coronavirus |last=Winsor |first=Morgan |last2=Schumaker |first2=Erin |website=[[ABC News]] |access-date=February 26, 2020 |last3=Nathanson |first3=Marc |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226000813/https://abcnews.go.com/International/coronavirus-live-updates-cdc-warns-americans-significant-disruption/story?id=69190968 |archive-date=February 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nCDC officials warned that widespread transmission may force large numbers of people to seek hospitalization and other healthcare, which may overload healthcare systems.<ref name=\"CDC COVID-19 Situation Summary\" /> Public health officials stressed that local governments would need assistance from the federal government if there were school and business closures.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |last1=transcript |title=Transcript: Chris Murphy on \"Face the Nation\", March 8, 2020 |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/transcript-chris-murphy-on-face-the-nation-march-8-2020/ |website=Face the Nation |accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Surgeon General Jerome Adams made several media appearances, in which he endorsed social distancing measures and warned the country: \"This week, it's going to get bad{{nbsp}}... we really, really need everyone to stay at home [...] Every single second counts. And right now, there are not enough people out there who are taking this seriously.\"<ref name=OpryskoMarch23>{{cite news |last1=Oprysko |first1=Caitlin |last2=Forgey |first2=Quint |title='Our country wasn't built to be shut down': Trump pushes back against health experts |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/23/trump-coronavirus-lockdown-skepticism-143800 |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===State, territorial, and local response===\n\n{{main|U.S. state and local government response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:Time series of active COVID-19 cases, most affected US states.svg|thumb|[[Semilog plot]] of number of cases in different states, with doubling times annotated]]\n\n===U.S. military response===\n\nAfter mid-March 2020, the [[Federal government of the United States|Federal government]] made a major move to use the [[United States Armed Forces|U.S. military]] to add health care capacity to impacted areas. The [[United States Army Corps of Engineers]] (USACE), under existing statutory authority that comes from authorizations and powers of the [[Federal Emergency Management Agency]] (FEMA), is leasing a large number of buildings nationwide such as hotels, college dormitories, and larger open buildings to immediately convert them into hospital facilities. Some of these facilities will have [[Intensive care unit|ICU]] capability for patients of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic]], while others will serve non-coronavirus patients to allow established hospitals to concentrate on the pandemic. A public briefing of the plan was given by Army General [[Todd T. Semonite|Todd Semonite]] on March 20, 2020. USACE will handle leasing and engineering, with contracts for rapid facility modification and setup issued to local contractors. The plan envisions that the operation of the facilities and the provision of medical staff would be entirely handled by the various [[U.S. state]]s rather than the Federal government.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> One of the early and largest buildings to be converted is the [[Jacob K. Javits Convention Center]] in New York City, which was quickly being transformed into a 2000-bed care facility on March 23, 2020.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-23/n-y-s-javits-center-to-add-2-000-beds-to-system-under-strain N.Y.'s Javits Center to Add 2,000 Beds to System Under Strain] March 23, 2020 ''www.bloomberg.com'', accessed March 26, 2020</ref>\n\nIn addition to the many popup hospitals nationwide, the [[United States Navy]] on March 18 prepared to deploy two [[hospital ship]]s, [[USNS Mercy (T-AH-19)|USNS ''Mercy'']] and [[USNS Comfort (T-AH-20)|USNS ''Comfort'']], to affected areas. The ships will take in non-coronavirus patients transferred from land-based hospitals, so those hospitals can concentrate on virus cases.<ref name=ships>{{Cite web|url=https://www.defense.gov/Explore/News/Article/Article/2116862/hospital-ships-other-dod-assets-prepare-for-coronavirus-response/|title=Hospital Ships, Other DOD Assets Prepare for Coronavirus Response|website=U.S. Department of Defense|language=en-US|access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> On March 22, Trump announced that the ''Comfort'' would go to the East Coast and the ''Mercy'' to the West Coast. He added the government may be using cruise ships.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/remarks-president-trump-vice-president-pence-members-coronavirus-task-force-press-briefing-8/|title=Remarks by President Trump, Vice President Pence, and Members of the Coronavirus Task Force in Press Briefing|website=The White House|language=en-US|access-date=March 24, 2020 }}</ref> The ''Mercy'' arrived in Los Angeles on March 27,<ref name = mercyarrives>{{cite news|url=https://www.navytimes.com/news/coronavirus/2020/03/27/usns-mercy-arrives-in-los-angeles-to-support-covid-19-response/|title=USNS Mercy arrives in Los Angeles to support Covid-19 response|last=Correll|first=Diana Stancy|date=27 March 2020|work=Navy Times|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> and the ''Comfort'' arrived in New York City on March 30.<ref name=comfortarrives>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/usns-comfort-arrives-in-nyc-monday-to-help-hospital-with-non-coronavirus-patients/2350317/|title=Crowds Greet USNS Comfort in NYC Monday; Ship to Help Hospitals With Non-Coronavirus Patients|accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United States Army]] also dispatched 300 soldiers of the 627th Hospital Center from [[Fort Carson]], [[Colorado]] to [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]] and 600 from [[Fort Campbell]]'s 531st Hospital Center and [[Fort Hood]]'s 9th Hospital Center to New York City to assist emergency medical facilities overrun with coronavirus patients. The soldiers are expected to construct field hospitals at [[CenturyLink Field]] in Seattle and Javits Convention Center in NYC to treat non-COVID-19 patients, which freed up local hospitals to deal only with those who contracted the virus.<ref>{{cite news|last=Johnson|first=Graham|title=Army to bring field hospital to CenturyLink Field Event Center|url=https://www.kiro7.com/news/local/centurylink-field-being-scouted-possible-field-hospital/34LHOG5V2FCBLOJMP4GIYHXKJE/|accessdate=March 29, 2020|work=KIRO-TV|date=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Dickstein|first=Corey|title=Army field hospital is expected to be caring for patients in NYC by Monday |url=https://www.stripes.com/news/us/army-field-hospital-is-expected-to-be-caring-for-patients-in-nyc-by-monday-1.623864 |accessdate=March 29, 2020|work=Stars and Stripes|date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Economic impact==\n\nEconomic analysts revised their forecasts downward going into March, with [[Goldman Sachs]] estimating on March 20 that the economy could contract by as much as 24% on an annualized basis during the second quarter of 2020, following their 5% decline estimate just four days earlier. Some analysts estimated a recession had already begun.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/dire-forecast-us-economy-could-tank-4-in-the-second-quarter-as-nation-shuts-down-to-fight-coronavirus-2020-03-12|title=Dire forecast: U.S. economy could tank 4% in the second quarter as nation shuts down to fight coronavirus|first=Jeffry|last=Bartash|website=MarketWatch}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/story/2020-03-16/us-economic-recession-coronavirus-ucla-anderson-forecast|title=US economy is now in recession, UCLA Anderson Forecast says|first1=Laurence|last1=Darmiento|url-access=subscription|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=March 16, 2020|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/16/economy/global-recession-coronavirus/index.html|title=The global coronavirus recession is beginning|first1=Julia|last1=Horowitz|date=March 16, 2020|access-date=March 22, 2020|website=cnn.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-jpmorgan-usa/jp-morgan-slashes-forecast-for-u-s-gdp-sees-14-second-quarter-drop-idUSKBN2153HU?il=0|title=JP Morgan economist says U.S. GDP could drop 14% in second-quarter|first1=Ann|last1=Saphir|date=March 18, 2020|access-date=March 22, 2020|publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.barrons.com/articles/u-s-economy-could-contract-by-24-next-quarter-goldman-sachs-says-51584713292|title=The U.S. Economy Could Contract by 24% Next Quarter, Goldman Sachs Says|first1=Alexandra|last1=Scaggs|date=March 20, 2020|access-date=March 22, 2020|website=barrons.com}}</ref>{{citation overkill|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Domestic travel===\n\n{{external media|float=right|video1=[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Qepa8bS72S8 CNBC interview with Southwest CEO Gary Kelly on March 5], YouTube video|video2=[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HRFGB7VMg0k KOMO: Coronavirus Impact on Air Travel], YouTube video}}\n\nIn mid-March, most major American and foreign airlines began cutting back on domestic and international flights as a result of the sudden drop in travel demand from the pandemic and subsequent travel bans. They have phased out routes and were making frequent schedule updates.<ref name=nyt-airlines>[https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/16/travel/international-airlines-service-cuts-coronavirus.html \"Airlines Cut International Flights in Response to the Pandemic\"], ''New York Times'', March 17, 2020</ref><ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2020/03/12/delta-command-center-coronavirus/?arc404=true \"Inside Delta's command center the week the coronavirus devastated the airline industry\"], ''The Washington Post'', March 13, 2020</ref>\n\nThe outbreak produced occasional disruptions to [[air traffic control]] with [[area control center]]s in New York and Indianapolis, and airport towers at [[Midway International Airport]] in Chicago and [[McCarran International Airport]] in Las Vegas evacuated for sterilization after at least one person who had been in each tested positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/32680/americas-air-traffic-control-system-is-suffering-crippling-shutdowns-due-to-covid-19|title=America's Air Traffic Control System Is Suffering Crippling Shutdowns Due To COVID-19|first=Stephen|last=Walker|website=The Drive|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n[[File:President Trump and the Vice President meet with Airline CEOs about the Coronavirus (49618513938).jpg|thumb|President Trump meeting with Airline CEOs discussing the COVID-19's impact on the [[Air transportation in the United States|travel industry]] on March 4, 2020]]\n\nOn March 14, [[Amtrak]] reduced its service between Washington and Boston as the COVID-19 outbreak drastically decreased travel demand. It faced steep revenue losses during the crisis. It also asked noncritical employees \"to take time off on an unpaid basis\".<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/transportation/2020/03/14/amtrak-cuts-more-trains-coronavirus-impacts-travel-demand/ \"Amtrak cuts more trains as coronavirus lessens demand\"], ''Washington Post'', March 14, 2020</ref> By the following week, New York's subways, usually the nation's busiest, were running mostly empty, which had the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] using $1 billion from its line of credit to stay afloat.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/in-a-week-the-coronavirus-razed-us-transit-and-rail-systems/2020/03/22/ca58a88a-6a21-11ea-9923-57073adce27c_story.html \"In a week, the coronavirus razed U.S. transit and rail systems\"], ''Washington Post'', March 22, 2020</ref>\n\nThe lobbying group for the airline industry, [[Airlines for America|Airlines for America (A4A)]], on March 16 called for a $50 billion subsidy, including $4 billion for cargo services.<ref>[https://thehill.com/business-a-lobbying/business-a-lobbying/487820-airline-industry-calls-for-25b-in-assistance-for Airline industry calls for $50B in assistance] The Hill, March 16, 2020</ref> [[CNBC]] reports that airlines are preparing for a ban on domestic flights after President Trump said on March 14 that he is considering travel curbs and acting DHS Secretary [[Chad Wolf]] said all options remained on the table when asked about a possible ban, the first since September 11, 2001. United Airlines said they expected a drop of $1.5&nbsp;billion in March revenue, American Airlines said they expected to decrease domestic capacity by 20% in April and 30% in May, and Delta Air Lines told employees it would cut capacity by 40%.<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/16/coronavirus-makes-airlines-consider-chances-for-a-halt-to-us-flights.html Coronavirus forces airlines to consider a once unthinkable possibility\u2014halting U.S. flights] by Leslie Josephs, CNBC, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\nSeveral of the largest [[mass transit]] operators in the U.S. have reduced service in response to lower demand caused by work from home policies and self-quarantines. The loss of fares and [[sales tax]], a common source of operating revenue, is predicted to cause long-term effects on transit expansion and maintenance.<ref>{{cite news |last=Taylor |first=Kate |date=March 17, 2020 |title=No Bus Service. Crowded Trains. Transit Systems Struggle With the Virus. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/us/coronavirus-buses-trains-detroit-boston.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> The [[American Public Transportation Association]] issued a request for $13 billion in emergency funding from the federal government to cover lost revenue and other expenses incurred by the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lindblom |first1=Mike |last2=Groover |first2=Heidi |date=March 19, 2020 |title=Sound Transit, Metro facing big drops in funding as coronavirus downturn takes hold |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/transportation/sound-transit-metro-facing-big-drops-in-funding-as-coronavirus-downturn-takes-hold/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> Many localities reported an increase in [[bicycling]] as residents sought socially distant means of getting around.<ref name=\"GristBikes\">{{cite news |last1=Anderson |first1=L.V. |title=Coronavirus has caused a bicycling boom in New York City |url=https://grist.org/climate/coronavirus-has-caused-a-bicycling-boom-in-new-york-city/ |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=Grist |date=March 13, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Financial market impacts===\n\n{{see also|Financial impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:March 3, 2020 FOMC Press Conference NZ73153 (49614546592).jpg|thumb|Federal Reserve chairman [[Jerome Powell]] announces a 50 basis point (0.5% percentage point) interest rate cut on March 3, 2020 in light of \"evolving risks to economic activity\" from the coronavirus.]]\n\nOn February 27, 2020, the [[Dow Jones Industrial Average]] (DJIA) dropped 1,191 points, the [[List of largest daily changes in the Dow Jones Industrial Average|largest single-day point drop]] in the index's history at the time; some attributed the drop to anxiety about the epidemic.<ref name=\"USA Today Dow Feb 27\">{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2020/02/27/dow-markets-plunge-correction-coronavirus/4889977002/ |title=Dow plunges 1,191 points, its biggest one-day point drop, as coronavirus fears escalate |last=Menton |first=Jessica |website=[[USA Today]] |access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> The same day, the S&P 500 logged a 4.4% decline.<ref name=\"CNBC SP 500 Feb 27\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/27/this-is-the-fastest-stock-market-correction-in-history.html |title=It took stocks only six days to fall into correction, the fastest drop in history |last=Li |first=Yun |publisher=[[CNBC]] |access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> Since then, the record has been beaten five more times during the outbreak on March{{nbsp}}9 (\u22122,013), March 11 (\u22121,465), March 12 (\u22122,353), and finally setting the current record for most points lost in a single day by losing 2,997 points on March 16. It once again fell another 1,338 points on March 18. On March 13, the stock market rebounded for the single largest one-day point gain in the market's history by gaining 1,985 points after Trump declared a state of national emergency to free up resources to combat the virus.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Winck |first1=Ben |title=Live updates: Dow rebounds sharply a day after index tanked its most since 1987 on coronavirus worries |url=https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/stock-market-news-today-index-reaction-coronavirus-global-stimulus-measures-2020-3-1028994772 |website=Markets Insider |publisher=Insider |accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Dow Jones Industrial Average |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/investing/index/djia |website=MarketWatch |publisher=MarketWatch |accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref> The six business days it took for the [[S&P 500 Index]] to drop 10% (from February 20 to 27) \"marked the quickest 10% decline from an all-time high in the index's history\".<ref name=\"CNBC SP 500 Feb 27\" /> From January 21 to March 1, the DJIA dropped more than 3,500 points, equating to roughly a 13% decrease.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/28/the-dow-just-lost-12percent-in-one-week-heres-why-and-what-likely-happens-next.html |title=The Dow lost 12% in one week. Here's why and what likely happens next |last=Imbert |first=Fred |website=CNBC\u2014Markets |publisher=CNBC |access-date=March 2, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302072632/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/28/the-dow-just-lost-12percent-in-one-week-heres-why-and-what-likely-happens-next.html |archive-date=March 2, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/investing/index/djia |title=Dow Jones Industrial Average\u2014Overview |website=MarketWatch |publisher=MarketWatch |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206132349/https://www.marketwatch.com/investing/index/djia |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nStock index [[futures contract|futures]] declined sharply during Trump's March 11 address,<ref>{{cite web | title=Are you a robot? | website=Bloomberg | date=March 12, 2020 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-12/u-s-index-futures-fall-after-trump-addresses-nation-k7o2ok5g | access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> and the [[Dow Jones Industrial Average|Dow Jones]] declined 10% the following day\u2014the largest daily decline since [[Black Monday]] in 1987\u2014despite the Federal Reserve also announcing it would inject $1.5 trillion into money markets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/us-policy/2020/03/12/markets-stocks-today-coronavirus/|title=U.S. stock market suffers worst crash since 1987, as Americans wake up to a new normal of life|website=Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nBy March 18, investors were shunning even assets considered safe havens during economic crises, such as government bonds and gold, moving into cash positions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/markets-enter-new-phasewhere-cash-is-all-that-matters-11584546863|title=Markets Enter New Phase\u2014Where Cash Is All That Matters|first=Paul J.|last=Davies|date=March 18, 2020|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref> By March 20, the [[Dow Jones Industrial Average]] was below the level when President Trump was inaugurated on January 20, 2017, having fallen 35% from its February peak.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/20/business/coronavirus-trump-stock-market.html |title=Stock market's gain under Trump vanishes |website=The New York Times |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe markets rallied between March 23 and 26, with the Dow having its best three-day gain since 1931. On March 27, the Dow fell 3.5% and the S&P 500 fell 3.2%. The Nasdaq Index also fell. Boeing fell 10%, while Exxon and Disney each fell 6%.<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/26/stock-market-futures-open-to-close-news.html Dow tumbles more than 700 points following a massive 3-day bounce] by Fred Imbert, CNBC, March 26, 2020</ref>\n\n===Employment effects===\n\nThe number of persons filing for [[unemployment insurance]] increased from 211,000 the week ending March 7, to 281,000 for the week ending March 14, an increase of 70,000 or 33%, the largest percent increase since 1992.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lite.cnn.com/en/article/h_95e07e22e32b448a3618b8e935c3a3bc|title=CNN\u2014Breaking News, Latest News and Videos|website=lite.cnn.com}}</ref> Just part way through the following week, 15 states had reported nearly 630,000 claims.<ref>{{cite news |title=Initial claims|url=https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/ICSA |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=fred.stlousfed.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Wolfers |first1=Justin |last2=Bui |first2=Quoctrung |title=The Staggering Rise in Jobless Claims This Week|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/03/19/upshot/coronavirus-jobless-claims-states.html|accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> [[Goldman Sachs]] forecast that more than two million people would file the week of March 21, an unprecedented number.<ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. jobless claims could exceed 2 million, Goldman Says|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-20/u-s-weekly-jobless-claims-could-exceed-2-million-goldman-says|accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=Bloomberg.com}}</ref> Goldman also forecast that the unemployment rate could rise towards nine percent over the second and third quarters, with much depending on the specifics of government stimulus plans.<ref>{{cite news |title=The U.S. Economy Could Contract by 24% Next Quarter, Goldman Sachs Says|url=https://www.barrons.com/articles/in-the-hunt-for-cash-here-are-5-companies-with-plenty-of-it-51584694800|accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=Barrons.com}}</ref> On March 26, the Labor Department reported a record number of unemployment claims: 3.28 million (previously 695 thousand in October 1982).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/26/weekly-jobless-claims.html|title=Jobless claims soar past 3 million to record|last=Cox|first=Jeff|date=March 26, 2020|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Restaurant industry===\n\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the restaurant industry in the United States}}\n[[File:Graeter's coronavirus sign 24 March 2020.jpg|alt=Signs read \"We're open, carryout & order pickup only at this time. Get it delivered.\" and \"Please keep social distancing in mind. Keep six feet apart from one another. Please take your order to go once received. Thank you for helping us comply with govermental health recommedations.\"|thumb|Signage on a restaurant door during COVID-19 closings]]\n\nThe 2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic impacted the restaurant industry worldwide via government closures, resulting in layoffs of workers and loss of income for restaurants and owners.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nThe U.S. restaurant industry was projected to have $899 billion in sales for 2020 by the [[National Restaurant Association]], the main trade association for the industry in the United States.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/cincinnati/news/2020/03/20/cincinnati-restaurants-ask-feds-for-coronavirus.html|title=Cincinnati restaurants ask feds for coronavirus bailout|last=Brownfield|first=Andy|date=March 20, 2020|website=login.research.cincinnatilibrary.org|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> The industry as a whole as of February 2020 employed more than 15 million people, representing 10% of the workforce directly.<ref name=\":02\" /> It indirectly employed close to another 10% when dependent businesses such as food producers, trucking, and delivery services were factored in, according to Ohio restaurateur Britney Ruby Miller.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nOn March 15, Ohio Governor [[Mike DeWine]] and Ohio Health Department director [[Amy Acton]] ordered the closure of all bars and restaurants to help slow the spread of the virus, saying the government \"encouraged restaurants to offer carryout or delivery service, but they would not be allowed to have people congregating in the businesses.\"<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/487684-ohio-closing-all-bars-restaurants-in-response-to-coronavirus|title=Illinois, Ohio closing all bars, restaurants in response to coronavirus|last=Conradis|first=Brandon|date=March 15, 2020|website=thehill.com}}</ref><ref name=\":02\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dispatch.com/news/20200315/coronavirus-governor-orders-ohio-bars-restaurants-to-shut-down|title=Coronavirus: Governor orders Ohio bars, restaurants to shut down|date=March 15, 2020|publisher=The Columbus Dispatch|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316153943/https://www.dispatch.com/news/20200315/coronavirus-governor-orders-ohio-bars-restaurants-to-shut-down|archive-date=March 16, 2020|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> The next day, Illinois, New York, New Jersey, and Maryland followed suit.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=Witte|first=Griff|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/coronavirus-ohio-dewine-outbreak/2020/03/16/9bde6b1e-67b2-11ea-9923-57073adce27c_story.html|title=Ohio Gov. Mike DeWine's coronavirus response has become a national guide to the crisis|date=March 16, 2020|work=Washington Post|access-date=March 22, 2020|last2=Zezima|first2=Katie}}</ref>\n\nGroups of restaurateurs in New York City and Cincinnati called on governments to provide help to the nation's small and independent restaurants.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/changing-america/respect/accessibility/488670-how-nycs-restaurant-industry-is-surviving-amid|title=How NYC's restaurant industry is surviving amid coronavirus closures|last=Somvichian-Clausen|first=Austa|date=March 20, 2020|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":02\" /> On March 19 the New York group called for state governments to issue orders for rent abatements, suspension of sales and payroll taxes, and a full shutdown so business interruption insurance coverage would be triggered.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://ny.eater.com/2020/3/19/21187117/momofuku-major-food-group-starr-restaurants-relief-coronavirus-nyc|title=NYC's Top Restaurant Groups Band Together to Petition for Government Relief|last=Adams|first=Erika|date=March 19, 2020|website=Eater NY|language=en|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> On March 20 the Cincinnati group called on the federal government to provide a $225 billion bailout to the restaurant industry.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nSeveral restaurant chains altered their operating procedures to prevent the spread of the virus, including removing seating, restricting the use of condiments, and switching to [[mobile payment]] systems. Many restaurants opted to close their dining rooms and instead switch to solely [[take-out]] food service to comply with [[physical distancing]] recommendations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/food/2020/03/15/starbucks-coronavirus-changes-mobile-orders-drive-thru-closing-locations/5055192002/|title=Starbucks closing some locations and moving to a 'to go' model at other stores due to coronavirus|author=Tyko, Kelly|date=March 15, 2020|work=USA Today|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Retail===\n\n[[File:Best Buy Line I (49674924422).jpg|thumb|[[Best Buy]] was only letting a limited number of people into their Union Square store in [[New York City]], March 18, 2020]]\n\nA number of retailers, particularly grocery stores, reduced their opening hours to allow additional time to restock and deep-clean their stores.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2020/03/14/coronavirus-store-closings-hour-changes/5051282002/ |title=Stores cutting hours or closing because of coronavirus: Walmart, Apple, Nike, Albertsons, Trader Joe's, more |author=Tyko, Kelly |work=USA Today |date=March 14, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref> Major stores such as [[Walmart]], [[Apple Inc.|Apple]], [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]], [[Albertson's]], and [[Trader Joe's]] also shortened their hours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2020/03/14/coronavirus-store-closings-hour-changes/5051282002/|title=Stores cutting hours or closing because of coronavirus: Walmart, Apple, Nike, Albertsons, Trader Joe's, more|last=Tyko|first=Kelly|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>[https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20200318005807/en/ Latest Walmart Store Changes to Support Associates and Customers] Business Wire</ref> Some grocery store chains, including [[Stop & Shop]] and [[Dollar General]], devoted a portion of their operating hours to serve only senior citizens.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2020/03/16/coronavirus-seniors-dollar-general-dedicates-hour-senior-shoppers/5065594002/ |title=Dollar General cuts store hours, dedicates hour to senior shoppers during coronavirus pandemic |author=Tyko, Kelly |work=USA Today |date=March 16, 2020 |accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boston.com/food/food/2020/03/16/stop-shop-gives-customers-over-60-their-own-shopping-hours |title=Stop & Shop gives customers over 60 their own shopping hours |author=Pickell, Jack |work=The Boston Globe |date=March 16, 2020 |accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref> Many grocery stores and pharmacies began installing plexiglass sneeze guards at register areas to protect cashiers and pharmacists, and adding markers six feet apart at checkout lines to encourage customers to maintain physical distance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/coronavirus-leads-grocers-install-plexiglass-014739290.html|title=Coronavirus leads Walmart, other grocers to install plexiglass to protect employees, customers|website=finance.yahoo.com|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\nTo prevent hoarding, many supermarkets and retailers placed limits on certain products such as toilet paper, hand sanitizer, over-the-counter medication, and cleaning supplies.<ref name=\"hoarding\">{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/15/trump-no-hoarding-coronavirus-grocery-stores-130771 |title=Trump urges no hoarding as coronavirus panic strains grocery stores |author=McCrimmon, Ryan |work=Politico |date=March 15, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref> However, the [[Food Marketing Institute]] announced that its supply chain was not strained and all products would be available in the future.<ref name=\"hoarding\"/> Major retail chains started hiring tens of thousands of employees to keep up with demand, including Walmart (150,000), [[CVS Pharmacy]] (50,000), Dollar General (50,000), and [[7 Eleven]] (20,000).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alexandrasternlicht/2020/03/20/whos-hiring-in-the-coronavirus-economy-2736-increase-for-warehouse-handler-7-eleven-adds-20000-postings-more/|title=Updated: Instacart To Hire 300,000 New Shoppers, CVS And Dollar General Add 50,000 Jobs Each\u2014Who's Hiring In Coronavirus Economy|first=Alexandra|last=Sternlicht|website=Forbes|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\nA daily senior shopping hour, checkout line distancing markers, hand washing and sanitizer for employees, disinfecting wipes for customers to use on carts, and a ban on reusable bags became mandatory in Massachusetts on March 25.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mass.gov/doc/grocery-and-pharmacy-store-order/download|title=Order of the Commissioner of Public Health, March 25 2020|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Shipping facilities===\n\nSince consumers were increasingly relying on online retailers, [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] planned to hire another 100,000 warehouse and delivery workers and raise wages $2 per hour through April. They also reported shortages of certain household staples.<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/16/amazon-to-hire-100000-warehouse-and-delivery-workers.html Amazon to hire 100,000 more workers and give raises to current staff to deal with coronavirus demands] by Annie Palmer, CNBC, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\nA March 21 article in the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' reported that employees at [[United Parcel Service|UPS]], [[FedEx]], and [[XPO Logistics|XPO]] often have been pressured not to take time off, even with symptoms such as fever and cough consistent with coronavirus. Public health authorities state that the risk is relatively low to customers receiving packages, in part because coronavirus does not live for very long on cardboard, but it most certainly is a danger for employees on crowded conveyor belts.<ref>[https://www.chicagotribune.com/coronavirus/ct-nw-nyt-coronavirus-package-delivery-employees-sick-20200321-kpijftkmlba3zodkmvtmhxojs4-story.html 'Terrified' package delivery employees are going to work sick], Chicago Tribune (New York Times), March 21, 2020.</ref>\n\nAt its warehouses, [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] has stopped exit screenings, as well as group meetings at the beginning of shifts, and has staggered shift times and break times. The company also announced it would provide up to two weeks of pay to all employees diagnosed with coronavirus or placed into quarantine, but presumably not for employees who merely have symptoms of fever and cough.<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/21/jeff-bezos-memo-about-coronavirus-safety-at-amazon-warehouses.html?&qsearchterm=Read%20the%20memo%20Jeff%20Bezos%20sent%20to%20Amazon%20employees%20about%20coronavirus%20safety%20at%20warehouses Read the memo Jeff Bezos sent to Amazon employees about coronavirus safety at warehouses], CNBC, updated March 22, 2020.</ref>  Amazon workers complained paid medical leave was difficult to obtain because of limited access to COVID-19 testing, and some petitioned the company to extend paid leave to elderly and medically vulnerable workers without a positive test.<ref name=\"kentucky\">[https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/26/822045229/amazon-closes-kentucky-warehouse-after-workers-test-positive Amazon Closes Kentucky Warehouse After Workers Test Positive]</ref> As small numbers of workers have tested positive for COVID-19, various Amazon warehouses have closed for sanitization, including one in Kentucky for several days.<ref name=\"kentucky\" /> Amazon workers at the [[Staten Island]] warehouse and some [[Instacart]] workers nationwide separately announced strikes for March 30, demanding access to personal protective equipment, better sick pay, hazard pay for Instacart orders, and a longer closure of the Staten Island warehouse for cleaning.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/2020/03/30/823767492/amazon-instacart-grocery-delivery-workers-strike-for-coronavirus-protection-and-]</ref>\n\n===Production of emergency supplies===\n\nIn response to shortages, some alcoholic beverage facilities started manufacturing and distributing alcohol-based [[hand sanitizer]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/21/817976872/white-house-to-give-an-update-on-coronavirus-tests-response|title=Pence Tests Negative For COVID-19; 'Hundreds Of Millions' Of Face Masks In Production|website=NPR.org|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> [[General Motors]] opened its manufacturing, logistics, and purchasing infrastructure for use by Ventec, a manufacturer of medical ventilators.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedrive.com/news/32691/general-motors-becomes-first-us-automaker-to-aid-in-ventilator-production-ramp-up|title=General Motors Becomes First US Automaker Committed to Ventilator Production Ramp-Up|first=James|last=Gilboy|website=The Drive|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> As medical mask manufacturers hired hundreds of new workers and increased output,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/23/metro/honeywell-will-start-making-n95-face-masks-its-smithfield-ri-plant-adding-500-jobs/|title=Honeywell will start making N95 face masks at its Smithfield, R.I., plant, adding 500 jobs\u2014The Boston Globe|website=BostonGlobe.com|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> in response to urgent requests from hospital workers, volunteers with home sewing machines started producing thousands of non-medical masks that can be sterilized and re-used. Fabric was bought privately or donated by [[Joann Fabrics]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/22/metro/mask-making-projects-are-popping-all-over-crafters-mobilize-against-coronavirus/|title=Mask-making projects are popping all over as crafters mobilize against coronavirus\u2014The Boston Globe|website=BostonGlobe.com|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The CDC recommended the use of homemade masks (preferably in combination with a full-face splash shield) only as a \"last resort\" when no other respiratory protective technologies were available, including reused professional masks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/hcp/ppe-strategy/face-masks.html|title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19)|date=February 11, 2020|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome U.S. officials and commentators criticized the [[outsourcing]] of critical materials\u2014like the production of essential medical supplies\u2014to China.<ref>{{cite news |title=Break with China? Top Trump aide eyes an opening with coronavirus |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/02/26/trump-china-trade-coronavirus-117531 |work=Politico |date=26 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Tucker Carlson: Spread of coronavirus is revealing a 'terrifying situation' |url=https://www.foxnews.com/media/tucker-carlson-coronavirus-pandemic-terrifying-situation-china-drugs |work=Fox News |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Other financial effects===\n\n[[File:President Trump Meets with Banking Leaders (49649253478).jpg|thumb|President Trump meeting with representatives of the [[Banking in the United States|banking industry]] on March 11, 2020]]\n\nIn February 2020, the American companies [[Apple Inc.]] and [[Microsoft]] began lowering expectations for revenue because of supply chain disruptions in China caused by the virus.<ref name=\"Forbes MSFT\">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/waynerash/2020/02/27/microsoft-warning-is-a-harbinger-of-coronavirus-impact-on-business-and-the-economy/ |title=Microsoft Warning Is A Harbinger Of Coronavirus Impact On Business and the Economy |last=Rash |first=Wayne |website=[[Forbes]] |access-date=February 28, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228072030/https://www.forbes.com/sites/waynerash/2020/02/27/microsoft-warning-is-a-harbinger-of-coronavirus-impact-on-business-and-the-economy/#628fd0f07449 |archive-date=February 28, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In a February 27 note to clients, [[Goldman Sachs]] said it expects no earnings growth for U.S. companies in 2020 as a result of the virus, at a time when the consensus forecast of Wall Street expected \"earnings to climb 7%\".<ref name=\"CNBC Goldman\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/27/goldman-sees-zero-earnings-growth-for-us-companies-this-year-because-of-coronavirus.html |title=Goldman sees zero earnings growth for US companies this year because of coronavirus |last=Fitzgerald |first=Maggie |publisher=[[CNBC]] |access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> On March 20, 2020 as part of an [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission|SEC]] filing, [[AT&T]] cancelled all [[Share repurchase|stock buyback]] plans included a plan to repurchase stock worth $4 billion during the second quarter. The reasons AT&T gave for the cancellation was to invest the money into its networks and in taking care of its employees during the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2020/biz/news/att-coronavirus-material-cancels-stock-buyback-plan-1203540168/ |title=AT&T Warns Coronavirus Financial Impact 'Could Be Material', Nixes $4 Billion Stock-Buyback Plan |last=Spangler|first=Todd |date=March 20, 2020 |website=Variety |language=en |access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe pandemic, along with the resultant [[2020 stock market crash|stock market crash]] and other impacts, has led to increased discussion of a recession in the United States.<ref name=\"USATodayRecession\">{{cite news |title=It may feel like 2008 all over again, but here's how the coronavirus crisis is different |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2020/03/11/recession-heres-how-coronavirus-crises-different-2008/5012228002/ |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=[[USA Today]] |date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312201200/https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2020/03/11/recession-heres-how-coronavirus-crises-different-2008/5012228002/ |archive-date=March 12, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Experts differ on whether a recession will actually take place, with some saying it's not inevitable while others say the country may already be in a recession.<ref name=\"USATodayRecession\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Cox |first1=Jeff |title=Economist Alan Blinder says the US is probably already in recession |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/11/economist-alan-blinder-says-the-us-is-probably-already-in-recession.html |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |publisher=[[CNBC]] |date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312181138/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/11/economist-alan-blinder-says-the-us-is-probably-already-in-recession.html |archive-date=March 12, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Of the economists surveyed in March by the [[University of Chicago]] at multiple U.S. universities, 51% agreed or strongly agreed there would be a \"major\" recession caused by COVID-19, while 31% were uncertain or disagreed.<ref>{{cite news |title=IGM Economic Experts Panel Coronavirus |url=http://www.igmchicago.org/igm-economic-experts-panel |accessdate=March 16, 2020|date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the economic damage caused by the pandemic, some economists have advocated for financial support from the government for individual Americans and for banks and businesses.<ref name=\"NYT_Golden\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/12/opinion/coronavirus-economy.html?action=click&module=Opinion&pgtype=Homepage|title=Can We Stop a Coronavirus Recession?|last=Golden |first=Ian|website=The New York Times|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Mankiw_Blog\">{{cite web |url=http://gregmankiw.blogspot.com/2020/03/thoughts-on-pandemic.html|title=Thoughts on the Pandemic|last=Mankiw|first=Greg|website=gregmankiw.blogstpot.com|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> Others have objected to intervention by the government on the grounds that it would alter the role of the [[Federal Reserve]] and enshrine [[moral hazard]] as a defining market principle.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Petrou |first1=Karen |title=Federal Reserve should not try to fight the coronavirus |url=https://www.ft.com/content/d3bf5890-5ba0-11ea-b0ab-339c2307bcd4 |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |work=[[Financial Times]] |date=March 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Telemedicine===\n\nThe COVID-19 pandemic has led to a sharp increase in the utilization of [[telemedicine|telemedical services]] in the United States, specifically for COVID-19 screening and triage.<ref name=\"Telemedicine demand\">{{cite web |author1=Leah Rosenbaum |title=The Coronavirus Has Created A Surge Of Telemedicine Demand. GoodRx Now Lets Consumers Compare Services |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/leahrosenbaum/2020/03/26/the-coronavirus-has-created-a-surge-of-telemedicine-demand-goodrx-now-lets-consumers-compare-services/#6e37a72b47f5 |publisher=Forbes |accessdate=29 March 2020 |date=26 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Telemedicine surge + Ro's service\">{{cite web |author1=Lauren Clason |title=Telehealth visits surge along with coronavirus cases |url=https://www.rollcall.com/2020/03/24/telehealth-visits-balloon-along-with-coronavirus-cases/ |website=Roll Call |accessdate=29 March 2020 |language=en |date=24 March 2020}}</ref> On March 26, 2020, [[GoodRx]] launched a telemedicine price comparison platform<ref name=\"GoodRx telemedicine price comparison platform\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) Assessments |url=https://www.goodrx.com/treatment/coronavirus |publisher=GoodRx |accessdate=29 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> that lists the prices of COVID-19 assessments by telemedicine provider and state.<ref name=\"Telemedicine demand\" /> {{As of|2020|3|29|df=US}}, three companies are offering free telemedical screenings for COVID-19 in the United States: [[K Health]] (routed through an AI [[chatbot]]), [[Ro (company)|Ro]] (routed through an AI chatbot), and GoodRx (offered through its HeyDoctor platform).<ref name=\"GoodRx telemedicine price comparison platform\" /><ref name=\"Free COVID-19 providers\">{{cite web |author1=Leah Rosenbaum |title=Worried That You Have Coronavirus? Here's How To See A Doctor For Free In Your Home |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/leahrosenbaum/2020/03/18/worried-that-you-have-coronavirus-heres-how-to-see-a-doctor-for-free-in-your-home/ |publisher=Forbes |accessdate=29 March 2020 |language=en |date=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Telemedicine surge + Ro's service\" /><ref name=\"Ro Chatbot\">{{cite web |author1=Leah Rosenbaum |title=Worried About Coronavirus? Now You Can Text Message A Chatbot With Questions |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/leahrosenbaum/2020/03/12/worried-about-coronavirus-now-you-can-text-message-a-chatbot-with-questions/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=29 March 2020 |language=en |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>{{citation overkill|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Timing of removing economic lockdowns===\n\nOn March 24, Trump expressed a target of lifting restrictions \"if it's good\" by April 12, the [[Easter]] holiday, for \"packed churches all over our country\".<ref name=\"auto2\"/> However, a survey of prominent economists by the [[University of Chicago]] indicated abandoning an economic lock-down prematurely would do more economic damage than maintaining it.<ref name=\"IGM_Lockdown\">{{cite news |title=IGM Economic Experts Panel-Policy for the COVID-19 Crisis|url=http://www.igmchicago.org/surveys/policy-for-the-covid-19-crisis/|accessdate=March 29, 2020|work=igmchicago.org |date=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The ''New York Times'' reported on March 24 that: \"There is, however, a widespread consensus among economists and public health experts that lifting the restrictions would impose huge costs in additional lives lost to the virus\u2014and deliver little lasting benefit to the economy.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Shutdown Spotlights Economic Cost of Saving Lives|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/24/business/economy/coronavirus-economy.html|work=nytimes.com |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> [[Bill Gates]] said:  \"It's very tough to say to people, 'Hey keep going to restaurants, go buy new houses, ignore that pile of bodies over in the corner, we want you to keep spending because there's some politician that thinks GDP growth is what counts'{{nbsp}}... It's hard to tell people during an epidemic{{nbsp}}... that they should go about things knowing their activity is spreading this disease.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Bill Gates says the US missed its chance to avoid coronavirus shutdown and businesses should stay closed|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/24/bill-gates-us-missed-its-chance-to-avoid-coronavirus-shutdown.html|work=cnbc.com |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>  On March 29, Trump extended the federal social distancing recommendations until the end of April.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/2020/03/30/822448199/how-15-days-became-45-trump-extends-guidelines-to-slow-coronavirus How 15 Days Became 45: Trump Extends Guidelines To Slow Coronavirus]</ref>\n\n===Criticism of proposed remedies===\n\nNobel Prize-winning economist [[Joseph Stiglitz]] says Congress is not ready to send out checks now (to individuals) and then if the crisis goes on another four weeks, or six weeks, to send out a second batch of checks. He states the U.S. economy was not in great shape to begin with, for example, with overall growth for March 2020 expected to be less than 2%. The main problem will be that people can't go to work because of fear of the virus. And regarding a welfare safety net, he writes, \"America has the weakest social protection of almost any of the advanced countries and so we're having to patch in a kind of social protection system on the fly and it's going to be really hard and that means the recovery is going to be very difficult.\"<ref>[https://wcbs880.radio.com/articles/news/stiglitz-discusses-possible-economic-fallout-of-coronavirus Nobel Prize-Winning Economist Fears Coronavirus Impacts Will Be Worse Than 1929 Fallout], WCBS News Radio, interview with Steve Scott, March 24, 2020.</ref>\n\n==Social impacts==\n\nIn order to minimize the spread of infection, public health officials and political figures have initiated steps to isolate infected patients, impose quarantines, and recommend or require physical distancing during group activities, including the closing of schools, retail stores, workplaces, sports events, and leisure activities such as dining and movies.\n\n===Lockdowns===\n\n{{main|U.S. state and local government response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:COVID-19 outbreak USA stay-at-home order county map.svg|thumb|right|300px|States, territories, and counties that issued a [[stay-at-home order]]:\n{{legend|#045a8d|Came into effect between March 15 and 21}}\n{{legend|#2b8cbe|Came into effect between March 22 and 28}}\n{{legend|#74a9cf|Came into effect between March 29 and April 4}}\n'''[[Commons:Data:Stay-at-home orders in the United States.map|Full map including municipalities]]''']]\n\nIn extreme instances, a number of cities and states have imposed lockdown measures which limit where people can travel, work and shop away from their homes:\n* California. The Governor has ordered everyone to stay at home except to get food, care for a relative or friend, obtain health care, or go to an \"essential job\". People working in critical infrastructure sectors may continue to go to their jobs, but should try to keep at least six feet apart from anyone else. Indoor restaurants, bars and nightclubs, entertainment venues, gyms and fitness studios are closed, although some restaurants can still provide take-out meals. Gas stations, pharmacies, grocery stores, convenience stores, banks and laundry services remain open.<ref name=WSJ-lockdowns/>\n* New York. Non-essential businesses must shut down their in-office personnel functions, with the exception of financial institutions, retailers, pharmacies, hospitals, news media, manufacturing plants and transportation companies, among others. Casinos, gyms, theaters, shopping malls, amusement parks and bowling alleys are to be closed. \"Non-essential gatherings\" of any size and for any reason are temporarily banned, and in public, people must keep at least six feet away from each other. Residents 70 and older and people with compromised immune systems or underlying illnesses must remain indoors (unless exercising outside), wear a mask in the company of others and prescreen visitors by taking their temperature.<ref name=WSJ-lockdowns/>\n\nSimilar restrictions to varying degree have been imposed in [[Illinois]], [[Texas]], [[Nevada]], [[New Jersey]] and [[Florida]], including the shutting down of hotels.<ref name=lockdowns-2>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/coronavirus-deaths-surpass-10-000-globally-11584698319?cx_testId=3&cx_testVariant=cx_2&cx_artPos=1#cxrecs_s \"Illinois, New York, California, Nevada Tighten Restrictions to Fight Coronavirus\"], ''Wall Street Journal'', March 20, 2020</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible\"\n!colspan=\"2\" |States with a lockdown order or advisory<ref name=\"nyt-mervosh-lu-states\">{{cite web |last1=Mervosh |first1=Sarah |last2=Lu |first2=Denise |title=See Which States and Cities Have Told Residents to Stay at Home |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/us/coronavirus-stay-at-home-order.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!State\n!Date enacted\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Arizona\n|March 30, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |California\n|March 19, 2020\n|-\t\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Colorado\t\n|March 26, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Connecticut\n|March 23, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Delaware\n|March 24, 2020\n|-\t\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Hawaii\t\n|March 25, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Idaho\n|March 25, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Illinois\n|March 21, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Indiana\n|March 24, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Kansas\n|March 30, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Kentucky{{efn|name=Advisory|Advisory order}}\n|March 26, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Louisiana\n|March 23, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Maryland\n|March 30, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Massachusetts{{efn|name=Advisory}}\n|March 24, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Michigan\n|March 24, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Minnesota\n|March 27, 2020\t\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Montana\n|March 28, 2020\t\n|-\t\n!style=\"text-align:left; |New Hampshire<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wmur.com/article/live-at-3-sununu-gives-update-on-covid-19/31941704#|title=Gov. Chris Sununu issues stay-at-home order for New Hampshire|author=Adam Sexton|work=WMUR|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\t\n|March 27, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |New Jersey\n|March 21, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |New Mexico\n|March 24, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |New York\n|March 22, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |North Carolina\n|March 30, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Ohio\n|March 23, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Oregon\n|March 23, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Vermont\t\n|March 25, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Virginia\n|March 30, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Washington\n|March 23, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |West Virginia\n|March 24, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Wisconsin\t\n|March 25, 2020\n|}\n\n===Educational impacts===\n\n{{see also|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on education}}\n[[File:Stevens Elementary School during COVID epidemic 05.jpg|thumb|left|Playground at a Seattle elementary school is closed due to the epidemic on March 25]]\n\n{{As of|2020|03|24|df=US}}, 124,000 public and private schools had closed nationwide, affecting at least 55 million students, with most schools in all 50 states, the District of Columbia, and all five inhabited territories closed statewide.<ref>{{cite web |title=Map: Coronavirus and School Closures |url=https://www.edweek.org/ew/section/multimedia/map-coronavirus-and-school-closures.html |website=Education Week |publisher=Editorial Projects in Education |access-date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> To ensure food-insecure students continued to receive lunches while schools were closed, many states and school districts arranged for \"grab-and-go\" lunch bags or used school bus routes to deliver meals to children.<ref>{{cite news|title=Schools Scramble to Feed Students After Coronavirus Closures|date=March 14, 2020|agency=Associated Press|work=U.S. News & World Report|location=Washington, D.C.|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/health-news/articles/2020-03-13/schools-scramble-to-feed-students-after-coronavirus-closures|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> To provide legal authority for such efforts, the [[U.S. Department of Agriculture]] waived several school lunch program requirements.<ref>{{cite website|title=H.R. 6201 Update\u2014USDA Issues Nationwide Child Nutrition Waivers|date=March 21, 2020|author=<!--no byline-->|website=News|publisher=School Nutrition Association|location=Arlington, Virginia|url=https://schoolnutrition.org/news-publications/news/2020/usda-issues-nationwide-child-nutrition-waivers/|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA large number of higher educational institutions canceled classes and closed dormitories in response to the outbreak, including all members of the [[Ivy League]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Murray |first1=Conor |title=Online classes, travel bans: How the Ivy League is responding to the coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.thedp.com/article/2020/03/penn-coronavirus-ivy-league-online-classes-travel |website=www.thedp.com |accessdate=29 March 2020 |language=en-us}}</ref> and many other public and private universities across the country.<ref>{{cite web |title=Columbia, Harvard, NYU, and other major US colleges and universities that have switched to remote classes and are telling students to move out of dorms to prevent the spread of the coronavirus |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/major-colleges-and-universities-going-remote-over-coronavirus-fears |website=Business Insider |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nDue to the disruption to the academic year caused by the COVID-19 pandemic, the [[United States Department of Education|U.S. Department of Education]] approved a waiver process, allowing states to opt-out of standardized testing required under the [[Every Student Succeeds Act]].<ref name=\"NPR-DOE\">{{cite news|title=Education Dept. Makes Changes To Standardized Tests, Student Loans Over Coronavirus|date=March 20, 2020|last=Nadworny|first=Elissa|work=Corona Virus Daily|publisher=National Public Radio|location=Washington, D.C.|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/20/818977484/education-dept-makes-changes-to-standardized-tests-student-loans-over-coronaviru|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> In addition, the [[College Board]] eliminated traditional face-to-face [[Advanced Placement exams]] in favor of an online exam that can be taken at home.<ref>{{cite web|title=AP Updates for Schools Impacted by Coronavirus|date=March 20, 2020|author=<!--no byline-->|work=AP Central|publisher=The College Board|location=New York City, New York|url=https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/about-ap/news-changes/coronavirus-update|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> The College Board also cancelled [[SAT]] testing in March and May in response to the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|title=SAT Coronavirus Updates|date=<!--no date-->|author=<!--no byline-->|website=College Board|url=https://pages.collegeboard.org/natural-disasters|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> Similarly, April [[ACT (test)|ACT exams]] were rescheduled for June 2020.<ref>{{cite web|title=ACT Reschedules April 2020 International ACT Test Date to June|website=ACT Newsroom & Blog|date=March 19, 2020|url=http://leadershipblog.act.org/2020/03/act-reschedules-april-2020.html|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Department of Education also authorized limited [[student loan]] relief, allowing borrowers to suspend payments for at least two months without accruing interest.<ref name=\"NPR-DOE\" />\n\n===Prison impacts===\n\n{{main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on prisons#United States}}\n\nAs COVID-19 was spreading to several prisons in the U.S., some states and local jurisdictions began to release prisoners considered vulnerable to the virus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51947802|title=US jails begin releasing prisoners amid pandemic|date=March 19, 2020|work=BBC News|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Xenophobia and racism===\n\n{{main|List of incidents of xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic#United States}}\n{{quote box| align = right| width = 25em| bgcolor = beige| quote = They're amazing people and the spreading of the virus is not their fault in any way shape or form. They're working closely with us to get rid of it{{nbsp}}... It's very important that we totally protect our Asian-American community in the United States and all around the world. | source = President Trump, March 23, 2020<ref name=\"DelaneyMarch24\"/>}}\nThere have been widespread [[List of incidents of xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic#United States|incidents of xenophobia and racism]] against [[Chinese Americans]] and other [[Asian Americans]].<ref name=\"NYT Racism\">{{cite news |last1=Tavernise |first1=Sabrina |last2=Oppel Jr |first2=Richard A. |title=Spit On, Yelled At, Attacked: Chinese-Americans Fear for Their Safety |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/23/us/chinese-coronavirus-racist-attacks.html |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> It had been reported that Asian Americans were purchasing firearms in response to the xenophobia arising from the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3076395/asian-americans-are-stocking-guns-protect-themselves|title=Asian-Americans stock up on guns and ammo during coronavirus pandemic|date=March 24, 2020|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The FBI issued an alert that [[neo-Nazi]] and [[white supremacist]] groups were encouraging members to, if they contract it, spread the virus via \"bodily fluids and personal interactions\" with [[Jews]] and police officers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/white-supremacists-encouraging-members-spread-coronavirus-cops-jews/story?id=69737522|title=White supremacists encouraging their members to spread coronavirus to cops, Jews, FBI says|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Media Matters for America]] accused [[Fox News Channel]] personalities and guests of racism for repeatedly using terms such as \"Chinese virus\" and \"Wuhan virus\" on-air.<ref>{{cite web|website=Media Matters|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/coronavirus-covid-19/fox-news-pushes-racist-and-xenophobic-language-coronavirus|title=Fox News pushes racist and xenophobic language for coronavirus|date=March 25, 2020|author=Bob Savillo}}</ref>\n\n===Event cancellations===\n\n{{See also|List of events affected by the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:Starbucks COVID-19 Response.jpg|thumb|right|On March 4, Starbucks announced that it will not fill reusable cups at its U.S. and Canadian stores during the ongoing COVID-19 outbreak.<ref>{{cite news|last=Williams|first=Rossann|url=https://stories.starbucks.com/stories/2020/managing-courageously-through-the-dynamics-of-covid-19/|title=Managing Through the Dynamics of COVID-19|date=March 4, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305115156/https://stories.starbucks.com/stories/2020/managing-courageously-through-the-dynamics-of-covid-19/|archive-date=March 5, 2020|agency=[[Starbucks]]}}</ref>]]\n\nAs \"[[social distancing]]\" entered the public lexicon, [[emergency management]] leaders encouraged the cancellation of large gatherings to slow the rate of infection.{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}} Technology conferences such as Apple Inc.'s [[Apple Worldwide Developers Conference|Worldwide Developers Conference]] (WWDC),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/13/apple-wwdc-moved-to-online-only-cancels-in-person-event.html|title=Apple moves WWDC developers conference online due to coronavirus|last=Leswing|first=Kif|date=March 13, 2020|publisher=CNBC|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> [[E3 2020]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2020/03/e3-2020-has-been-canceled/|title=It's official: E3 2020 has been canceled [Updated]|last=Machkovech|first=Sam|date=March 11, 2020|website=Ars Technica|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311022503/https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2020/03/e3-2020-has-been-canceled/|archive-date=March 11, 2020|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> [[Facebook F8]], [[Google I/O]] and Cloud Next,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/27/21156308/facebook-f8-developer-conference-cancelled-coronavirus-concern-covid-19|title=Facebook cancels F8 developer conference due to coronavirus concerns|last=Gartenberg|first=Chaim|date=February 27, 2020|website=The Verge|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311202715/https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/27/21156308/facebook-f8-developer-conference-cancelled-coronavirus-concern-covid-19|archive-date=March 11, 2020|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> and Microsoft's MVP Summit<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/microsoft-cancels-mvp-summit-due-to-covid-19-coronavirus-fears/|title=Microsoft cancels MVP Summit due to COVID-19 coronavirus fears|last=Foley|first=Mary Jo|publisher=ZDNet|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303080934/https://www.zdnet.com/article/microsoft-cancels-mvp-summit-due-to-covid-19-coronavirus-fears/|archive-date=March 3, 2020|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/2/21162185/google-microsoft-io-2020-build-tech-conference-coronavirus|title=Google and Microsoft just canceled two conferences ahead of their major ones|last=Statt|first=Nick|date=March 2, 2020|website=The Verge|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311202715/https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/2/21162185/google-microsoft-io-2020-build-tech-conference-coronavirus|archive-date=March 11, 2020|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> have been either cancelled or have replaced in-person events with [[internet streaming]] events.\n\nOn February 21, Verizon pulled out of an [[RSA Security|RSA]] conference, joining the ranks of AT&T Cybersecurity and IBM.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsaconference.com/novel-coronavirus-update|title=Novel Coronavirus Update|date=January 26, 2020|website=RSA Conference|access-date=February 29, 2020}}</ref> On February 29, the [[American Physical Society]] cancelled its annual March Meeting, scheduled for March 2\u20136 in [[Denver]], Colorado, even though many of the more than 11,000 physicist participants had already arrived and participated in the day's pre-conference events.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Castelvecchi|first1=Davide|date=March 2, 2020|title=Coronavirus fears cancel world's biggest physics meeting|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-00609-0|url-status=live|journal=Nature|doi=10.1038/d41586-020-00609-0|pmid=32203350|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302191008/https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-00609-0|archive-date=March 2, 2020|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> On March 6, the annual [[South by Southwest]] (SXSW) conference and festival scheduled to run from March 13 to 22 in [[Austin, Texas]], were cancelled following after the city government declared a \"local disaster\" and ordered conferences to shut down for the first time in 34 years.<ref name=\"us-covid-19-20200306-2020-event-update-city-of-austin-cancels-sxsw-march-events\">{{cite press release|date=March 6, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020|title=2020 Event Update: City of Austin Cancels SXSW March Events|agency=[[South by Southwest|SXSW]]|url=https://www.sxsw.com/2020-event-update/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306220834/https://www.sxsw.com/2020-event-update/|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"us-covid-19-20200306-sxsw-canceled-due-to-coronavirus-after-austin-declares-local-disaster\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/06/sxsw-cancelled-due-to-coronavirus.html|title=SXSW canceled due to coronavirus after Austin declares 'local disaster'|last=Graham|first=Megan|date=March 6, 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306220022/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/06/sxsw-cancelled-due-to-coronavirus.html|archive-date=March 6, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020}}</ref> The cancellation is not covered by insurance.<ref name=\"us-covid-19-sxsw-pledges-future-credit-if-you-bought-a-badge-this-year\">{{cite web|url=https://www.statesman.com/business/20200307/sxsw-pledges-future-credit-if-you-bought-badge-this-year|title=SXSW pledges future credit if you bought a badge this year|last1=Sechler|first1=Bob|date=March 7, 2020|work=[[The Austin American-Statesman]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308082915/https://www.statesman.com/business/20200307/sxsw-pledges-future-credit-if-you-bought-badge-this-year|archive-date=March 8, 2020|access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"us-covid-19-20200306-sxsw-cancellation-not-covered-by-insurance\">{{cite web|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/daily/news/2020-03-06/sxsw-cancellation-not-covered-by-insurance/|title=SXSW Cancellation Not Covered by Insurance; Communicable diseases, viruses, and pandemics not part of policy|last=Curtin|first=Kevin|date=March 6, 2020|work=[[The Austin Chronicle]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307070427/https://www.austinchronicle.com/daily/news/2020-03-06/sxsw-cancellation-not-covered-by-insurance/|archive-date=March 7, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020}}</ref> In 2019, 73,716 people attended the conferences and festivals, directly spending $200&nbsp;million and ultimately boosting the local economy by $356&nbsp;million, or four percent of the annual revenue of the region's hospitality and tourism economic sectors.<ref name=\"us-covid-19-20200307-loss-of-sxsw-gut-punch-for-some-austin-businesses\">{{cite web|url=https://www.statesman.com/business/20200307/loss-of-sxsw-gut-punch-for-some-austin-businesses|title=Loss of SXSW a gut punch for some Austin businesses|last1=Sechler|first1=Bob|last2=Hawkins|first2=Lori|date=March 7, 2020|work=[[Austin American-Statesman]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308063805/https://www.statesman.com/business/20200307/loss-of-sxsw-gut-punch-for-some-austin-businesses|archive-date=March 8, 2020|access-date=March 7, 2020|last3=Novak|first3=Shonda}}</ref><ref name=\"us-covid-19-20200306-austin-cancels-sxsw-over-coronavirus-declares-local-disaster\">{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/486371-austin-cancels-sxsw-over-coronavirus-declares-local-disaster|title=Austin cancels SXSW over coronavirus, declares 'local disaster'|last1=Seipel|first1=Brooke|date=March 6, 2020|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]], Washington, D.C.|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307155608/https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/486371-austin-cancels-sxsw-over-coronavirus-declares-local-disaster|archive-date=March 7, 2020|access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter the cancellations of the [[Ultra Music Festival]] in Miami and SXSW in Austin, speculation began to grow about the [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival|Coachella]] festival set to begin on April 10 in the desert in [[Indio, California]].<ref name=\"us-covid-19-petitions-for-and-against-cancelling-coachella-are-circulating-online\">{{cite web|url=https://www.desertsun.com/story/life/2020/03/06/coronavirus-update-petitions-and-against-cancelling-coachella-appear/4975706002/|title=Coronavirus update: petitions for and against cancelling Coachella are circulating online|last=Blueskye|first=Brian|date=March 6, 2020|work=[[The Desert Sun]], Palm Springs, Calif.|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308012351/https://www.desertsun.com/story/life/2020/03/06/coronavirus-update-petitions-and-against-cancelling-coachella-appear/4975706002/|archive-date=March 8, 2020|access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"us-covid-19-will-coronavirus-cancel-coachella-riverside-county-public-health-officer-says-not-yet\">{{cite web|url=https://www.desertsun.com/story/news/2020/03/05/coronavirus-cancel-coachella-county-official-says-not-yet/4958589002/|title=Will coronavirus cancel Coachella? Riverside County public health officer says not yet|last1=Atagi|first1=Colin|last2=Plevin|first2=Rebecca|date=March 5, 2020|work=[[The Desert Sun]], Palm Springs, Calif.|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308012446/https://www.desertsun.com/story/news/2020/03/05/coronavirus-cancel-coachella-county-official-says-not-yet/4958589002/|archive-date=March 8, 2020|access-date=March 8, 2020|last3=Daniels|first3=Melissa}}</ref> The annual festival, which has attracted some 125,000 people over two consecutive weekends, is insured only in the event of a ''[[force majeure]]'' cancellation such as one ordered by local or state government officials. Estimates on an insurance payout range from $150&nbsp;million to $200&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"us-covid-19-20200307-amid-growing-coronavirus-concerns-locals-are-torn-over-coachella-festival-coming-to-their-town\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2020-03-07/coachella-festival-coronavirus-cancellation-locals-indio-palm-springs|title=Amid growing coronavirus concerns, locals are torn over Coachella festival coming to their town|last1=Brown|first1=August|date=March 7, 2020|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|url-status=live|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308005709/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2020-03-07/coachella-festival-coronavirus-cancellation-locals-indio-palm-springs|archive-date=March 8, 2020|access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref> On March 10, event organizers announced the festival had been postponed to October.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Media===\n====Publishing====\n\nThe scale of the COVID-19 outbreak has prompted several major publishers to temporarily disable their [[paywall]]s on related articles, including [[Bloomberg News]], ''[[The Atlantic]]'', ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', and ''[[The Seattle Times]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jerde |first=Sara |date=March 12, 2020 |title=Major Publishers Take Down Paywalls for Coronavirus Coverage |url=https://www.adweek.com/digital/major-publishers-take-down-paywalls-for-coronavirus-coverage/ |work=[[AdWeek]] |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CJR\">{{cite news |last=Allsop |first=Jon |date=March 13, 2020 |title=How the coronavirus could hurt the news business |url=https://www.cjr.org/the_media_today/coronavirus_news_business_advertising.php |work=[[Columbia Journalism Review]] |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeveral [[Alternative newspaper|alt weekly]] newspapers in affected metropolitan areas, including ''[[The Stranger (newspaper)|The Stranger]]'' in Seattle and ''[[Austin Chronicle]]'', have announced layoffs and funding drives due to lost revenue. Public events and venues accounted for a majority of revenue for alt-weekly newspapers, which was disrupted by the cancellation of large public gatherings.<ref name=\"CJR\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Scire |first=Sarah |date=March 12, 2020 |title=\"This time is different\": In Seattle, social distancing forces The Stranger to make a coronavirus plea |url=https://www.niemanlab.org/2020/03/this-time-is-different-in-seattle-social-distancing-forces-the-stranger-to-make-a-coronavirus-plea/ |publisher=[[Nieman Foundation for Journalism]] |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Film====\n\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema}}\n\nMost U.S. cinema chains, where allowed to continue operating, reduced the [[seating capacity]] of each show time by half to minimize the risk of spreading the virus between patrons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/movie-theater-chains-limiting-salescoronavirus-1203534095/|title=Movie Theaters Cut Seating Capacity Over Coronavirus|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=March 13, 2020|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> Audience limits, as well as mandatory and voluntary closure of cinemas in some areas, led to a total North American box office sales the lowest since October 1998.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/vin-diesel-bloodshot-i-still-believe-the-hunt-weekend-box-office-coronavirus-1202882333/|title=Weekend Box Office Plunges To 22-Year Low At $55M+, Theater Closings Rise To 100+ Overnight As Coronavirus Fears Grip Nation\u2014Sunday Final|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=March 15, 2020|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 16, numerous theater chains temporarily closed their locations nationwide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/coronavirus-movie-theaters-shutdown-alamo-drafthouse-cineplex-odeon-amc-1202885115/|title=Coronavirus Theater Closures In U.S./Canada Hit 3K As Alamo Drafthouse & Others Go Dark: \"This News ... Is Devastating\"|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=March 17, 2020|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> A number of Hollywood film companies have suspended production and delayed the release of some films.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/feature/movie-productions-postponed-coronavirus-hollywood-films-1202882857/|title=Coronavirus: Movies That Have Halted Or Delayed Production Amid Outbreak|last=Hipes|first=Patrick|date=March 16, 2020|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/movies/story/2020-03-12/coronavirus-movies-cancelled-postponed|title=Here are all the movie releases that have been postponed due to coronavirus|date=March 17, 2020|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=March 16, 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n====Television====\n\n{{see also|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on television}}\n\nIn March, a number of studio-based [[talk show]]s and [[game show]]s announced plans to film behind closed doors with no audience.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/coronavirus-jeopardy-wheel-of-fortune-tape-without-live-audience-1203528383/|title=Coronavirus Concerns Prompt 'Jeopardy!', 'Wheel of Fortune' to Tape Without Live Audiences|last=Low|first=Elaine|date=March 10, 2020|website=Variety|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310144717/https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/coronavirus-jeopardy-wheel-of-fortune-tape-without-live-audience-1203528383/|archive-date=March 10, 2020|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> Some television networks and [[news channel]]s have adjusted their programming to incorporate coverage of the pandemic and adhere to CDC guidelines, including encouraging remote work and physical distancing on-air (including separation between on-air anchors and increased use of remote interviews).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/17/fox-and-friends-social-distancing-133619|title=The president's favorite morning show starts social distancing|last=Forgey|first=Quint|website=Politico|language=en|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/tv-news-coronavirus-coverage-today-cbs-news-1203535596/|title=From Big Debate to 'Today', Coronavirus Forces Quick Change for TV News|last=Steinberg|first=Brian|date=March 16, 2020|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/abc-news-coronavirus-amy-robach-strahan-sara-keke-1203536909/|title=ABC Will Suspend 'Strahan, Sara & Keke' in Favor of Coronavirus News Show|last=Steinberg|first=Brian|date=March 17, 2020|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nQuarantine and remote work efforts, as well as interest in updates on the pandemic, have resulted in a larger potential audience for television broadcasters, especially news channels. Nielsen estimated that by March 11 television usage had increased by 22% week-over-week. It was expected that [[streaming service]]s would see an increase in usage, while potential economic downturns associated with the pandemic could accelerate the market trend of [[cord cutting]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lee|first=Edmund|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/business/media/coronavirus-television-netflix.html|title=Glued to TV for Now, but When Programming Thins and Bills Mount ...|date=March 17, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 19, 2020|last2=Koblin|first2=John|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2020/03/tv-viewership-advertising-coronavirus-analysis-1202218603/|title=Analysts Warn TV Viewership Increases Won't Stop Financial Hit from Coronavirus|last=Hersko|first=Tyler|date=March 18, 2020|website=IndieWire|language=en|access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Draper|first=Kevin|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/16/sports/sports-television-coronavirus.html|title=When Coronavirus Turns Every Sports Channel Into ESPN Classic|date=March 16, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 19, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> [[WarnerMedia]] reported that [[HBO Now]] saw a spike in usage, and the most viewed titles included documentary ''Ebola: The Doctors' Story'' and the 2011 film ''[[Contagion (2011 film)|Contagion]]'' for their resonance with the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/hbo-now-usage-leaps-40-amid-coronavirus-crisis-warnermedia-posts-viewership-gains-with-titles-like-ebola-contagion-1202891495/|title=HBO Now Usage Leaps 40% Amid Coronavirus Crisis; WarnerMedia Posts Viewership Gains With Titles Like 'Ebola' & Contagion'|first=Denise|last=Petski|date=March 24, 2020|publisher=Deadline|accessdate=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n===Sports {{anchor|Impact on sports}}===\n\n{{main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\n[[File:Sacramento Kings game postponed, 2020-03-11.jpg|alt=A large screen announcing the game canceled|thumb|The NBA was the first major sports league to suspend operations, including clearing out this March 11 game between the [[New Orleans Pelicans]] and [[Sacramento Kings]].]]\n\nA suspension of games for various time periods were announced by almost all professional sports leagues in the United States on March 11 and 12, including the [[National Basketball Association]] (which had a player announced as having tested positive),<ref name=\"wsj-sportsshutdown\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/ncaa-medical-chief-says-testing-shortage-threatens-march-madness-11584030721|title=The Day Sports Shut Down|date=2020-03-12|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2020-03-28|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>[[National Hockey League]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/nhl/nhl-suspends-regular-season-due-coronavirus-concerns/|title=NHL suspends regular season due to coronavirus concerns|work=[[Sportsnet]]|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> [[Major League Baseball]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/sports/mlb/mets/2020/03/16/coronavirus-mlb-delays-season-indefinitely-amid-cdc-restrictions/5061192002/|title=MLB delays season indefinitely after CDC announces restrictions amid coronavirus fears|first=Justin|last=Toscano|website=North Jersey}}</ref> and [[Major League Soccer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/concacaf-champions-league/story/4073261/concacaf-champions-league-suspended-liga-mx-take-coronavirus-measures|title=CONCACAF, Liga MX take coronavirus measures|date=March 12, 2020|publisher=ESPN|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/12/major-league-soccer-suspends-season-for-30-days-amid-concern-over-coronavirus.html|title=Major League Soccer suspends season for 30 days amid concern over coronavirus|last=Kimball|first=Spencer|date=March 12, 2020|publisher=CNBC|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> [[College athletics]] competitions were similarly cancelled by schools, [[Athletic conference|conferences]] and the [[NCAA]]\u2014which cancelled all remaining championships for the academic year on March 12. This also resulted in the first-ever cancellation of the NCAA's popular [[NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|\"March Madness\" men's basketball tournament]] (which had been scheduled to begin the following week) in its 81-year history.<ref name=\"wsj-sportsshutdown\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/story/2020-03-12/march-madness-ncaa-tournament-canceled-coronavirus|title=No shining moments: NCAA basketball tournaments are canceled for the first time|date=March 13, 2020|website=Los Angeles Times|url-access=subscription|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-football/news/coronavirus-updates-ncaa-cancels-championship-competition-for-all-winter-and-spring-sports/|title=Coronavirus updates: NCAA cancels championship competition for all winter and spring sports|website=CBSSports.com|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 BNP Paribas Open|2020 Indian Wells Masters]] tennis tournaments were cancelled on March 10.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rothenberg|first=Ben|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/08/sports/coronavirus-indian-wells-canceled.html|title=Indian Wells Tennis Tournament Canceled Because of Coronavirus Outbreak|date=March 8, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 10, 2020|last2=Clarey|first2=Christopher|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The [[ATP Tour]] and [[WTA Tour]] have both suspended competition until late-April, which has also led to the cancellation of the [[Miami Open (tennis)|Miami Open]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/tennis/51841130|title=Coronavirus: ATP Tour shuts down for six weeks because of outbreak|date=March 12, 2020|work=BBC Sport|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> [[NASCAR]] on March 13 postponed the races at [[Atlanta Motor Speedway]] and announced on March 16 that it will postpone all race events until May 3.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nascar.com/news-media/2020/03/16/nascar-schedule-update-statement-race-coronavirus/|title=NASCAR statement: All race events through May 3 postponed|date=March 16, 2020|work=NASCAR.com|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref> The [[IndyCar Series]] similarly announced the cancellation of all races through the end of April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ibj.com/articles/indycar-series-canceling-all-races-before-month-of-may-in-indy|title=IndyCar series canceling all races before Month of May in Indy|website=Indianapolis Business Journal|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[PGA Tour]] played the first round of the [[2020 Players Championship]] on March 12, and said subsequent rounds and tournaments would be held without spectators,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/12/pga-tour-wont-allow-fans-for-foreseeable-future-due-to-coronavirus.html|title=PGA Tour won't allow fans for foreseeable future due to coronavirus|last=Golden|first=Jessica|date=March 12, 2020|publisher=CNBC|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> but later cancelled the rest of the tournament and subsequent events through early-May.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.golfdigest.com/story/here-are-all-the-golf-tournaments-that-have-been-canceled-or-postponed-due-to-the-coronavirus|title=Here are all the golf tournaments that have been canceled or postponed due to the coronavirus|last=Herrington|first=Ryan|website=Golf Digest|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/golf/story/_/id/28894497/pga-tour-cancels-players-championship-first-round|title=Players Championship scrapped after 1st round|date=March 13, 2020|publisher=ESPN|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> The [[LPGA Tour]] similarly cancelled all events through April.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/golf/story/_/id/28893923/lpga-reschedule-3-events-including-first-major-ana-inspiration|title=LPGA postpones 3 events, including first major|date=March 12, 2020|publisher=ESPN|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> Two [[Men's major golf championships|men's majors]], the Masters and PGA Championship, were postponed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/golf/story/_/id/28897249/augusta-national-announces-masters-postponed-played|title=Augusta announces Masters will be postponed|date=March 13, 2020|publisher=ESPN|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" />\n\n===Religious services===\n\n{{main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on religion}}\n[[File:COVID-19 NC church closure.jpg|thumb| ]]\n\nAmidst the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic, some American churches continue to operate their [[food bank|food pantries]] that are offering bags filled with meat and toilet paper rolls for needy families.<ref name=\"Dias2020\">{{cite web |last1=Dias |first1=Elizabeth |title=A Sunday Without Church: In Crisis, a Nation Asks, 'What Is Community?' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/15/us/churches-coronavirus-services.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=17 March 2020 |language=English |date=15 March 2020}}</ref> The [[National Cathedral]] of the United States, which belongs to [[the Episcopal Church]], donated more than five thousand [[NIOSH air filtration rating|N95 surgical masks]] to hospitals of [[Washington D.C.]], which were in shortage during the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic.<ref name=\"Gryboski2020\">{{cite web |last1=Gryboski |first1=Michael |title=National Cathedral donates 5,000 respirator masks to DC hospitals |url=https://www.christianpost.com/news/national-cathedral-donates-5000-respirator-masks-to-dc-hospitals.html |website=www.christianpost.com |publisher=[[The Christian Post]] |accessdate=26 March 2020 |language=English |date=26 March 2020}}</ref> Other churches, such as the [[Church of the Highlands]], an evangelical Christian megachurch, have offered free [[COVID-19 testing|COVID-19 tests]] in their parking lots.<ref name=\"RFBF2020\">{{cite web |title=Amazon Adds Jobs and Megachurch Helps with Covid-19 Testing |url=https://religiousfreedomandbusiness.org/2/post/2020/03/amazon-adds-jobs-and-megachurch-helps-with-covid-19-testing.html |publisher=Religious Freedom & Business Foundation |accessdate=19 March 2020 |language=English |date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome churches have suspended services, others have moved to radio, television and online services, while still others have offered drive-in services.<ref>{{cite web |title=Westerville church offering 'drive in' service |url=https://www.10tv.com/article/westerville-church-offering-drive-service-2020-mar |publisher=[[WBNS-TV]] |accessdate=22 March 2020 |language=English |date=22 March 2020}}</ref> Some state orders against large gatherings, such as in Ohio and New York, specifically exempt religious organizations.<ref>{{cite web|website=Newsweek|title=U.S. CHURCHES HOLD PUBLIC SUNDAY SERVICES DESPITE CORONAVIRUS OUTBREAK: 'THIS IS DANGEROUS' |date=March 23, 2020|author=Jason Murdock|url=https://www.newsweek.com/church-sunday-service-open-despite-coronavirus-covid19-health-advice-social-distancing-1493756}} [https://www.citybeat.com/news/blog/21124035/one-of-greater-cincinnatis-largest-churches-continues-services-despite-coronavirus One of Greater Cincinnati's Largest Churches Continues Services Despite Coronavirus] City Beat (Cincinnati), March 24, 2020</ref> Colorado Springs Fellowship Church insists it has a constitutional right to defy a state closure order.<ref>[https://krdo.com/news/2020/03/24/colorado-springs-church-says-it-has-constitutional-right-to-open-defying-state-health-order/ Colorado Springs church says it has Constitutional right to open, defying state health order] By Chelsea Brentzel, KRDO, March 24, 2020</ref> Evangelical college [[Liberty University]] of Lynchburg, Virginia, moved its classes online but called its 5,000 back to campus despite Governor [[Ralph Northam |Ralph Northam's]] (D) order to close all non-essential businesses.<ref>[https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/489212-liberty-university-welcomes-back-students-amid-covid-19-outbreak?fbclid=IwAR3n2vjm37_qmm97yyvEzyllibSINsUTRwtB083ZDJ5zuUbNKZFSXfdFb-Y Liberty University welcomes back students despite coronavirus] BY MARTY JOHNSON, The Hill, March 24, 2020</ref> Rev. Rodney Howard-Browne of the River at Tampa Bay Church in Florida was arrested and fined on March 30 for violating coronavirus-related bans on large gatherings. He had encouraged crowds as large as 500 over the weekend and argued that churches should get exemptions as essential services.<ref>{{cite web|website=boston.com/The Washington Post|title=Florida sheriff charges megapastor who kept church open, said closings are for 'pansies'|date=March 30, 2020|author=Michelle Boorstein|accessdate=March 30, 2020 |url=https://www.boston.com/news/national-news-2/2020/03/30/florida-sheriff-charges-megapastor-who-kept-church-open-said-closings-are-for-pansies}}</ref>\n\nBy March 20, every [[Catholic Church in the United States|Roman Catholic]] diocese in the United States had suspended the public celebration of Mass and [[Dispensation (canon law)|dispense]]d with the obligation to attend [[Mass (liturgy)|Mass]] on the [[Lord's Day]], as had the [[Personal Ordinariate of the Chair of Saint Peter]]. The [[Ukrainian Greek Catholic Church]] in the United States also suspended public Divine Liturgies.<ref>{{cite news|title=Do we have Mass? Coronavirus closures and dispensations in US dioceses|publisher=[[Catholic News Agency]]|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020|url=https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/do-we-have-mass-coronavirus-closures-and-dispensations-in-us-dioceses-96801}}</ref><ref>{{cite letter|title=Suspension of public Masses|first=John Francis|last=Doerfler|authorlink=John Francis Doerfler|recipient=Brothers and Sisters in Christ|publisher=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Marquette]]|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020 |url=https://dioceseofmarquette.org/images/files/Communications/03-17-20_SuspensionofpublicMasses.pdf|format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite letter|title=Decree\u2014suspending liturgical services & other activities|first=Curtis J.|last=Guillory|authorlink=Curtis J. Guillory|recipient=Sisters and Brothers in Christ|publisher=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Beaumont]]|date=March 18, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020|url=https://www.dioceseofbmt.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Decree-3-18-2020-English.pdf|format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite letter|title=Public Mass suspended|first=Peter F.|last=Christensen|authorlink=Peter F. Christensen|recipient=the Catholic Faithful of the Diocese of Boise|publisher=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Boise]]|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020 |url=https://www.catholicidaho.org/media/1/sUS%20mAS%20E%26S.pdf|format=PDF}} {{cite letter|title=Decree for Protocols Regarding Coronavirus-19 COVID-19|first=Patrick|last=Zurek|authorlink=Patrick Zurek|publisher=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Amarillo]]|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020|url=https://www.amarillodiocese.org/protocols-regarding-coronavirus-english}}</ref><ref>{{cite letter|title=Instruction regarding Protocols in Response to the Presence of COVID-19 in the Diocese of El Paso|first=Mark J.|last=Seitz|authorlink=Mark J. Seitz|publisher=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of El Paso]]|date=March 18, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020|url=https://www.elpasodiocese.org/bishops-letter-for-covid-19.html}} {{cite web|title=Coronavirus Precautions|publisher=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Fort Worth]]|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020|url=https://fwdioc.org/coronavirus-precautions|quote=The circumstances current in our community are such that attendance at Mass borders on an impossibility and thus there is no obligation to attend.}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March 2020, Bishop Elaine JW Stanovsky of the Pacific Northwest Annual Conference of the [[United Methodist Church]] issued a statement that would be updated no later than the start of [[Holy Week]], which directed \"the local churches of any size and other ministries in the states of Alaska, Idaho, Oregon and Washington to suspend in-person worship and other gatherings of more than 10 people for the next two weeks\".<ref name=\"Bloom2020\">{{cite web |last1=Bloom |first1=Linda |title=Churches adapting to COVID-19 restrictions |url=https://www.umnews.org/en/news/churches-adapting-to-covid-19-restrictions |publisher=United Methodist News Service |accessdate=17 March 2020 |language=English |date=13 March 2020}}</ref> Many parts of the [[Methodist Church]]es, which uphold [[Sunday Sabbatarianism|Sunday Sabbatarian]] teaching, have transitioned  their church services online; ninety percent of the parishes within the Pacific Northwest Annual Conference of the United Methodist Church, for example, are now offering worship via internet livestream.<ref name=\"Bloom2020\"/>\n\nOn March 24, President Trump said, in regard to Easter (April 12), \"Wouldn't it be great to have all the churches full? You'll have packed churches all over our country. I think it'll be a beautiful time.\" As of March 25, many churches were not prepared to risk reopening, and most churches were predicted to remain closed on Easter.<ref>{{cite web|website=Washington Examiner|title=Churches won't be 'packed' for Easter despite Trump call|author=Nicholas Rowan|date=March 25, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/churches-wont-be-packed-for-easter-despite-trump-call}}</ref>\n\n==Public response==\n\nOpinion polling showed a significant partisan divide regarding the outbreak.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/15/21180506/coronavirus-poll-democrats-republicans-trump|title=A new poll shows a startling partisan divide on the dangers of the coronavirus|first=Zeeshan|last=Aleem|date=March 15, 2020|website=Vox}}</ref> NPR, PBS NewsHour and Marist found in their mid-March survey that 76% of Democrats viewed COVID-19 as \"a real threat\", while only 40% of Republicans agreed; the previous month's figures for Democrats and Republicans were 70% and 72% respectively.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Allyn |first1=Bobby |last2=Sprunt |first2=Barbara |title=Poll: As Coronavirus Spreads, Fewer Americans See Pandemic As A Real Threat |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/17/816501871/poll-as-coronavirus-spreads-fewer-americans-see-pandemic-as-a-real-threat |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=[[NPR]] |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> A mid-March poll conducted by NBC News and ''The Wall Street Journal'' found that 60% of Democrats were concerned someone in their family might contract the virus, while 40% of Republicans expressed concern. Nearly 80% of Democrats believed the worst was yet to come, whereas 40% of Republicans thought so. About 56% of Democrats believed their lives would change in a major way due to the outbreak, compared to 26% for Republicans.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/meet-the-press/sixty-percent-believe-worst-yet-come-u-s-coronavirus-pandemic-n1159106 |title=Sixty percent believe worst is yet to come for the U.S. in coronavirus pandemic; Public attitudes about the coronavirus response are split along partisan lines in a new NBC News/Wall Street Journal poll |website=NBC News |author=Mark Murray |date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> A mid-March poll by the [[Kaiser Family Foundation]] found that 83% of Democrats had taken certain precautions against the virus, compared to 53% of Republicans. The poll found that President Trump was the least-trusted source of information about the outbreak, at 46% overall, although 88% of Republicans expressed trust in the president, second only to their trust in the CDC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/business/2020/03/democrats-republicans-coronavirus-trump.html|title=Democrats Are Being Much, Much More Careful About the Coronavirus Than Republicans|first=Jordan|last=Weissmann|date=March 17, 2020|website=[[Slate.com]]}}</ref>\n\n==Background and preparations==\n\nThe United States has experienced pandemics and epidemics throughout its history, including the 1918 [[Spanish flu]], the 1957 [[Influenza A virus subtype H2N2#Asian flu|Asian flu]], and the 1968 [[Hong Kong flu]] pandemics.<ref name=\"abc7\">{{cite news |last1=Miguel |first1=Ken |title=Here's a look at some of history's worst pandemics that have killed millions |url=https://abc7news.com/5974174/ |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |publisher=ABC 7 News |date=February 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lileks |first1=James |title=How the news media played down the pandemics of yore, from Spanish flu to Swine flu |url=http://www.startribune.com/how-the-news-media-played-down-the-pandemics-of-yore-from-spanish-flu-to-swine-flu/568899732/?refresh=true |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |publisher=Star Tribune |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Brown |first1=Jeremy |title=The Coronavirus Is No 1918 Pandemic |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/03/were-not-facing-second-spanish-flu/607354/ |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |publisher=[[The Atlantic]] |date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> In the most recent pandemic prior to COVID-19, the [[2009 flu pandemic|2009 H1N1 swine flu]] took the lives of more than 12,000 Americans and hospitalized another 200,000.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shrestha|first=Sundar S.|last2=Swerdlow|first2=David L.|last3=Borse|first3=Rebekah H.|last4=Prabhu|first4=Vimalanand S.|last5=Finelli|first5=Lyn|last6=Atkins|first6=Charisma Y.|last7=Owusu-Edusei|first7=Kwame|last8=Bell|first8=Beth|last9=Mead|first9=Paul S.|last10=Biggerstaff|first10=Matthew|last11=Brammer|first11=Lynnette|date=January 1, 2011|title=Estimating the burden of 2009 pandemic influenza A (H1N1) in the United States (April 2009 \u2013 April 2010)|journal=Clinical Infectious Diseases: An Official Publication of the Infectious Diseases Society of America|volume=52 Suppl 1|pages=S75\u201382|doi=10.1093/cid/ciq012|issn=1537-6591|pmid=21342903}}</ref><ref name=briefing /><ref name=\"abc7\" /> Because of this pandemic and the 2014 [[Western African Ebola virus epidemic|Ebola epidemic]], which saw only a small number of Americans infected,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lupkin |first1=Sydney |title=Ebola in America: Timeline of the Deadly Virus |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Health/ebola-america-timeline/story?id=26159719 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |publisher=ABC News |date=November 17, 2014}}</ref> the [[Obama Administration]] increased planning and analysis that focused on deficiencies in the government's response to outbreaks.<ref name=briefing /> In 2017, outgoing Obama administration officials briefed incoming Trump administration officials on how to respond to pandemics by using simulated scenarios, although by the time of the COVID-19 outbreak in the U.S., around {{nowrap|two-thirds}} of Trump administration officials at the briefing had left the administration.<ref name=briefing>{{cite news |last1=Toosi |first1=Nahal |last2=Lippman |first2=Daniel |last3=Diamond |first3=Dan |title=Before Trump's inauguration, a warning: 'The worst influenza pandemic since 1918' |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/16/trump-inauguration-warning-scenario-pandemic-132797 |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=[[Politico]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United States Intelligence Community]], in its annual worldwide threat assessment reports of 2017 and 2018, stated new types of microbes that are \"easily transmissible between humans\" remained \"a major threat\". Similarly, for the 2019 worldwide threat assessment, the U.S. intelligence agencies warned that \"the United States and the world will remain vulnerable to the next flu pandemic or large-scale outbreak of a contagious disease that could lead to massive rates of death and disability, severely affect the world economy, strain international resources, and increase calls on the United States for support.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Reider |first1=Rem |title=Contrary to Trump's Claim, A Pandemic Was Widely Expected at Some Point |url=https://www.factcheck.org/2020/03/contrary-to-trumps-claim-a-pandemic-was-widely-expected-at-some-point/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=[[Factcheck.org]] |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Dilanian |first1=Ken |title=U.S. intel agencies warned of rising risk of outbreak like coronavirus |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/u-s-intel-agencies-warned-rising-risk-outbreak-coronavirus-n1144891 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=[[NBC News]] |date=February 29, 2020}}</ref>\n[[File:Alex Azar declares PHED for Coronavirus.jpg|thumb|[[Alex Azar]] signing a public health emergency declaration]]\n\nCiting lessons learned from the swine flu pandemic, Ebola outbreak, and the [[2001 anthrax attacks]], President Trump released a [[National Biodefense Strategy]] on September 18, 2018 in response to a Congressional directive.<ref name=\"statement\">{{cite web |last1=Trump |first1=Donald |title=Statement from the President on the National Biodefense Strategy and National Security Presidential Memorandum |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/statement-president-national-biodefense-strategy-national-security-presidential-memorandum/ |publisher=The White House |accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"UPI\">{{cite news |last1=Brokaw |first1=Sommer |title=Trump signs presidential memo on national biodefense |url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/US/2018/09/18/Trump-signs-presidential-memo-on-national-biodefense/2071537290820/ |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |agency=UPI |date=September 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://apnews.com/4c21af485a7d4ccebb22f7316b55d014/White-House-sets-'new-direction'-in-biodefense-strategy|title=White House Sets 'New Direction' in Biodefense Strategy|last=|first=|date=September 18, 2018|agency=Associated Press|access-date=September 28, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref name=BartholomewOmberg>Rachel Bartholomew & Kristin Omberg, [https://thebulletin.org/2019/01/making-sense-of-the-2018-national-biodefense-strategy/ Making sense of the 2018 National Biodefense Strategy], ''Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists'' (January 18, 2019).</ref> According to Trump, the new strategy was designed to strengthen the nation's defenses against disease outbreaks and bioterrorism and to make responses to them more efficient and better coordinated.<ref name=\"statement\" /><ref name=\"UPI\" /> Concurrently, he released a National Security Presidential Memorandum that appointed the Secretary of HHS [[Alex Azar]] to oversee implementation of the government's new biodefense strategy and directed [[National Security Advisor (United States)|National Security Advisor]] [[John Bolton]] to assist in reviewing and improving the nation's biodefenses.<ref name=\"Owermohle\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/09/18/trump-hhs-biodefense-827973|title=Trump puts HHS in charge of defense against biological threats|last=Owermohle|first=Sarah|website=Politico|access-date=December 31, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Memo\">{{cite web |last1=Trump |first1=Donald |title=Presidential Memorandum on the Support for National Biodefense |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/presidential-actions/presidential-memorandum-support-national-biodefense/ |publisher=The White House |accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"statement\" /> At a time when multiple agencies and departments shared responsibility for biodefense,<ref name=BartholomewOmberg /> Bolton and Azar claimed this centralization of primary authority for biodefense in the HHS would provide greater accountability.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Watson |first1=Kathryn |title=Trump administration outlines new biodefense approach |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trump-administration-rolling-out-new-biodefense-strategy/ |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |publisher=CBS |date=September 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Bolton reorganized the executive branch's [[United States National Security Council]], largely merging the group responsible for global [[health security]] and [[biodefense]] into a bigger group responsible for [[counter-proliferation]] and biodefense. Along with the reorganization, the leader of the global health security and biodefense group, Rear Admiral [[Timothy Ziemer]], left to join another federal agency, while [[Tim Morrison (presidential advisor)|Tim Morrison]] became the leader of the combined group.<ref name=KellyMarch20>{{cite news |last1=Kessler |first1=Glenn |last2=Kelly |first2=Meg |title=Was the White House office for global pandemics eliminated? |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/20/was-white-house-office-global-pandemics-eliminated |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/ce014d94b64e98b7203b873e56f80e9a|title=Trump disbanded NSC pandemic unit that experts had praised|author-last=Riechmann|author-first=Deb|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=March 14, 2020|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> Also in 2018, [[Homeland Security Advisor]] [[Tom Bossert]] left the administration; reportedly at Bolton's request. Bossert had helped to create the Trump administration's biodefense plans, and it was his responsibility to coordinate the government's response in the event of a biological crisis.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Robertson |first1=Lori |last2=McDonald |first2=Jessica |last3=Farley |first3=Robert |title=Democrats' Misleading Coronavirus Claims |url=https://www.factcheck.org/2020/03/democrats-misleading-coronavirus-claims/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=March 3, 2020 |work=[[Factcheck.org]]}}</ref> Bossert's successor, [[Doug Fears]], and Fears' successor [[Peter J. Brown]], took over the biodefense responsibilities of the DHS. ''[[Bloomberg News]]'' reported in January 2020 that biodefense was by then a \"less prominent\" part of the Homeland Security Advisor's responsibilities.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jacobs |first1=Jennifer |last2=Dlouhy |first2=Jennifer A. |title=Trump Homeland Security Adviser to Leave Soon, Sources Say |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-04-30/trump-s-homeland-security-adviser-fears-is-said-to-leave-soon |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work =[[Bloomberg News]] |date=April 30, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Jacobs |first1=Jennifer |title=White House Homeland Security Aide Likely to Be Reassigned |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-19/white-house-homeland-security-adviser-being-shifted-out-of-job |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=January 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn other departures, [[Luciana Borio]], the National Security Council director for medical and biodefense preparedness, left her post in March 2019. ''[[The Washington Post]]'' reported in March 2020 that the White House would not confirm the identity of Borio's replacement.<ref name=KellyMarch20/> Meanwhile, in July 2019, Linda Quick, a U.S. CDC expert working within the [[Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention]], left her post without a replacement, as her position would have been eliminated in September 2019 due to the [[China\u2013United States trade war]]. [[Reuters]] reported Quick's departure in March 2020; her role was training Chinese field epidemiologists to respond to disease outbreaks at their hotbeds; the post had existed since 2007 or earlier.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Marisa |title=Exclusive: U.S. axed CDC expert job in China months before virus outbreak |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-china-cdc-exclusiv/exclusive-u-s-axed-cdc-expert-job-in-china-months-before-virus-outbreak-idUSKBN21910S |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Reuters]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Trump administration from January to August 2019 simulated a series of pandemic outbreaks from China and found that the U.S. government response was \"underfunded, underprepared, and uncoordinated\", with the \"not to be disclosed\" draft report detailing repeated cases of \"confusion\" during the exercises. A briefing was given to the [[United States Congress]] in December 2019 of some of the findings from the exercise, including the conclusion that the U.S. could not speedily manufacture certain medical supplies to cope with demand, because many of these items were imported. In response to the problems illustrated in the simulation, Trump issued an executive order to make flu vaccines more readily available and of higher quality, and he provided additional funds for the pandemic threats program in the HHS.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sanger|first=David E.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/19/us/politics/trump-coronavirus-outbreak.html|title=Before Virus Outbreak, a Cascade of Warnings Went Unheeded|date=March 19, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 20, 2020|last2=Lipton|first2=Eric|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Sullivan|first3=Eileen|last4=Crowley|first4=Michael}}</ref>\n\nDespite all these activities, [[National Geographic]] reported that as of March 3, 2020, the \"U.S. has only a fraction of the medical supplies it needs to combat coronavirus.\" An additional 300 million N95 respirators (face masks) and surgical face masks could be required to protect health workers. However, in Senate testimony, U.S. HHS Secretary [[Alex Azar]] said \"the [[Strategic National Stockpile]] has just 30 million surgical masks and 12 million respirators in reserve.\" HHS said it intends to purchase as many as half a ''b''illion respirators and surgical face masks over the next year and a half. A previous 2015 CDC study found that seven billion N95 respirators might be necessary to handle a \"severe respiratory outbreak [such as COVID-19]\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Akpan |first1=Nsikan |title=U.S. has only a fraction of the medical supplies it needs to combat coronavirus.|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/science/2020/03/us-america-has-fraction-medical-supplies-it-needs-to-combat-coronavirus/? |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[National Geographic]] |date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> The ''New York Times'' reported on March 18 that about 170,000 [[ventilators]] were in the U.S., versus an [[American Hospital Association]] estimate that 960,000 people may need them during the pandemic. The shortage of ventilators is one reason why slowing the spread of the virus is so important. Ramping up production is challenging due to global supply chains and the complexity of the devices, with major U.S. hospitals having trouble finding more.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kliff |first1=Sarah |title=There Aren't Enough Ventilators to Cope With the Coronavirus|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/18/business/coronavirus-ventilator-shortage.html|accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[New York Times]]|date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> ''Bloomberg News'' reported on March 23 that: \"NY Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] said the state, which has about 5,000 to 6,000 ventilators, might need 30,000 of them.\" China is significantly increasing ventilator production to assist other countries, with plans to supply about 14,000 non-invasive ventilators in April. The U.S. government has also called on U.S. manufacturers to assist.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hong |first1=Jishan |title=China's Factories Work 24/7 to Build Ventilators for Milan, New York|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-23/china-s-factories-work-24-7-to-build-ventilators-for-milan-ny? |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]|date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n\n{{gallery\n| File:COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in the United States (Density).svg|Map of states and territories in the U.S. with number of confirmed cases ({{As of|2020|03|29|lc=y|df=US}})\n{{legend|#FFDDCC|<500 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FFAAAA|500\u2013999 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FF7777|1,000\u20131,999 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FF0000|2,000\u20134,999 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#BB0000|5,000\u201350,000 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#500000|>50,000 confirmed}}\n| File:COVID-19 Pandemic Deaths in the United States (Density).svg|Map of states and territories in the U.S. with number of confirmed deaths ({{As of|2020|3|24|lc=y|df=US}})\n{{legend|#FFDDCC|1\u20133 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FFAAAA|4\u20136 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FF7777|7\u20139 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FF0000|10\u201349 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#BB0000|50\u2013250 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#500000|>250 confirmed}}\n| File:COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in the United States by counties (Confirmed).svg|Confirmed COVID-19 cases by county ({{As of|2020|03|27|lc=y|df=US}})\n| File:Lab-specimens-tested.jpg|Number of tests done per day in the United States<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/testing-in-us.html |website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |accessdate=March 10, 2020 |date=February 11, 2020}}</ref>{{br}}\u00a7 Data during this period are pending.\n| File:CoViD-19 US.svg|Number of cases (blue) and number of deaths (red) on a [[logarithmic scale]]\n}}\n\nThe following numbers are based on CDC data. However, CDC data is incomplete. In most U.S. locations, testing for some time was performed only on symptomatic people with a history of travel to Wuhan or with close contact to such people.<ref name=\"Madrigal\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/925233|title=Persons Evaluated for 2019 Novel Coronavirus\u2014US, Jan 2020|website=Medscape|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/new-york-man-denied-coronavirus-test-japan-trip-fever-cough-2020-3|title=A New York City man wasn't tested for the coronavirus even though he had symptoms and had gone to Japan. It highlights the troublingly limited scope of US testing.|first=Morgan|last=McFall-Johnsen|website=Business Insider|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> A quarantined nurse in California, showing symptoms of COVID-19 but without a travel history, said she was denied testing by the CDC in early March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2020/03/08/u-s-response-to-the-covid-19-coronavirus-moves-from-containment-to-mitigation|title=US response to the COVID-19 coronavirus moves from 'containment' to 'mitigation'|date=March 8, 2020|first=Jonathan|last=Shieber|work=TechCrunch}}</ref> CDC testing protocols did not include non-travelling patients with no known contact with China until February 28.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/27/health/us-cases-coronavirus-community-transmission/index.html|title=The CDC has changed its criteria for testing patients for coronavirus after the first case of unknown origin was confirmed|first1=Sarah |last1=Moon |first2=Holly |last2=Yan |first3=Jen |last3=Christensen |first4=Christina|last4=Maxouris|publisher=CNN|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe original CDC-developed tests sent out on February{{nbsp}}5 turned out to be faulty.<ref name=\"factcheck.org\">{{cite web|url=https://www.factcheck.org/2020/03/trumps-misplaced-blame-on-obama-for-coronavirus-tests/|title=Trump's Misplaced Blame on Obama for Coronavirus Tests|first=Jessica|last=McDonald|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> On February 29, the FDA announced that labs would be allowed to do their own in-house testing immediately, independently of CDC testing, as long as they complete an emergency use authorization (EUA) within 15 days.<ref name=\"factcheck.org\"/> In Washington, state regulators at one point told health care workers to stop testing previously collected samples from an existing non-COVID19 flu study.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/10/world/coronavirus-news.html|title=U.S. Cases of Coronavirus Surpass 1,000; British Health Minister Is Infected|date=March 10, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 18, the CDC reported that 37,824 specimens had been tested for COVID-19, 4,484 of which were tested by CDC labs, and 33,340 tested by U.S. public health labs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/cases-updates/testing-in-us.html|title=Testing in the U.S.|last=|first=|date=March 16, 2020|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316204847/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/cases-updates/testing-in-us.html|archive-date=March 16, 2020|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation estimates a peak in deaths per day by April 15, with a total of about 80,000 deaths in the United States due to coronavirus by August.<ref>{{cite web|website=The Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation (IHME)|url=https://covid19.healthdata.org/projections|title=COVID-19 Projections|accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===CDC reported U.S. totals===\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States medical cases chart}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Cases in the United States per the CDC<ref>{{cite web |title=Cases in the US |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/cases-updates/cases-in-us.html |website=CDC.gov |publisher=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref><br>As of March 30, 2020\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"| Cases in the United States reported to CDC\n|-\n|Travel-related || style=\"text-align:right\"|886\n|-\n|Close contact|| style=\"text-align:right\" |2,351\n|-\n|Under investigation ||style=\"text-align:right\" |137,667\n|-\n!Total cases !!style=\"text-align:right\" |140,904\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\"|\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Cases among persons repatriated to the United States\n|-\n|Wuhan, China||style=\"text-align:right\"|3\n|-\n| Cruise ship [[Diamond Princess outbreak|''Diamond Princess'']] || style=\"text-align:right\" |46\n|-\n